<FIRST>u a AM-AzoresCrash-Plane 3rdLd-Writethru a0811 02-08 0717</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Azores Crash-Plane, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0811,0729</SECOND>
<HEAD>Plane, Owned By Tennessee Company, Had </HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Azores Crash, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 5th graf, `As for...' with two grafs to expand on FAA reaction
to list of service problems.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SMYRNA, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 20-year-old jetliner that crashed in the
Azores on Wednesday had not been subjected to a high number of
takeoff and landings but had several problems requiring repairs in
recent years, officials said.
   The craft was one of two Boeing 707s owned by Independent Air
Corp. of Smyrna, said A.L. Pittman, Independent president. It had
12,500 cycles, or takeoffs and landings, and less than 50,000 hours
in the air.
   Jack Barker, spokesman for the Federal Aviation Administration in
Atlanta, agreed that the figures cited by Pittman were not excessive.
   ``If properly maintained, there should not be a problem because
of hours or number of cycles. Other aircraft involved in the news
have had as much as 50,000 cycles, a great many more.''
   Asked Wednesday night about the plane's repair record, Barker
said he had not seen the service difficulty reports filed with the
FAA, but that the faults found would not be considered a problem,
``not if they've been repaired.''
   ``The important thing is that they're fixed properly,'' he said.
   The charter plane crashed on approach to Santa Maria Airport in
the Azores, killing the 137 Italian tourists who were passengers and
an American crew of seven. The flight was headed from Bergamo,
Italy, to the Dominican Republic, and would have continued without
passengers to Jamaica.
   In the Azores, an island chain west of Portugal, airport
dispatcher Gualder Cordero said there were no radio messages or
warnings before the plane went down.
   Pittman said one of the company's two jets lost oil pressure Jan.
21 as it flew into Denver and required repairs before resuming eight
to 10 hours later. He did not know if the same jet crashed
Wednesday, and said of the oil problem, ``Don't look for anything in
that.''
   Barker said Independent Air Corp. was fined $18,000 in 1984, but
he could offer no further information about that FAA enforcement
action before Thursday.
   Records at the FAA's Mike Monroney Aeronautical Center in
Oklahoma City show seven service difficulty reports on the plane
over the past six years, spokeswoman Bobbie Mardis said.
   They included two reports in January 1983: an engine shutdown due
to turbine failure and failure of a switch in the main landing gear.
   Filings in July 1987 showed problems occurred with an electrical
transformer powering a lavatory heater, altimeter and air-speed
monitor problems caused a return to Atlanta for replacement of a
static line, a left inboard keel beam extension fitting was found
cracked on the fuselage, and the right fitting was found broken.
   The seventh report, filed in December, indicated that during
inspection, a mechanic noticed a crack in the No. 2 engine first
stage fan duct. Further inspection revealed a {-inch crack, the
report said, adding that the duct was replaced and the plane was
returned to service.
   ``I'm not aware (of the service difficulty reports) so I'd have
to say they are fairly minor,'' Independent co-owner Orien Dickerson
said. ``We have the same stringent monitoring program as Delta,
American and all the major airlines. Every time you go into a major
maintenance check you'll find some amount of corrosion.''
   Pittman identified six of the victims as: Leon Daugherty, 41, of
Nashville, the captain; Sammy Adcock, 36, Nashville, first officer;
Jorge Gonzalez, 34, Rex, Ga., the flight enginner; and flight
attendants Yvette Murray, 26, of Marietta, Ga., Angela Urban, 24,
West Palm Beach, Fla., Helen Ziegler, 45, Warner Robins, Ga., and
Sabrina Cromarty, whose age and hometown he did not know.
   The remaining flight attendant, a woman, was not identified
pending notification of relatives.
   Independent Air has 100 employees, 65 of whom are crew members,
Pittman said.
   ``Generally everybody knows everybody else in a company this
size,'' he said. ``It's like losing a member of your family. We are
deeply saddened. There have been some tears here today in shock.''
   The Boeing 707-320B, which could seat 186 passengers, was 152
feet, 11 inches long with a wingspan of 145 feet, 9 inches. The
aircraft was first introduced by Boeing in 1961.
</TEXT>
