<FIRST>r i AM-Philippines-Marcos     02-08 0568</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Philippines-Marcos,0587</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: U.S. Warns Philippines On Deals With Marcos</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Justice Department said it
would not help prosecute Ferdinand Marcos and would seize his
property if Manila agrees to an unacceptable deal for his return
home, it was reported Wednesday.
   Teodoro Locsin Jr., publisher of the Philippine Daily Globe and
President Corazon Aquino's speechwriter, said the warning was
relayed to Mateo Caparas, chairman of the Presidential Commission on
Good Government.
   ``The U.S. Attorney General has made it clear: `Total discretion
cuts both ways. If Philippine officials have total discretion to
undo years of American efforts to secure justice for the Filipino
people, U.S. officials have equally total discretion to make
Filipinos pay for tolerating such officials,''' Locsin said.
   Caparas arrived in the United States last week, supposedly to
determine whether the ousted president is prepared to negotiate in
order to come home from exile in Hawaii.
   The Philippine government says Marcos and his associates
embezzled up to $10 billion. President Corazon Aquino has said the
government will not discuss his return until he gives back the money.
   Caparas' trip to the United States, confirmed Wednesday by Mrs.
Aquino, raised speculation that the Aquino administration was
prepared to negotiate a deal. Aquino said Caparas was only to meet
with Marcos representatives but not negotiate.
   U.S. officials said a hasty settlement of Philippine charges by
Manila could undermine American efforts to prosecute Marcos.
   ``The justice officials from the U.S. Attorney General's office
insisted that whatever terms and conditions Caparas negotiates, a
plea of guilty by either Marcos or his wife should be
non-negotiable,'' Locsin wrote.
   Locsin quoted Caparas as saying U.S. officials threatened to
withhold evidence of Marcos' alleged secret bank accounts received
from the Swiss government.
   They also warned that the U.S. attorney general could take
possession of Marcos' properties in New York, which the Philippine
government hopes to sell, and ``dispose of them as he deems fit,''
Locsin added.
   The properties are estimated to be worth $300 million.
   Marcos and his wife Imelda have lived in Hawaii since a 1986
popular uprising toppled his 20-year administration. Marcos has been
hospitalized since Jan. 15 with heart and lung ailments and has
asked to return to die in his homeland.
   Last October, the Marcoses were indicted on U.S. federal
racketeering charges alleging they stole more than $100 million and
stashed much of the money in American banks.
   Locsin said U.S. Attorney Charles LaBella of New York told
Caparas that U.S. officials could also agree to a plea-bargain that
would be unfavorable to Manila.
   ``In seven days ... the U.S. cases could be dropped and all U.S.
legal constraints on Marcos' return to Manila would evaporate,''
Locsin said. ``The Philippines would then have no leverage to deal
with Marcos, either to secure a financial restitution or even a
promise of good behavior from him.''
   Efforts to contact Caparas in New York were unsuccessful because
he refused to return calls from The Associated Press.
   In another development, an ex-Cabinet minister said he deposited
into a Swiss bank account more than $4.5 million in kickbacks from
Japanese companies for Marcos, according to court documents obtained
Tuesday.
   The seven Japanese companies he named all denied the allegation.
   Baltazar Aquino, Marcos' former public works and highways
minister, made the allegation in four statements submitted Friday
during deposition hearings in connection with 39 civil suits against
the former president.
</TEXT>
