<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--Grenada     02-08 0119</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Grenada,0121</SECOND>
<HEAD>British Navy Helps Grenada Celebrate Independence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. GEORGE'S, Grenada (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British sailors from the frigate
Avenger and a British helicopter towing a huge Grenadian flag took
part in a military parade marking this Caribbean island's 15th
anniversary of independence from Britain.
   Premier H.A. Blaize, Gov. Gen. Sir Paul Scoon and other
dignitaries and opposition leaders took part in the ceremony,
attended by about 2,000 people.
   The tiny eastern Caribbean island, with a population of 100,000
people, became independent from Britain on Feb. 7, 1974.
   It was the scene of a U.S.-led invasion in October 1983 that
ousted a regime of hard-line Marxists, who days before assassinated
leftist Prime Minister Maurice Bishop in a bloody coup.
