<FILEID>AP-NR-02-08-89 0119EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-FuelSpill     02-08 0310</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fuel Spill,0318</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Accepts No Contest Plea</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ashland Oil Inc. entered a no contest plea
Tuesday on two federal environmental law violations stemming from
the January 1988 diesel fuel spill.
   U.S. District Judge Gustave Diamond accepted the plea after a
six-hour hearing. He set a sentencing hearing for March 6.
   Under federal law, a no contest plea, while not an admission of
guilt, is a conviction.
   ``They'll face the same criminal penalty as a person who is found
guilty,'' said Acting U.S. Attorney Charles Sheehy.
   In Ashland's case, that amounts to a maximum fine that could
include $200,000 for each of the two counts, $25,000 for each day of
the violation and twice the amount of damages to persons and
property.
   A federal grand jury in September indicted Ashland on two
misdemeanor counts of violating the Clean Water Act and Refuse Act.
   Two months later the company filed a brief seeking dismissal of
the charges. Ashland cited false testimony given by Allegheny County
fire and police officials concerning the company's efforts to obtain
permits to erect the tank.
   In late November, two of the top county officials involved were
forced to resign because of their testimony. A third was suspended.
   Sheehy opposed acceptance of the plea during the hearing, saying
it ``lends credence to the view that a double standard of justice
exists.''
   Sheehy also noted in his brief that such pleas have been opposed
by the U.S. Justice Department as a way to skirt moral
responsibility.
   Ashland still faces 18 civil lawsuits as a result of the Jan. 2,
1988, spill at its Floreffe terminal on the Monongahela River. The
sudden collapse of a diesel storage tank sent about 713,000 gallons
of fuel into the river, creating a slick that disrupted water
supplies to thousands of customers in western Pennsylvania, West
Virginia and Ohio.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
