<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--SAfrica-Unionist     02-08 0143</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--SAfrica-Unionist,0145</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leader of Black Labor Federation Denied Passport</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The general secretary of the
country's largest labor federation was denied a passport to go to
Zimbabwe for a conference dealing with sanctions on South Africa,
the federation says.
   The Congress of South African Trade Unions, a predominantly black
federation that actively opposes apartheid, said Tuesday that Jay
Naidoo submitted an urgent passport application on Jan. 5 in hopes
of attending this week's conference in Harare.
   Representatives of eight Commonwealth countries are meeting to
discuss ways of intensifying pressure on South Africa's
white-dominated government to dismantle its system of racial
separation.
   The federation said it received no response to Naidoo's
application despite two letters and four telephone calls to the
Department of Home Affairs. The department refuses to disclose
reasons for its decisions on passport and visa applications.
</TEXT>
