<FIRST>r w PM-Skinner-Terrorism     02-08 0458</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Skinner-Terrorism,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Skinner To Seek Anti-Terrorism Measures</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner says he
will seek strong measures against air terrorism when he attends an
international meeting in Montreal next week but will oppose steps
that put U.S. airlines at a business disadvantage.
   Skinner, at his first news conference as secretary, on Monday
rejected the idea of public warnings of terrorist threats. He also
announced that he would replace Federal Aviation Administrator Alan
McArtor, who he said has asked to return to private business.
   The Montreal meeting of the Council of the International Civil
Aviation Organization Feb. 15-16 was called to find ways to improve
international standards for passenger, baggage and cargo security.
Top transportation officials from the 33 council member nations have
been invited.
   Skinner did not give details of the steps the United States would
seek at the Montreal conference but said worldwide safety measures
are needed. He said restrictions should not apply only to U.S.
airlines.
   U.S. and British officials called for the session after the
explosion of Pan Am Flight 103 that killed all 259 people aboard and
11 other people on the ground in Scotland Dec. 21. Authorities say a
bomb blew up the plane and they are still considering several
possible perpetrators, methods and motives.
   Families of Flight 103 victims called Monday for McArtor's
resignation for FAA failure to ensure safety of the
Frankfurt-London-New York flight and warn passengers of threats
against the flight.
   ``If we were to shut down airlines every time there is a threat,
we will allow terrorists to disrupt the economy of not only this
nation but every nation in the world,'' Skinner said.
   Skinner said McArtor had done a ``good job in many aspects'' but
has said he wants to step down. McArtor had indicated he wanted to
leave prior to the security concerns raised by the destruction of
Flight 103.
   On other topics:
   _Skinner said he will decide within a few days whether to allow
lower mileage standards for the automobile industry than the 27.5
miles-per-gallon average scheduled to go into effect for 1990
models. The industry claims the tougher standard would be too costly
and force car makers to produce smaller cars the public won't buy.
The current standard is 26.5 miles per gallon.
   _He said mass transit systems should be weaned away from federal
funding but the government cannot ``just cut off the spigot of
federal funds.'' Skinner headed the mass transit system in Northern
Illinois before becoming secretary.
   _The new secretary rejected for now the idea of reorganizing the
department as proposed by his predecessor, James Burnley, but said
he would try to make the present setup work and might look at
reorganization later.
</TEXT>
