<FIRST>r w PM-AIDS-PayRaise     02-08 0329</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AIDS-Pay Raise,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pay Raise Vote Compounds Problem of Recruiting Scientists, Experts
Say</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Pay Raise Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY DENISE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Health experts say defeat of the federal pay
raise will further hinder efforts to recruit and retain scientists
for the government's battle against AIDS.
   Food and Drug Administration Commissioner Frank Young told a
Senate panel that scientists who are paid about $60,000 annually at
his agency ``can leave for salaries of four or five times'' that.
   Testifying to the Senate Labor and Human Resources Committee
hours before Congress voted Tuesday to deny itself a 51 percent pay
raise, Young said the FDA was in much the same predicament as the
National Institutes of Health, which said recently it had been
unable to recruit a senior scientist in the last 10 years.
   The pay raise measure that Congress rejected included increases
of $40,000 to $59,500 for top-level officials in the executive
branch. Among those would have been scientists for the FDA and NIH.
   The commissioner said the agency's drug review division where the
number of applications for new AIDS drug research had doubled was
especially hard hit by the shortage of scientists.
   For example, he said, the FDA hadn't anticipated that the number
of applications for AIDS drug research would double, that there
would be annual instead of biannual inspections of the nation's drug
supply, or that there would be problems with inspections of condoms
and rubber gloves.
   ``We're in a difficult position of knowing how to prepare a
budget,'' Young also said, because ``we can't anticipate two years
ahead'' as the federal budget process requires.
   AIDS, or acquired immune deficiency syndrome, is a contagious
disease that attacks the body's immune system, rendering it
incapable of resisting other diseases and infections.
   As of Jan. 2 the Centers for Disease Control in Atlanta said
there were 32,311 AIDS cases reported in the United States in 1988,
a 57 percent increase from a year before.
</TEXT>
