<FIRST>r w PM-Judges'Pay     02-08 0509</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Judges' Pay,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judges Hardest Hit by Pay Raise Rejection, Legal Profession Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Pay Raise Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of the legal profession contend that
federal judges are the biggest losers in the congressional vote to
scuttle hefty pay raises for top government officials.
   While members of Congress ``can still supplement their income''
with speech-making fees and political committee contributions,
``judges are left with salaries that have decreased in real dollars
by 30 percent over the past two decades,'' American Bar Association
President Robert Raven said Tuesday.
   ``The recommended increase for federal judges did little more
than restore lost ground,'' said Raven, a San Francisco lawyer.
   John J. Curtin Jr., a Boston lawyer who in August will become
president of the 350,000-lawyer ABA, said the lost pay raise for
judges ``will destroy their morale.''
   ``The fallout on the federal judiciary is going to be
devastating,'' Curtin said, adding that his organization will lobby
President Bush and Congress to raise the pay of federal judges only.
   Had the raise taken effect today, salaries for federal trial
judges _ like those of members of Congress _ would have climbed from
$89,500 to $135,000 a year.
   The annual salaries of federal appellate judges would have risen
from $95,000 to $145,000; Supreme Court justices from $110,000 to
$165,000; and chief justice from $115,000 to $175,000.
   ``Congress' rejection of the pay raise quells a political
firestorm over raising congressional salaries but foments a serious
problem within the federal judiciary,'' Raven said.
   He said that inflation-eroded pay for federal judges ``flouts the
wisdom of our Constitution'' and the lifetime judicial appointments
it provides.
   ``Inadequate and decreasing pay forces all but independently
wealthy judges to forgo their life tenure and market their
experience and training on the bench in the more lucrative arena of
private (law) firms,'' Raven said.
   Salaries of federal judges have been raised six times this decade
_ and now are 24 percent higher than they were in 1980. But the cost
of living, as measured by the Consumers Price Index, has risen by 46
percent over the same period.
   Since 1969 _ a period in which many federal judges say their
buying power has dropped by a third _ the cost of living has risen
by 227 percent.
   Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist had called the pay raises
``essential if we are to continue to attract from the financially
greener fields of private practice the sort of experienced and
capable lawyers whom we want as judges.''
   During House debate on the pay raise Tuesday, Rep. Vic Fazio,
D-Calif., emphasized the problem for judges. ``There are Supreme
Court justices who make less than their clerks the day after they
(the clerks) go into private practice,'' Fazio said.
   Raven said Fazio's comment was ``not far off,'' and noted that
some law firms offer starting salaries of $76,000 a year.
   ``Certainly a starting lawyer who receives two years' credit for
having worked as a law clerk immediately is making more than a trial
judge,'' Raven said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
