<FIRST>r a PM-Jackson-School Bjt   02-08 0533</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Jackson-School, Bjt,0549</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rocker Visits Scene Of Massacre, Wounded Children</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHLEEN MACLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKTON, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pop idol Michael Jackson's surprise visit
to an elementary school still scarred by a deranged gunman's
murderous rampage was so thrilling that one child couldn't even
remember her last name.
   ``It was kind of neat to see after what the school has
experienced,'' said Ron Teague, 36, who helped organize the
Cleveland Elementary School pupils for Jackson's lightning visit on
Tuesday. ``The children were just ecstatic, they treated him like a
brother.''
   ``I think they'll remember this for a long time,'' said Stockton
Unified School District spokesman John Klose.
   Jackson also dropped in at San Joaquin General Hospital, where
two youngsters were still being treated. The two were among 30
wounded on Jan. 17, when 26-year-old Patrick Edward Purdy returned
to his old elementary school and opened fire on the school yard with
an assault rifle, killing five children before committing suicide.
   At the hospital, Jackson, wearing a dark military-style jacket
with red epaulets but without his trademark glittering glove, spent
a few minutes with Vann Sa, 7, and Long Keo, 6.
   ``It was not what I would call a dialogue,'' said hospital
spokeswoman Sharon Booker. ``But five to seven minutes with Michael
Jackson _ what can you compare it to?''
   Vann Sa was listed in fair condition and was expected to remain
in the hospital for another week. Long Keo was released later in the
day.
   School officials weren't sure the visit was on until a few hours
beforehand. The hospital didn't know for sure until an hour before
Jackson arrived.
   Hundreds of people assembled outside the school on the chilly
morning, hoping for a glimpse of the superstar. But Jackson, who
arrived in a white limousine, was whisked into the school through a
back door.
   He visited classrooms where kindergarten, first, second and third
grade pupils were gathered, then stopped at an assembly of fourth
through sixth graders. No reporters or photographers were allowed to
watch as Jackson met with the children.
   ``He made a grand appearance,'' said Teague. ``All the children
were smiling.''
   ``He just smiled and that's it,'' said 6-year-old Lanisha, who
added that she was so flustered over Michael's visit she couldn't
remember her last name. Eleven-year-old Hannah Schardt, who attends
another school, came with her mother.
   ``He just made a peace sign and left right away after about five
seconds,'' she said. ``He just kind of said, `Hi' and nodded.''
   The visit came a day after City Council unanimously approved an
ordinance outlawing possession or sale of assault rifles like the
AK-47 Purdy used in his rampage. Los Angeles' City Council on
Tuesday unanimously approved a similar ban.
   Purdy, wearing combat fatigues, slipped into the schoolyard as
children were playing at midday recess and opened fire with his
semi-automatic weapon, firing more than 100 shots.
   The Stockton ordinance makes possession of assault guns a
misdemeanor and carries a $500 fine and a maximum six months' jail
sentence. It takes effect in seven days, after which any
semi-automatic weapon found in the city would be confiscated and
destroyed. Opponents said they would appeal before then.
</TEXT>
