<FIRST>r a PM-Parkinson's-Brain     02-08 0394</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Parkinson's-Brain,0405</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study Shows Modest Improvement From Parkinson's Disease Operation</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Wednesday's 6 p.m. EST embargo has been broken. This story is
for immediate release.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An experimental brain operation to treat
Parkinson's disease has produced moderate improvement for some
victims but not the ``miracle'' that an earlier report suggested, a
researcher said.
   ``All the patients in our group have said they felt it was
worthwhile, but in no case has it achieved what they hoped it
would,'' said Dr. Christopher G. Goetz of Rush-Presbyterian-St.
Luke's Medical Center in Chicago.
   The operation involves removing tissue from patients' adrenal
glands and transplanting it in their brains. The goal is to provide
the victims' brains with a source of dopamine, an essential
message-carrying chemical that they lack.
   The operation was first reported two years ago by Dr. Ignacio
Madrazo and colleagues at the National Autonomous University of
Mexico and the social security hospital system in Mexico City. They
reported dramatic improvement in two patients. Since then, surgeons
at many medical centers have tried to duplicate their results.
   ``What came out originally was the sense that this was a
miracle,'' said Goetz. ``This is no miracle.''
   His report combined the results of surgery on 19 patients at his
hospital and at the University of South Florida and the University
of Kansas. The results were being published in Thursday's New
England Journal of Medicine.
   Parkinson's disease results from destruction of a part of the
brain called the nigral tissue, which makes dopamine. The adrenal
glands, which lie above the kidneys, also produce the substance.
   The disease afflicts between 500,000 and 1 million Americans,
including 2 percent of people over age 70. Victims often suffer
tremors and have trouble controlling their movements.
   Drugs can control the disease, but as the illness worsens, the
medicines lose their effectiveness and often don't work for hours at
a time.
   Before the surgery, the patients' drugs worked about half the
time. Afterward, this increased to three-quarters of the time.
   While the drugs are working, the patients are able to move about
and care for themselves with little assistance, although they still
clearly show the effects of the disease. When the drugs are not
effective, the patients usually need wheelchairs.
   ``Despite cautious optimism, we conclude that the widespread use
of this procedure outside of research centers is premature,'' the
researchers wrote.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890208-0039 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-08-89 0210EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Walesa Bjt   02-08 0745</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Walesa, Bjt,0772</SECOND>
<HEAD>Solidarity Leader, In Fancy Suit, Captivates Working Class Rally</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The featured guest at the government-run
Institute of Building Techniques apologized to the crowd for his
fancy blue suit.
   ``I wanted to say I'm not that elegant. I also work hard, I'm
just a worker,'' Lech Walesa told the roughly 500 people in the
audience.
   The 45-year-old shipyard electrician who chairs the banned
Solidarity free trade union movement won a round of applause Tuesday
when introduced by institute director Marian Weglarz.
   ``I want to welcome the great Pole, the laureate of the Nobel
Peace Prize, Mr. Lech Walesa. It is a great honor that Mr. Walesa
bothered to come to us the day after the session of the round table.
Long live Walesa,'' said Weglarz.
   Walesa is leading the opposition delegation in historic
``round-table'' talks with Communist authorities that began Monday
and seeks the social accord needed to tackle Poland's daunting
economic crisis.
   ``We are witnesses to historic moments that will remain in our
memory until the end of our lives. Long live Lech Walesa,'' Weglarz
added.
   Since Solidarity was crushed in a December 1981 military
crackdown and banned the next year, Walesa has rarely been allowed
to address workers legally on state property.
   But Walesa held a lively hour-long question-and-answer session
with his constituents _ the rank-and-file for whom he is trying to
gain restoration of Solidarity's legal status in the round-table
talks.
   The rally was a reminder of the days during Solidarity's 16-month
legal existence when Walesa traveled the country, captivating
audiences with straightforward speeches explaining the need for free
trade unions.
   Walesa responded to Weglarz's introduction with some easy-going
banter.
   ``I'm surprised. I have stage fright and I don't know what to
answer. Mr. Director, let me speak, you are talking too much,'' he
said.
   The crowd laughed.
   The Solidarity chairman seemed aware that to some, it might
appear a different Walesa was behind the podium, and he apologized
for his fancy suit. He is more frequently seen in drab polyester.
   He explained: ``I came here straight from the embassy, where I
said goodbye to the Swiss foreign minister and I came here straight
to you.''
   Then, speaking from a platform draped with a large Solidarity
banner, he explained why he feels compelled to negotiate with the
same authorities that crushed his movement and are widely distrusted
by much of the populace.
   ``I'm doing everything to take advantage of all chances to build
agreement, to build a better Poland. I think I won't let anybody
cheat me. I think you will not let anybody cheat you,'' he said.
   ``I don't believe in the round table, but I do believe in you and
in structures. Lech Walesa and company are making it possible so
that you can get organized, so that you can choose structures and
organizations to solve Polish problems with them,'' he said.
   Above all, Walesa counseled patience in Poland, which is wracked
by a $39 billion foreign debt, 60 percent inflation, chronic
consumer shortages and rising worker dissatisfaction.
   The government first proposed the round-table talks in August
during the country's worst labor unrest since Solidarity's heyday.
   Walesa branded as ``great political stupidity'' a call for a
second Solidarity congress by Andrzej Gwiazda, a former rival for
leadership of the union who has criticized him for refusing to hold
another national convention.
   ``The congress would show many weaknesses (within Solidarity) and
we don't need it right now,'' Walesa said.
   The audience peppered him with questions, asking him what
Solidarity means, how will it be organized and whether he trusts the
authorities.
   ``Solidarity means first of all reform ... It is a fundamental
problem today that we should get organized as a trade union,''
Walesa said.
   He warned the crowd to above all remain peaceful.
   ``If the Polish peaceful evolution doesn't win, there will be a
revolution in this country and splinters may fall down far away ...
So if you want to live in security, it's in your interest to allow
the Polish evolution to develop peacefully and it will be profitable
for all.
   ``We must remember that seven years have been wasted. We must
save the national tissue, we must stop youth from escaping from
Poland. No one will make order in Poland for us. It is our Poland,''
he said.
   ``It's beautiful to hear him again,'' one woman in the crowd said.
</TEXT>
