<FILEID>AP-NR-02-08-89 0213EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     02-08 0249</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0256</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shares Set Another Record High, Dollar Unchanged</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices rose further to end Wednesday's session
at yet another trading high on the Tokyo Stock Exchange, while the
U.S. dollar showed no change against the Japanese yen from the
previous closing.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which surpassed
the 32,000-point level for the first time in Wednesday's morning
session, rose further in the afternoon to gain 184.47 points, or
0.58 percent, and finish at record high of 32,065.12.
   The dollar closed at 129.50 yen, unchanged from both its opening
level and its finish on Tuesday. The currency moved in a narrow
range of 129.40-129.53 yen during the day's dealings.
   Trading in the U.S. currency will remain in a narrow range ahead
of President Bush's budget address before Congress, scheduled for
Thursday night, dealers said.
   ``The dollar-yen rate hardly moved because the investors were
equally selling and buying the U.S. money for speculative reasons,''
said Chemical Bank's Ichiro Ikeda.
   On the stock exchange, the Nikkei opened sharply higher after
rises on overseas markets overnight, stock dealers said.
   ``Individual and foreign investors' strong buying interest has
contributed to the recent rise in the Nikkei,'' said a dealer with
Nomura Securities, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Recent stability in the currency market has prompted investors to
buy, he said.
   Prices on the exchange rise naturally because demand for stocks
exceeds supply. But the recent surge in prices could make investors
nervous, the dealer said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
