<FILEID>AP-NR-02-08-89 0314EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Drugs-Mayors     02-08 0601</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drugs-Mayors,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bennett Makes No Promises on Drug-Fighting Money to Cities</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX10</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayors from cities across the nation, anxious
to discover whether the Bush administration will help them fight the
drug war on the city streets, got an encouraging sign but no
promises from drug czar-designate William J. Bennett.
   ``This is serious business,'' Bennett told the U.S. Conference of
Mayors on Tuesday. ``This is the business of state and local
governments. But it is emphatically the business of the federal
government.''
   But Bennett, nominated by President Bush to become the nation's
first director of National Drug Control Policy, didn't say how that
business would translate into dollars for the local governments.
   The mayors are extremely concerned about funding because while
the drug bill called for $275 million to be spent in the current
fiscal year for Justice Assistance programs _ grants to state and
local agencies _ only $220 million has been appropriated by Congress.
   And no money at all was included for those programs in President
Reagan's budget proposal for fiscal 1990. In that year, the drug
bill called for $350 million to be spent on those programs. Bush is
expected to reveal his budget proposals for fiscal 1990 later this
week.
   San Diego Mayor Maureen O'Connor, noting that her city suffered
96 drive-by shooting incidents last year, called for federal funds
to be funneled directly to the local governments, a suggestion
loudly applauded by her colleagues.
   ``The problem with some of the federal money in the past is that
it had to go through so many hands before it go to the streets, and
by the time it gets to the streets, it's too late,'' O'Connor said.
   Addressing her remarks to Bennett, she said, ``If there's some
way that you could organize a program ... to go from the federal
government right to the local entity to help solve the problem, you
will have done more for the war on drugs than anything I can think
of.''
   Bennett told reporters after the conference that his budget
decisions would have to await completion of the national drug
control strategy report, which is due 180 days after he is confirmed
by the Senate. His hearings before the Senate Judiciary Committee
are scheduled to begin March 1.
   ``Certainly some of the effort is going to take money,'' he said.
``You're going to see some progrss and some movement on this issue
very soon. The six-month report is the critical document to me.''
   Sen. Joseph R. Biden Jr., D-Del., chairman of the Senate
Judiciary Committee, predicted that Congress would fully fund the
drug bill for the current year, approving legislation already
introduced in both houses to add $1.6 billion to spending.
   While those bills do not specify how to pay for that spending,
Biden said it could be provided by raising taxes on cigarettes, beer
and liquor.
   ``We're still 60 percent behind what the tax was in 1954 on those
commodities,'' he said. ``If you have a better idea, suggest it, or
stop saying you support the drug bill.''
   Bennett said he will pay attention to the law enforcement end of
the drug war and is considering a bigger role for the military, but
he wouldn't disclose what role that might be.
   Joking about the controversy over Bush's decision to leave him
out of the Cabinet, Bennett told the mayors, ``I have a meeting with
the president tomorrow, one on one. As a bonus on Thursday, I'm
going to a Cabinet meeting. ... I always prefer a one-on-one
tutorial to a seminar.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
