<FIRST>r w PM-Sullivan-HHS     02-08 0621</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sullivan-HHS,610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sullivan to Divest Holdings, Recuse Self on Morehouse</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of the Senate Finance Committee are
reviewing the financial file on Cabinet nominee Louis Sullivan along
with assurances from government ethics officials that he will have
no conflicts of interest.
   Sullivan, President Bush's nominee to head the Department of
Health and Human Services, has agreed to sell some of his financial
holdings and recuse himself on matters that involve his medical
school, according to an HHS ethics official.
   The actions will ``avoid the potential for any conflicts of
interests or appearance'' of a conflict, Darrel J. Grinstead, HHS
ethics official, said in a letter to Frank Q. Nebeker, director of
the Office of Government Ethics.
   Copies of the letter were sent to Finance Committee members along
with copies of Sullivan's financial disclosure form, the ethics
office said.
   Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, chairman of the committee, said he
wanted ``to move as expeditiously as possible'' on Sullivan's
confirmation hearing, but congressional sources who spoke on the
condition of anonymity said the hearing probably won't be held for
at least two weeks.
   Though initial review of the ethics report raised few questions
among committee members, lawmakers say they want time for a close
review of the nominee's financial disclosure report, and Congress is
scheduled to be in recess next week.
   ``This man looks excellent on paper to us,'' said a congressional
source who spoke on the condition of anonymity. But, the source
added, ``we don't want to have any corners on this tent that aren't
nailed down.''
   Sullivan's confirmation, originally scheduled for last week, was
postponed by lingering questions over Sullivan's financial situation
and his FBI background check.
   The nominee put to rest the major concerns raised about his ties
to the Morehouse School of Medicine when he said he would resign as
president, forgo nearly $300,000 in severance pay and take an unpaid
leave of absence as a professor of medicine.
   An FBI background check focused in part on his connection to a
Georgia politician convicted of extortion who, unrelated to the
extortion case, was paid as a part-time lecturer by Morehouse while
he used his seat on the county commission to support issues that
benefited the school.
   Presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Tuesday the
background investigation had been completed and found ``no adverse
information as far as we know.''
   Grinstead's letter said Sullivan agreed to divest himself of
holdings in three companies to avoid any potential conflicts of
interest.
   The holdings he will divest are valued at between $7,000 and
$25,000 in a total portfolio worth between $633,000 and $1.17
million or more. His largest holdings are in pension plans, valued
at between $450,000 and $750,000 or more. His liabilities are listed
at between $40,000 and $115,000.
   While on leave, Sullivan will not be paid by Morehouse, but will
continue to participate in the school's employee benefit plans,
including health and life insurance, disability insurance and the
school's retirement plan, according to Grinstead's letter.
   The letter also says that because of his continued tie to
Morehouse, Sullivan would recuse himself from participating as HHS
secretary in matters such as grants, contracts, litigation,
investigations and enforcement actions specifically involving the
school.
   The White House, however, has agreed to allow Sullivan to
participate in general policy matters ``such as regulations and
legislation that would affect Morehouse only to the same extent that
similarly situated institutions would be affected,'' Grinstead said
in the letter.
   Finance Committee members want more information about ``others
who have maintained their ties with academic institutions'' after
taking a federal government job, the congressional source said.
``We're looking for examples in which this kind of situation has
occurred before.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890208-0046 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-08-89 0339EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-PayRaise-Radio     02-08 0647</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pay Raise-Radio,0671</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressional Pay Raise Dominated Talk Radio Shows</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Pay Raise-States, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JONATHAN W. OATIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The 51 percent pay raise that Congress wound up rejecting
dominated the airwaves around the country, with switchboards at some
talk-radio stations lighting up nearly once a minute and practically
every caller was against it.
   ``Since the election, it's been the best issue as far as stirring
people up,'' talk-show host Roger Gray of KPRC in Houston said
Tuesday.
   ``And it's almost unanimously negative. I think today we got one
caller in support. But callers like that are in the distinct
minority.''
   Responding to the outcry against the proposed pay hike, Congress
voted overwhelmingly Tuesday to reject it, then rushed the
legislation to President Bush, who signed it hours before a midnight
deadline.
   Rep. Vic Fazio, a pay raise defender, chided House colleagues for
not having ``the courage to speak out'' in their own defense. ``We
became cartoon cannon fodder for trash television and talk radio,''
the California Democrat complained.
   ``This wasn't artificially created,'' said talk-radio host Mike
Siegel of station KING in Seattle, who ran his show from Washington,
D.C., last week and testified before a Senate committee on the pay
raise. ``The lines were flooded every day.''
   Siegel urged listeners to write and call representatives to
express opposition to the proposal, and was part of a network of
stations nationwide that suggested sending lawmakers tea bags
symbolic of the Boston Tea Party.
   ``Everybody's thrilled'' by Tuesday's vote, said Cindy Slay,
producer of the Jim Eason talk show at KGO in San Francisco. ``I get
maybe one call out of 50 who say they were for the pay raise.''
   Slay said the show, which is on weekdays from 2-4 p.m., received
about 50 calls per hour, or nearly one a minute, on the issue.
   Several callers to KGO thanked talk-show hosts and activists such
as Ralph Nader for drawing attention to the issue, Slay said.
   ``The credit should go to the outraged citizenry who mailed in
tea bags and truckloads of letters and who complained and made phone
calls,'' said Eason.
   In Baltimore, WBAL talk-show host Ron Smith said, ``People were
just very gratified, amazed and delighted that they made this effort
against the odds and that they actually achieved something.''
   He said 80 to 90 percent of his callers expressed outrage at the
pay raise's size, its timing and the original plan for it to have
taken effect automatically.
   In Washington, callers to WWRC expressed happiness that the pay
raise had been turned down, said producer Lori Madock,
   ``Our lines are going crazy,'' she said, noting that the
station's nine telephone lines had been receiving about 25 calls an
hour.
   ``This congressional pay raise is a joke,'' said a caller
identifying himself as Jim of Herndon, Va. ``Look at the mess
they've made of things.''
   But Rita in Bethesda, Md., said she thought the raise should have
been approved. ``These people (who oppose the raise) seem to think
that's a tremendous amount of money and it isn't,'' she said.
   In Phoenix, KTAR News Director Preston Westmoreland said so many
callers opposed the plan because ``people feel that with the
economic troubles of today and the budget deficit that you just have
no business giving yourself a 50 percent pay raise.''
   Of the dozen people who called Pittsburgh's KDKA on Tuesday,
``the overriding message now that it's done is `Let's find out who
supported it and vote them out of office,''' said producer Greg Jena.
   Among those taking heavy fire were House Speaker Jim Wright,
D-Texas, who initially had planned to let the increase take effect
automatically today without a House vote.
   ``I'm very disgusted in Jim Wright,'' said one caller to KLIF-AM
in Fort Worth, which Wright represents. ``I'm going to work as hard
as I can to get him out of office.''
</TEXT>
