<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     02-08 0446</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Congressman Who Suffers From Lyme Disease Urges Research,
Education</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Rep. Berkley W. Bedell returned to
Congress to seek funding for research and education on Lyme disease,
the tick-borne disease that forced him out of office.
   The Iowa Democrat, who served in the House for 12 years, said
Tuesday public education is badly needed to fight the disease, which
activists said is second only to AIDS as the most widespread new
infectious disease of the 1980s.
   Bedell, who left office in 1987, said he supports new legislation
by Reps. George Hochbrueckner, D-N.Y., and Sam Gejdenson, D-Conn.,
to provide $2.5 million annually for three years for research and
treatment grants and another $1 million a year for education.
   Bedell, 67, said he has an irregular heartbeat, suffers from
arthritis, experiences loss of memory and tires easily due to the
affliction. But he said his condition was diagnosed quickly and
treated. Others often do not realize they have the disease until it
becomes more debilitating.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>Consumer Debt Grew By $5.4 Billion in December</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans borrowed $5.4 billion more than they
repaid in December, the government reports.
   The December borrowing raised the consumer debt at an annual rate
of 9.9 percent, the Federal Reserve Board said Tuesday. The consumer
debt rose $4.7 billion in November and increased $3.9 billion in
October.
   The seasonally adjusted annual rate of credit growth was 8.5
percent in November and 7.2 percent in October.
   December's increase matched the 9.9 percent rise recorded last
August, which was the highest since a 15.2 percent increase in June.
   The December jump was paced by an increase in outstanding auto
loans, while growth in the category of debt that includes credit
cards slowed from the rapid pace of the preceding two months.
   Consumer spending is closely watched as a barometer of economic
health because it accounts for two-thirds of the gross national
product.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>World Bank Loans to Hit Record $21 Billion</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New loans by the World Bank, biggest source of
aid to the Third World, will reach a record $21 billion in the year
ending June 30, bank officials predict.
   Ernest Stern, vice president for finance, estimated Tuesday that
$16 billion would go to the somewhat more prosperous countries which
still need easy loans to raise their living standards. They pay
interest at a variable rate, now 7.65 percent a year.
   Sheldon Rappaport, the bank's financial spokesman, said over $5.5
billion will go to the poorest countries from the bank's
International Development Association. It makes loans at less than 1
percent interest.
   New loans in the previous year totaled $19.2 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
