<FILEID>AP-NR-02-08-89 0610EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-BusAccident     02-08 0599</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bus Accident,0620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Driver Warned Passengers He Had No Brakes Moments Before Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ENSENADA, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bus driver told passengers ``Hang on, I
have no brakes'' moments before his city bus plunged off a steep,
winding road and down a 60-foot cliff, killing 19 people and
injuring 22, authorities said.
   The driver, Enrique Hernandez de Jesus, and two children were
among the 14 bus occupants dead at the scene of the accident on the
outskirts of this Baja California resort 65 miles south of the U.S.
border.
   Five other passengers died at hospitals, Ensenada Fire Department
spokesman Jose Luis Chavez said. Several of the injured passengers
remained hospitalized Tuesday in critical condition, said Miroslava
Cuellar, a spokeswoman for the city of Ensenada.
   A mass funeral was planned for today, said Ramon Moreno, owner of
the Moreno Funeral Home, which is handling the arrangements.
   Baja California transit office records show the vehicle had gone
five years without a mechanical inspection and had no insurance as
required by state law, Cuellar said.
   ``It is well-known that there is corruption between the transport
companies and state transit officials,'' she said.
   ``Considering that these vehicles are allowed to operate without
inspections and without insurance, and that drivers are paid not a
salary but by the number of passengers they can cram into their
buses, it is clear there is corruption.''
   Officials of Transportes Rojo y Blanco (Red and White bus line),
the private transit company that owns the bus, declined comment
Tuesday about the accident.
   Chavez said he hoped the tragedy would prompt an investigation of
Ensenada's public transportation system, which he said is ``full of
buses ... (that are) coffins on wheels.''
   Most of the passengers on the bus bound for downtown were from a
poor neighborhood of Ensenada, a city of 78,000 people, but it
wasn't immediately known if any of the occupants were from outside
of Mexico.
   The accident occurred Monday as the bus, traveled a steep, windy
stretch of road four miles northeast of downtown.
   The bus apparently was going too fast when Hernandez came to a
sharp curve, causing the vehicle to careen over an embankment,
Chavez said.
   It tore through the wire fence of the Ensenada Country Club and
rolled several times down a dirt slope, stopping about 100 feet from
the club's swimming pool. The roof of the mangled bus was flattened
almost to the floor in some places, authorities said.
   ``People started screaming and pushing, trying to get to the
door, and then everything was flying,'' passenger Juana Santiago,
19, said from her bed at Ensenada General Hospital. ``I hugged my
baby and closed my eyes. I don't remember anything that happened
after that.''
   Santiago, who was taking her daughter to a vaccine center,
suffered a broken leg. She said her daughter was not injured
seriously, but her mother-in-law, who was seated next to her, was
dead.
   One passenger told fire officials that the driver yelled, ``Hang
on tight, I have no brakes,'' moments before the bus' plunge.
   A woman who lives about 200 yards from the accident scene said
she ran to see what happened after hearing a tremendous crash.
   ``It was a horror scene,'' said Leticia Perez de la Rosa.
``People were screaming, begging for help and I started to cry.''
   Eduardo Guillen, commander of the Baja California judicial police
in Ensenada, said the state has ordered an immediate inspection of
all buses in the city.
   ``If the company is found to be responsible (for the accident
through negligence), then it will have to pay for all damages,''
Guillen said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
