<FILEID>AP-NR-02-08-89 0610EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-SriLanka     02-08 0489</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sri Lanka,0506</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tamil Rebels Ask UN To Mediate Ethnic Conflict</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A militant Tamil separatist group said
today it has appealed to the U.N. Commission on Human Rights to
mediate an end the 5-year ethnic conflict that has claimed 8,500
lives in Sri Lanka.
   The Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam, the most powerful Tamil
guerrilla group, also called for an immediate cease-fire and the
withdrawal of the estimated 47,000 Indian soldiers on the Indian
Ocean island.
   Indian troops were sent to Sri Lanka in 1987 to disarm the Tigers
in order to enforce an Indian-sponsored peace accord.
   The Tigers initially accepted the accord but later reneged,
resuming attacks on the country's Sinhalese ethnic majority and
battling the Indian peacekeeping force.
   The Tigers, in a letter to the U.N., claimed ``Indian troops
under the cover of `peacekeeping' operations continue to engage
themselves in a ruthless and brutal war against the innocent
civilian masses, causing intolerable suffering to the Tamil people.''
   The Tigers accused Indian soldiers of committing torture,
executions without trial and ``extermination'' of more than 200
prominent Tamils who opposed the 1987 accord.
   In New Delhi, an Indian official rejected the Tigers' accusation,
calling it ``part of their usual propaganda.''
   A copy of the Tigers' appeal to the U.N. was sent by telex to
news offices in Colombo from the guerrillas' information office in
London.
   Its arrival coincided with today's withdrawal from northern Sri
Lanka of an Indian battalion, one of two the Sri Lankan Defense
Ministry announced Tuesday would return home within two weeks
following discussions between the Indian and Sri Lankan governments.
   Two other battalions, consisting of about 3,500 men, withdrew in
early January.
   President Ranasinghe Premadasa, who took office Jan. 2, has
pledged to seek the withdrawal of Indian troops and to convert the
July 1987 Indian-Sri Lankan accord into a peace and friendship
treaty.
   The accord was signed by Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi of India and
President Junius R. Jayewardene, Premadasa's predecessor.
   India, which once provided sanctuary to the Tigers on Indian
soil, became involved in the affairs of its small island neighbor
because of the political clout of Indian Tamils, who comprise about
7 percent of India's 880 million people.
   In Sri Lanka, Tamils account for 18 percent of the population of
16 million.
   The Tamils, like the majority of Indians, are Hindu. In Sri
Lanka, they claim they were discriminated against by the Sinhalese
Buddhist majority that comprises 75 percent of the population.
   The Tigers and other Tamil guerrilla groups launched their
separatist war in 1983, saying they needed their own homeland to
combat alleged discrimination in jobs, education and efforts to
impose the Sinhalese language on Tamil-speakers.
   Since then, more than 8,500 people have been killed. The majority
of the victims were Sinhalese civilians. More than 600 Indian
soldiers have been killed in ambushes or battles with the Tamil
guerrillas.
</TEXT>
