<FIRST>r a PM-Husband-Guardian     02-08 0582</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Husband-Guardian,0600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man's Guardianship of Pregnant Wife Blocked</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT MILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINEOLA, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anti-abortion activists obtained a court
order temporarily blocking an abortion for a comatose woman just
hours after her haggard husband won a judge's permission to have the
operation performed.
   ``All I want to do is save my wife's life,'' Martin Klein, 34, of
Upper Brookville on Long Island said Tuesday after state judge
Bernard McCaffrey named him guardian of his wife, Nancy, as a
courtroom packed with family members, abortion supporters and
opponents, and reporters looked on.
   Three hours later, anti-abortion activists John Short of
Farmingdale and John Broderick of Syosett won a temporary stay of
the order from Appellate Division Judge Vincent Balletta Jr. despite
objections from the state attorney general's office.
   Short and Broderick, who are seeking to become guardians of Mrs.
Klein and her fetus, and Klein must file papers today with the full
Appellate Division, which is expected to issue a ruling by Friday.
   Mrs. Klein, who is about 17 weeks pregnant, has been in a coma at
North Shore University Hospital since a car accident Dec. 13.
   Her husband sought an abortion after several physicians said it
could help her recovery, but the hospital said it would need a court
order to perform the operation.
   McCaffrey ruled that an abortion was not necessary to save Mrs.
Klein's life, but said the issue was what constituted ``the
constitutional rights of a hospitalized comatose woman who is
approximately 17 weeks pregnant.''
   The judge said that, based on medical testimony and records, Mrs.
Klein is incompetent and a guardian should be appointed.
   He gave Klein permission to authorize any medical procedures that
may be necessary to preserve his wife's life, specifically ruling
that Klein is authorized to approve an abortion.
   ``The responsibilities of the guardian in this instance are
awesome'' because of the woman's extensive brain injury and because
the only type of abortion she could have would involve a very high
risk, McCaffrey said.
   He noted that if Mrs. Klein were competent, she would have the
absolute right to an abortion for any reason up to the 24th week of
pregnancy.
   ``This case is not an abortion case, it's a guardianship case,''
said Elizabeth Bradford of the state attorney general's office.
``Clearly, if Mrs. Klein was given the choice of husband of nine
years versus a stranger ... she would opt for her husband.''
   Klein's attorney, Sidney Schutz, labeled the anti-abortion
activists ``interlopers adding to the problems of the family.''
   McCaffrey had dismissed their petitions last week, agreeing that
neither Broderick nor Short had a standing in the procedure.
   In a two-day hearing last week, five medical experts testified
that pregnancy increased the risks for Mrs. Klein and could threaten
her life. But the Nassau County district attorney produced experts
who testified the pregnancy was not life-threatening.
   Short, founder of the Long Island Right-To-Life Committee,
rejects the possibility that an abortion would improve Mrs. Klein's
condition.
   ``The risk physically is equal to abort the child and carry the
child to term,'' Short argued. ``We're saying nobody addressed the
question of her psychological health. Were she to recover, being
told that her child is alive, psychologically, could only be a
benefit. Telling her that they killed the child, psychologically,
could be a disaster.''
   And if Mrs. Klein should die, Short said, ``why not let the baby
be an extension of Mrs. Klein's life?''
   The Kleins have a 3-year-old daughter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890208-0062 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-08-89 0629EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-SniperAttack     02-08 0374</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sniper Attack,0386</SECOND>
<HEAD>Charges Filed in Juvenile Court in Sniper Attack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PEORIA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A teen-ager armed with an assault rifle and
clad in combat fatigues was arrested on charges of wounding a woman
and her infant son in a sniping attack while they were driving on
the outskirts of this city.
   The teen-ager, who was also armed with a shotgun, scattered
police with semiautomatic gunfire before he was captured Monday
evening about three hours after the attack, police said.
   A squad of about 50 officers using dogs and two helicopters were
involved in the search at a suburban housing subdivision.
   Lynn Fess, 33, was in serious condition Tuesday at St. Francis
Medical Center after undergoing surgery to close a grazing wound to
the head, said Chris Lofgren, a hospital spokesman. Her 14-month-old
son, Adam, was in fair condition with an arm wound.
   At a juvenile court hearing, State's Attorney Kevin Lyons filed
two counts of attempted murder and two counts of armed violence and
aggravated battery and asked that the teen-ager be tried as an adult.
   Circuit Judge M. Peter Ault scheduled a Feb. 16 hearing to review
the case and ordered a psychiatric exam to determine if the youth is
competent to stand trial. His name was not released because he is a
juvenile, Peoria County Sheriff's Sgt. Dan Basfield said.
   ``At this time, we don't know what the motive was or the
reasoning behind it,'' said Sheriff George Shadid.
   ``He obviously has a serious problem to do something like this. I
think he had every intention when he shot at the lady and the baby
of hitting someone,'' Shadid said.
   The suspect, who was wearing combat fatigues when arrested,
attended Richwoods High School, The Peoria Journal-Star reported.
Mrs. Fess was a special education teacher at the school, but school
officials said she did not know the teen-ager.
   Defense attorney Gerard Serritella spoke on behalf of his parents
at the hearing.
   ``The parents are broken-hearted,'' Serritella said. ``All of
their sympathy goes out to the victims.''
   Police said the gunman shot at Mrs. Fess's car from behind a
guardrail along the road. They found seven bullets in her car.
   Another son, Matthew, 5, was in the car but escaped injury.
</TEXT>
