<FIRST>r a PM-PreacherSentencing     02-08 0369</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Preacher Sentencing,0382</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prosecutor Hopes Leyva's Sentence Will Help Heal Emotional Scars
Of Victims</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note contents.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIRK BEVERIDGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALEM, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prosecutor said he hopes the 2{-year prison
sentence a preacher received for sodomizing two teen-agers will help
heal the emotional wounds suffered by the scores of boys the
evangelist molested since the 1960s.
   ``I think the victims kept a lot of things inside for a long
time,'' Roanoke County Assistant Commonwealth's Attorney Randy Leach
said Tuesday after Mario ``Tony'' Leyva's sentencing in Circuit
Court.
   Leyva, who could have been sentenced to 10 years in prison,
received 15 months for each of two counts of child sodomy.
   The 43-year-old, self-ordained Pentecostal preacher from
Columbus, Ga., apologized for lying when he testified in September
that he had not committed any homosexual acts with minors.
   But Judge Kenneth Trabue chastized Leyva, upheld the penalty
recommended by the jury and said he wished he could give the
preacher even more time.
   ``I suppose the thing that troubles me most is somebody of the
cloth, who knows the truth, has openly and flagrantly lied,'' Trabue
said. ``There was an overt effort to poison the jury on your
behalf.''
   Leyva changed his story in October when he agreed to a plea
bargain in a similar federal case, in which he still faces
sentencing. He told the FBI he had molested at least 100 boys since
the 1960s, when he was a preacher in North Carolina.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Jennie Montgomery said Leyva and two
fellow Pentecostal preachers, Rias Edward Morris and Freddie M.
Herring, used Leyva's traveling ministry to gain access to trouble
boys they used for sex.
   The three pleaded guilty in October to federal charges they
shipped boys across state lines to use them in illegal sex acts in
exchange for money and favors.
   Morris, 47, was the organist in Leyva's ministry. Herring, 50,
founded the Lighthouse Assembly in Douglasville, Ga.
   Under their plea bargains, Leyva faces a maximum prison sentence
of 20 years and the other ministers 15 years.
   Leyva and the others, who were not charged in the state case,
have been undergoing psychiatric evaluations at a federal prison in
Butner, N.C.
</TEXT>
