<FIRST>r a PM-ComparableWorth     02-08 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Comparable Worth,0332</SECOND>
<HEAD>Union Says California Underpaying Women Since '30s</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The trial of the nation's largest sex
discrimination salary case began with a state union's charge that
California intentionally began paying women less than men in the
early 1930s and never stopped.
   The state ``explicitly considered sex'' when it overhauled its
civil service classifications in 1930-31, said William Dickens, a
labor economist who was the first witness at the trial Tuesday.
   Dickens, an associate professor of economics at the University of
California at Berkeley, cited a 1930 report recommending the state
``pay somewhat higher for those occupations filled predominantly by
men.''
   Dickens was the leadoff witness for the California State
Employees Association, which is suing the state on behalf of 60,000
to 70,000 past and present female employees.
   Deputy Attorney General Richard Tullis defended the state's wage
system, calling California ``a very progressive state.''
   U.S. District Judge Marilyn Hall Patel, hearing the case without
a jury, is limiting testimony in the first phase of the trial to the
intent and effects of state policies in the 1930s, when the current
wage system is said to have originated.
   The union must prove that when the state's Civil Service
Commission reclassified jobs and pay scales it deliberately set
wages for women at a lower rate than for men.
   It must then prove that that early policy accounts for pay gaps
existing at least through the 1970s.
   Lawyers for the state deny it ever had a policy of intentional
pay discrimination and say any trace of bias was eliminated in a
reorganization of job classifications in 1937-38.
   Dickens said the changes in state pay classifications in 1937-38
were no more than an attempt to ``refine the system,'' while leaving
the basic structure in place.
   State lawyers say damages in the case could run into the billions
of dollars, an estimate the union calls highly inflated.
</TEXT>
