<FIRST>u i PM-Philippines-Marcos     02-08 0551</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Philippines-Marcos,0567</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senator: Marcos Rules Out Deals For Coming Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ferdinand Marcos has ruled out any
deals as the price for coming home and asked President Corazon
Aquino to tell her relatives ``to stop bothering him about money
matters,'' an opposition senator said today.
   Sen. Juan Ponce Enrile said the ailing ex-president made the
statement to Vice President Salvador Laurel in Hawaii last Thursday
and asked that the message be relayed to Mrs. Aquino.
   Laurel had told reporters Saturday that he was carrying secret
messages for Mrs. Aquino from the hospitalized Marcos, who has asked
to return from exile in Hawaii to die in his homeland.
   Mrs. Aquino refused to see Laurel, and he has not disclosed the
messages.
   Enrile, however, said Laurel told him Marcos wanted Mrs. Aquino
``to instruct her relatives not to bother President Marcos about
money matters.'' Enrile said Laurel told him of Marcos' remarks on
Sunday.
   ``As far as I know, according to the vice president, Marcos told
him `I'm not going to make any deals with anybody,''' Enrile told
reporters.
   Last year, Mrs. Aquino's uncle, Rep. Francisco Sumulong, and a
cousin, Rep. Egmidio Tanjuatco, visited the 71-year-old Marcos.
Their visits and that of Laurel prompted speculation Marcos was
prepared to negotiate.
   The Philippine government says Marcos and his associates
embezzled up to $10 billion before Marcos was ousted in a February
1986 civilian-military uprising. Mrs. Aquino has said the government
will not discuss his return until he gives back the money.
   In October, a U.S. grand jury indicted Marcos and his wife Imelda
on racketeering charges for allegedly embezzling more than $100
million and stashing much of it in the United States.
   Mrs. Aquino today said she told Mateo Caparas, chairman of the
Presidential Commission on Good Government, to contact Marcos'
representatives in the United States for a deal on Marcos' return.
   ``But he (Caparas) will not negotiate,'' she told reporters. ``I
will see what they have to offer first of all, and first of all, if
indeed they want to talk, because to this date, we have not received
any letter authorizing certain persons to speak for Mr. Marcos or
Mrs. Marcos.''
   Teodoro Locsin Jr., publisher of the Philippine Daily Globe and
Mrs. Aquino's speechwriter, today wrote that Caparas told U.S.
Justice Department officials he was authorized to negotiate with
Marcos and demanded ``total discretion'' in his talks.
   Locsin said U.S. officials warned Caparas they would cease
cooperation in investigations of Marcos and seize his property in
New York if Manila reached an unacceptable agreement for his return.
The properties, which the Philippine government wants to sell, are
estimated at $300 million.
   Locsin quoted Caparas as saying U.S. officials had threatened to
withhold evidence of Marcos' alleged secret bank accounts received
from the Swiss government.
   Locsin said U.S. Attorney Charles LaBella of New York told
Caparas that U.S. officials could also agree to a deal that would be
unfavorable to Manila.
   Caparas refused to return calls from The Associated Press.
   In Honolulu's St. Francis Medical Center, Marcos remained in
guarded condition connected to a respirator, but a hospital
spokeswoman reported his condition was improving.
   He was admitted Jan. 15 and underwent a tracheotomy to drain
fluid from his lungs. He was hospitalized twice in December for
congestive heart failure.
</TEXT>
