<FIRST>r i PM-SAfrica-Prosecutions     02-08 0287</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SAfrica-Prosecutions,0296</SECOND>
<HEAD>Charges To Be Filed Against White Extremist and Tutu's Son</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government today said it
will prosecute politically sensitive cases involving a
white-supremacist leader, the son of black Archbishop Desmond Tutu
and a white man who harassed the black Anglican clergyman.
   The three cases are not linked directly, and the government
appeared to be trying to show its willingness to act against
suspected offenders across the political spectrum.
   Klaus von Lieres, attorney general for the Johannesburg region,
announced the decisions at a news conference.
   He said Eugene TerreBlanche, leader of the Afrikaner Resistance
Movement, would be charged with malicious damage to property.
TerreBlanche allegedly tried to ram his car through a gate at an
Afrikaner historical monument near Johannesburg in December.
   The attorney general said a charge of criminal injury would be
filed against Willeboer Venter, who allegedly swore at Archbishop
Tutu and threatened to break his neck in June when the
anti-apartheid leader was boarding an airplane at Jan Smuts Airport
outside Johannesburg.
   Tutu's son, Trevor, is to face six charges in connection with
three separate incidents dating back to October, when he allegedly
obstructed a police officer, von Lieres said.
   Trevor Tutu, 32, also will be charged with falsely telling police
at Jan Smuts Airport on Dec. 31 that there might have been a bomb in
his luggage. He also will be charged with malicious damage to
property in an altercation with police when he was arraigned at a
magistrate's court on Jan. 3.
   No trial dates have been set, von Lieres said.
   Under apartheid, the black majority has no vote in national
affairs and whites control the economy and maintain separate
districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
