<FIRST>r a PM-Cyanide-Yogurt     02-08 0336</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cyanide-Yogurt,0346</SECOND>
<HEAD>Comatose Victim Of Cyanide Dies After Removal From Life Support</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VOORHEES, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investigators were still trying to
determine how cyanide got into yogurt eaten by a 17-year-old boy,
who died after spending five weeks in a coma.
   Thomas Lee of Haddonfield died Tuesday at West Jersey
Hospital-Voorhees after he was removed from a respirator, said Leon
Rose, a lawyer for the youth's parents, Frances and Hsin-Yi Lee.
   The FBI has joined local and county officials in investigating
whether the poisoning should be treated as a homicide, suicide or
product-tampering case, although they say the last choice is highly
unlikely.
   ``We are still in the investigation until such time that there is
a determination made that it was not product tampering,'' said FBI
Agent John H. Kundts of the bureau's Philadelphia office. He said
the case would be presented to a grand jury Feb. 15.
   Cyanide was recovered from a Rutgers University laboratory in
Camden, where the boy's father is a renowned biology professor, and
from the family's home, but it remains unknown whether the samples
matched cyanide found in the yogurt.
   Breyers, makers of the yogurt, said it determined the cyanide did
not originate in any of its production facilities.
   The teen-ager had been in critical condition since eating the
black cherry yogurt on his way to school Jan. 3. Doctors had given
him little chance of recovery.
   Rose said the boy's parents, court-appointed guardian Joseph
Kenney and physicians reached a unanimous decision Monday night to
remove the artificial life support.
   ``The medical testimony was clear and convincing ... that there
was no chance of a recovery to a cognitive and sapient state,'' Rose
said.
   Superior Court Judge Paul A. Lowengrub appointed Kenney as
guardian last month when it became evident his family would try to
remove life support.
   Hospital officials and investigators at the Camden County
prosecutor's office declined comment on the case. A family friend
who answered the telephone at the Lee home said the parents were not
home.
</TEXT>
