<FIRST>r a PM-WheelchairDriver     02-08 0260</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wheelchair Driver,0269</SECOND>
<HEAD>Disabled Woman Fights for Easier Acess for the Handicapped</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MELANIE BURNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GLASSBORO, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Monica Himes says she's been urged not to
``rock the boat,'' but she intends fight a $20 traffic citation for
not putting lights on her motorized wheelchair.
   ``It's important for me to stand up for my rights,'' Mrs. Himes
said Tuesday. ``I guess I was just born a fighter.
   Mrs. Himes, 34, filed a complaint against a driver following a
near-collision Dec. 19 involving her wheelchair. She said she was
crossing within the pedestrian crosswalk when a car nearly hit her.
   ``I was well-lit,'' she said. ``I could have been seen.''
   But police issued her a citation for not having lights on her
wheelchair.
   Police Chief Patricia Kunchynski said the citation was a warning
to Mrs. Himes, who has multiple sclerosis, to do something so
vehicles can see her.
   But Mrs. Himes' attorney, Dale Lundquist, said no laws classify a
motorized wheelchair as a motor vehicle.
   A hearing on both complaints is set for March 7. A judge will
also hear a disorderly conduct complaint filed against Mrs. Himes by
an off-duty police officer who claimed she shouted obscenities while
discussing the matter in a store.
   Mrs. Himes, who has fought for six years to make the community
more accessible to the disabled, said her husband, Thomas, who works
for the county, told her, ``We have to live here. Don't rock the
boat.''
   But, she said, ``You can't back down. You gotta do what you gotta
do.''
</TEXT>
