<FIRST>u a PM-BellevueDoctor     02-08 0283</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bellevue Doctor,0293</SECOND>
<HEAD>Murder Suspect Watched Surgery at Bellevue</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man accused of strangling a pregnant doctor in
her Bellevue Hospital office used to wander the halls in surgical
scrubs and went into operating rooms unhindered during surgery, a
newspaper reported today.
   Meanwhile, a Bellevue nurse's aide who police believe Steven
Smith had picked out as his second victim said Smith sweet-talked
her and then hounded her when he learned she had a boyfriend.
   ``He wanted all my time,'' said the aide, Viola Durham. ``I
ignored it. He never threatened me.''
   Smith is charged with raping and murdering pathologist Kathryn
Hinnant on Jan. 7.
   A detective's report filed Monday said Smith told police that
``there was a girl known to him as Viola ... that was his age (who)
could well have been his next victim.'' Ms. Durham said she was
shocked by the report.
   New York Newsday reported today that police believe that Smith
often walked around the hospital in hospital pajamas or surgical
scrubs, ate in the staff cafeteria and slept in various hospital
rooms.
   When he allegedly killed Hinnant, Smith was wearing a white lab
coat over surgical scrubs and had a stethoscope draped around his
neck, police said.
   Several hospital employees told police that Smith apparently was
not asked to leave the operating rooms, Newsday said, citing
unidentified sources.
   Bellevue spokesman Al Palmieri said he doubted the reports.
   ``I think it's unlikely even if he was dressed in surgical greens
with a mask on that he would be allowed to be in an operating room
just standing around,'' he said.
   ``We do have some operating rooms that allow for external
observation; that's a possibility.''
</TEXT>
