<FIRST>r i PM-Iran-WindsOfChange 1stLd-Writethru a0412 02-08 1234</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iran-Winds Of Change, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0412,1267</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iran Moves toward New Freedoms after War with Iraq</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 2 grafs for 9th pvs, ``The progressive...'' to UPDATE with
report of amnesty. Pickup 10th pvs, ``The executions...''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Note Feb. 11 is anniversary of Islamic revolution. An accompanying
story is PM-Iran-Exiles. This story also was sent in advance Jan. 30
as b0278.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Only on rare occasions are Western reporters
allowed to enter Iran. The writer of this dispatch has been there in
the past and now monitors developments in Iran from The AP listening
post in Nicosia, Cyprus.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iranian leaders of all stripes are calling
for greater political and social freedom now that the war with Iraq
appears over and the Islamic revolution reaches its 10th anniversary
Feb. 11.
   As the country prepares to face the challenges of peace after
eight years of war in the Persian Gulf, progressive religious
figures are urging fresh interpretations of the sharia, Islam's
religious laws and cornerstone of Iran's rigid political and social
system.
   Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini, Iran's supreme authority, has thrown
his weight behind the trend.
   In a decree Jan. 4, he stressed the need for Islam to adapt to
the modern world. His decree was seen as one of his most important
pronouncements since the revolution that toppled Shah Mohammad Reza
Pahlavi in 1979.
   He called on the conservative Council of Guardians, which has
repeatedly blocked key economic legislation on the grounds it
violated Islam's tenets, to avoid obscure theological arguments that
will ``drive us to dead ends.''
   Khomeini, 88 years old, was reflecting a groundswell of sentiment
among influential religious and political leaders seeking to move
Iran toward a ``Decade of Dawn.''
   The revolutionary patriarch, who during the war with Iraq
repeatedly appealed to his bickering officials for unity, refused
requests in November that he settle a fierce debate over economic
policy. He urged open discussion.
   He decreed that ``academic argument should be given a high place
in Islam and encouraged, rather than suppressed'' because of
``dogmatic interpretations and authoritarian outlooks.''
   Today, Tehran Radio announced that Khomeini has pardoned an
unspecified number of political prisoners in Iran in a general
amnesty. It said the government determined they ``no longer
constitute a threat to the revolution.''
   However, these progressive moves are taking place at the same
time as a new wave of dissident executions, in which by most
accounts hundreds have died.
   The executions, along with the prospect of a power struggle for
supremacy in the post-Khomeini era and the influence among 50
million Iranians of the deeply entrenched mullahs, or Shiite Moslem
priests, have made many people skeptical about just how far Iran
will progress along a progressive course.
   Travellers from Tehran, the capital, say many Iranians refer to
the next 10 years (the Decade of Dawn to officials) as the ``Decade
of Suffering.''
   Nonetheless, there are clear indications the winds of change are
blowing stronger.
   Freedom of expression and other liberties were widely restricted
during the Persian Gulf war, but with the case-fire restrictions
appear to have been relaxed.
   Hojatoleslam Mohammad Javad Hojati Kermani, a middle-ranking
cleric who has become Iran's most popular newspaper columnist,
recently chided traditionalist mullahs.
   ``In the same way that permitting what God has forbidden is
forbidden, forbidding what God has permitted is also forbidden,'' he
wrote in Tehran's Ettela'at newspaper.
   ``I am puzzled why our religious authorities consider the safe
course to be obsessively guarding the fortress of what has been
forbidden rather than guarding the flower garden of what is indeed
permitted by God.''
   Parliament Speaker Hashemi Rafsanjani, viewed as the government's
leading pragmatist and architect of efforts to open up Iran after a
decade of isolation, noted in a recent speech: ``We still have a lot
of unanswered questions with regard to society.
   ``We have not come forward with clear principles in our foreign
policy ... or in religious matters that vastly differ today from
earlier eras of Islam.''
   After the sacrifices of the war, in which by some estimates 1
million Iranians were killed, Iranians want to enjoy the fruits of
peace.
   Scheherazade Daneshku, a Paris-based Iranian analyst, noted that
leaders like Rafsanjani understand that now ``some of the more
puritanical and uncompromising aspects of Islamic rule will almost
certainly have to be dispensed with.''
   Khomeini's designated successor, Ayatollah Hussein-Ali Montazeri,
who has long urged wider freedoms, told Islamic students last
October: ``Freedom of expression ... is the natural and
constitutional right of every individual.
   ``The officials of this country and the revolution, who
experienced the bitter taste of repression under the monarchy,
should take notice of this and avoid the assumption we no longer
need freedom of expression.''
   Montazeri warned: ``Should we grow intolerant to challenges to
our ideas, these challenges will inevitably turn into bullets.''
   Parliament member Elias Hazrati declared during a debate on
postwar reconstruction and the future shape of society: ``Ten years
after the revolution, we have to bitterly admit that we have not
been successful in developing and reforming the systems we inherited
from the former regime.''
   Cleric Kermani noted in one of his columns: ``There are still
people who refuse to listen to the radio, watch television or
believe that women should not participate in marches and Friday
prayers, let alone Parliament.
   ``Some citizens are still heard complaining about the songs aired
on the radio and TV. They are against women appearing on television
as newscasters, interviewers and actresses and doubt the
advisability of consorting with foreign non-Moslems, infidels,
communists and women who do not wear the chador (cloaklike dress).''
   Khomeini said in a letter Oct.5 to Hojatoleslam Mohammad Hussein
Qadiri, a senior religious scholar at the Qom seminary who
questioned the ayatollah's ruling that chess and musical instruments
were permissible under Islamic law: ``According to your reverence's
interpretation of the hagiological tradition, modern civilization
should be destroyed and people should go back to mud huts or live in
deserts forever.''
   Khomeini urged Qadiri to ``avoid being affected by sanctimonious
and illiterate mullahs'' whom many Iranians criticize for burying
religion in inflexible tenets and medieval interpretations of the
Koran, Islam's holy book.
   Kermani noted that Khomeini's precepts are ``the start of a new
revolution in our deep-rooted ... traditional theology. ... Now is
the time to explicitly say that there must be a transformation, a
revolution in the way that the huge resources of the rich Shiite
theology are being exploited.''
   He said the brand of theology presented by backward-looking
clerics is ``not capable of managing a home or a village, let alone
a country!''
   Mohammad Hashemi, Rafsanjani's brother and head of the state-run
television and radio network, called in a November for greater media
freedom to air grievances and criticism of the government.
   Official action, he added, in an interview published by his
network's Soroush magazine, had prevented his organization from
``doing our duty in reflecting criticisms to the extent that our
mission requires.''
   Soroush also carried an interview with Mahdi Nasari,
editor-in-chief of Kayhan, Iran's largest selling newspaper, in
which he said the press has not done enough to criticize the
revolution's shortcomings.
   ``If a society is deprived of the blessing of criticism and
critical encounters ... throughout the mass media, then it can be
said that it is a society facing gradual death and at the very
least, decline,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
