<FILEID>AP-NR-02-08-89 0907EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Korea     02-08 0472</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Korea,0488</SECOND>
<HEAD>North Demands End to U.S.-South Korea Exercises; More Talks Set</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By M.H. AHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANMUNJOM, Korea, (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   North Korean delegates today demanded a
halt to joint U.S.-South Korean military exercises and told southern
delegates the maneuvers are blocking dialogue between North and
South.
   Delegates from both sides met nearly two hours in an attempt to
set down terms for the first meeting of their prime ministers. They
didn't agree on anything except the date for their next meeting _
March 2.
   The five-member delegations exchanged testy statements over North
Korea's demand for the halt to the annual U.S.-South Korea ``Team
Spirit'' exercises. North Korea says they are ``war preparations.''
   Each side accused the other of blocking progress.
   ``The South Korean side did not show sincerity at today's
meeting. We hope they will come to the next meeting with a sure
answer,'' North Korea's chief delegate, Paik Nam Jun, told reporters.
   South Korea's senior delegate, Song Han-ho, accused North Korea
of being insincere, saying: ``Their demand for a halt to the
exercises seems to be a precondition to dialogue.''
   Paik demanded soon after the meeting opened that the exercises be
halted. ``The exercises, which are heightening tension to an extreme
level and deepening distrust and misunderstanding, must be stopped
immediately and unconditionally.'' he said.
   ``The exercises are an obstacle to dialogue,'' he added.
   The North's official Pyongyang Radio said northern delegates will
boycott preliminary parliamentary talks, originally scheduled
Friday, until the exercises are over.
   The radio, monitored in Tokyo, quoted an unidentified North
Korean spokesman as saying the North wanted the question of stopping
the exercises on the talks' agenda and that holding the talks as
scheduled would be difficult since the exercises have already begun.
   Friday's scheduled talks were aimed at arranging full-scale
North-South parliamentary negotiations on such issues as a
non-aggression pact.
   Today's meeting was called to set the terms for a meeting of the
two nations' prime ministers for the first time since the division
of their land 44 years ago. The prime ministers' talks, if held,
would be the highest-level discussions between the two Koreas.
   The delegates exchanged handshakes with broad smiles before
starting the talks today, but the cordinal mood quickly dissipated.
   The chief South Korean negotiator said the joint exercises,
conducted annually since 1976, were defensive in nature and an
``inappropriate subject'' for discussion at the talks.
   He said the exercises could be modified or stopped if the leaders
of the two Koreas were to meet and resolve their basic differences.
   North Korea said it would not object to training exercises by
South Korean forces but did not want further joint U.S.-South Korea
maneuvers.
   Although there has been no official confirmation, this year's
exercises reportedly began last week. About 200,000 U.S. and South
Korean troops participated in last year's two-month exercise.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
