<FILEID>AP-NR-02-08-89 0928EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-StrandedDancers     02-08 0373</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Stranded Dancers,0383</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stranded Dancers Offer Thank-You Performance in Baltimore</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANE E. ALLEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet ballet troupe struggling to continue
its U.S. debut tour after its financial backers pulled out planned a
free performance tonight to thank those who have donated meals,
gifts and hotel rooms.
   The Donetsk Ballet tour announced Tuesday the young Ukrainian
dancers would take the stage again at the Lyric Opera House, where
they played to five small audiences last week during the first stop
of their 15-city tour.
   U.S. audiences had expected stars from well-known troupes such as
the Kirov Ballet to headline the tour, but when the stars weren't
allowed to leave the Soviet Union, investors withdrew $200,000,
stranding the dancers since last week.
   People touched by the dancers' plight have given them money,
cases of vodka and even a gold pinky ring sent by a man who called
himself ``an adoring ballet fan.''
   Robert M. Pomory, president of the Lyric Opera, said he would pay
the ballet company's hotel bill for two more days _ a contribution
of around $3,000 _ to guarantee the group's stay until Friday.
   ``I'm not going to put these kids on the street,'' said Pomory,
who moved into the hotel to watch over the dancers. ``If I had room
in my house I'd take them all home.''
   After a day of negotiations involving tour producer Jan Urdzik of
California-based Heart of the Art Inc., ``influential people from
New York,'' including producers, will attend tonight's program, he
said.
   In the meantime, the dancers _ most under the age of 25 _ watched
television, toured the city and practiced at the Baltimore School
for the Arts.
   ``Only I want tour to do,'' said Vadim Pisarev, the ballet's top
soloist.
   Pisarev, who celebrated his 24th birthday here, won the 1988
prize for best dancer in the Soviet Union and took home the gold
medal from the prestigious International Ballet Competition in
Jackson, Miss., in 1986.
   Despite his prominence in Soviet dance circles, Pisarev is not
well known to U.S. audiences.
   The dancers had been scheduled to go on to Detroit, Chicago, and
Columbus, Ohio, but their plans are now uncertain because of the
lack of financing.
</TEXT>
