<HEAD>Manson Faces Another Parole Hearing</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Hearing scheduled for 1 p.m. EST; lead prospects uncertain.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN QUENTIN, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Charles Manson, serving a life term
for the 1969 murders of actress Sharon Tate and six others, faced
his seventh parole hearing today at San Quentin Prison.
   At his last hearing, three years ago, Manson told the panel that
he spent his time in prison making scorpion dolls with the power to
``torment,'' and he vowed to pursue violent world revolution if
freed.
   When another hearing was scheduled 10 years ago, Manson refused
to attend. Instead, he sent the parole board Monopoly money along
with a game card that read, ``Advance to Go, Collect $200.''
   Manson, 54, and several members of his so-called ``family'' of
followers were convicted in the Los Angeles slayings of the pregnant
Miss Tate, four of her guests and two other people in a separate
attack the following night.
   Prosecutors contended Manson ordered the killings to trigger a
race war that he believed was foretold in the Beatles' song ``Helter
Skelter.''
