<DOCNO> AP890208-0084 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-08-89 0939EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Housing-Blacks     02-08 0452</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Housing-Blacks,0465</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study: Good Job, Income Doesn't Get Blacks Into Integrated Neighborhoods</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAULINE JELINEK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   No matter what level of income and education they
achieve, blacks aren't as readily accepted in white neighborhoods as
Hispanics and Asians, suggesting the American dream ``is not a
viable option for blacks,'' researchers say.
   Hispanics and Asians move easily into the U.S. mainstream as they
get more schooling, better jobs and higher income, according to the
study by two University of Chicago researchers in today's edition of
Social Science Quarterly.
   The study said figures show that ``integration is possible, even
likely, for all ethnic and racial groups except blacks.''
   It said an Asian or Hispanic who has completed the third grade is
more likely to live in an integrated neighborhood than a black with
a doctorate.
   And an Asian or Hispanic who makes less than $2,500 has a higher
chance of living in an integrated neighborhood than a black who
earns more than $50,000, the researchers found.
   ``The implications of these findings for blacks are troublesome,
given the civil rights legislation of recent decades,'' said Nancy
Denton, a demographer who worked on the study with sociology
professor Douglas Massey.
   ``The American dream of working one's way up is not a viable
option for blacks in the United States, at least in terms of
residence,'' she said in a telephone interview Tuesday.
   ``No matter what their education or occupational achievements ...
blacks are exposed to higher crime rates, less effective educational
systems, higher mortality risks, more dilapidated surroundings and a
poorer socioeconomic environment than whites, simply because of the
persistence of strong barriers to residential integration,'' Denton
said in the study.
   She said the study is the first national one to compare
segregation patterns for three minority groups in the 20
metropolitan areas where each of the three minority groups has the
largest populations. It used data from the 1980 census, the first
with detailed statistics on American's growing Asian population.
   An earlier study on how social and economic status affects
segregation in ``typical'' U.S. neighborhoods found integration
improved modestly from 1970 to 1980.
   Michael White, a researcher at the Urban Institute in Washington
who worked on that study, said researchers came to the conclusion in
the 1950s and '60s that segregation wasn't substantially linked to
social-economic differences.
   He said that further studies, including Denton's, help policy
makers ``understand who is segregated, by how much and what are some
of the reasons for that.''
   The latest study said that although blacks' ability to integrate
rises as their socioeconomic status rises, the difference is
``generally trivial.''
   ``For blacks of all social backgrounds ... integration remains an
elusive goal,'' the study said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
