<FIRST>r i PM-Pope-Lent     02-08 0158</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pope-Lent,0161</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pope Warns Christians of Hyprocrisy as Lent Begins</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II marked Ash Wednesday by
warning Christians of hypocrisy and of falling for ideologies and
fads.
   In today's comments during his general audience, he said Lent, a
period of fasting and penitence before Easter, should bring a
``purification of the heart.''
   John Paul also observed Ash Wednesday, the opening day of Lent,
with an afternoon Mass at the 5th-century Saint Sabina Church.
   The pope said ``purification of the heart'' calls for pure
thoughts, intentions, desires and passions ``so that our external
behavior is really sincere and not the fruit of that hypocrisy and
`human glory' against which Christ was so severe.''
   ``The subtle temptation, for us Christians, is that of appearing
Christian without really being so, stooping to pacts with ideologies
and with the fads of this world,'' the pope told several thousand
pilgrims and tourists in Paul VI Auditorium.
</TEXT>
