<SECOND>PM-TV Purchase,0219</SECOND>
<HEAD>Governor Takes TV Dispute On The Air</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Guy Hunt and the manager of a state
pension fund that bought a TV station took their dispute over the
purchase into the station's studio today, with Hunt saying the deal
is a bad precedent.
   Hunt and David Bronner took seats in a studio of WSFA to be
interviewed on NBC's ``Today Show.''
   Bronner, who handled the $70 million purchase of WSFA for the
Retirement Systems of Alabama, said that it was a wise financial
move and that the TV station would be allowed to report the news
without state interference.
   Hunt said the acquisition of the capital's dominant commercial TV
station by a state-funded agency could set ``a dangerous
precedent,'' opening the door for government entities across the
country to take control of news media properties.
   Bronner, who oversees the investments of the $8 billion pension
fund, said he is considering the purchase of other news media
properties in Alabama and in other states. He said there is a
``great market'' for media acquisitions.
   The purchase is pending before the Federal Communications
Commission.
   Hunt has asked the FCC to delay transfer of the WSFA license
until legal issues in Alabama can be settled in the courts.
