<FIRST>r i PM-PapuaNewGuinea     02-08 0284</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Papua New Guinea,0291</SECOND>
<HEAD>600 Soldiers Smash Windows of Parliament in Wage Dispute</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORT MORESBY, Papua New Guinea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of soldiers today
smashed windows of Parliament and overturned cars after Parliament
granted them their first pay raise since 1975 but gave them less
than they wanted.
   Witnesses said 600 soldiers assaulted bystanders and stole
cameras from journalists covering the demonstration. No figures on
injuries were available.
   ``I was surrounded by a bunch of soldiers who cuffed me about the
head with the branch from a tree,'' Ian Vallance, a Port
Moresby-based correspondent told The Associated Press. ``I was
kicked, I was threatened. It was very scary.''
   The riot occurred after the government agreed to raise soldiers'
pay 72 percent but said the increase would be phased in over three
years. The soldiers, who receive about $50 a week, wanted the full
raise immediately.
   Vallance said in a telephone interview that about half of
Parliament's ground floor windows were broken, and ``windows up to
the fourth floor were smashed with rocks.'' AAP reported earlier
that the troops had not been given a pay increase since independence
in 1975.
   The soldiers defied orders to return to their barracks and police
fired tear gas to disperse them, according to local radio.
   They finally dispersed after Deputy Prime Minister Akoka Doi
promised the government would reconsider the size of the raise.
   Prime Minister Rabbie Namaliu was out of town at the time but was
reported flying back to the capital because of the riot.
   Papua New Guinea, a former U.N. territory administered by
Australia, has about 3.5 million inhabitants. It occupies the east
half of New Guinea island and nearby islands in the southwest
Pacific.
</TEXT>
