<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Moslems     02-08 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Moslems,0300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Controversial Moslem Chief Resigns in Central Asia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leader of the Soviet Union's huge Moslem
population in Central Asia resigned after residents accused him of
not attending prayers, a source reported today.
   Zamalityen Buranov, a teacher at the Islamic seminary in Bukhara,
Uzbekistan, said the religious leader had generated considerable
controversy.
   ``Not everyone respected him,'' Buranov said in a telephone
interview from the seminary, the Mir-Arab Madrasah. ``People don't
like him. They say he doesn't go to prayers.''
   Buranov said the resignation of Shamsuddin Babakhan, the
50-year-old chairman of the Islamic Board of Central Asia and
Kazakhstan, had been demanded at a demonstration on Friday.
   The official news agency Tass reported Saturday that more than
200 Moslems marched from a mosque through the Uzbek capital,
Tashkent, and ``put forth demands concerning questions of their
religious organizations.'' It did not specify the demands.
   Tass reported Tuesday that the ruling body of the Islamic board
had accepted Babakhan's resignation and appointed Mukhammadsadyk
Mamayusupov, 36, to take over his duties temporarily. He currently
is head of the Islamic Institute in Tashkent, Tass said.
   An estimated 45 million to 50 million Moslems live in the Soviet
Union, making them the largest minority after ethnic Russians. Their
number is growing more rapidly than ethnic Russians who hold the
reins of political power.
   The Kremlin has expressed concern that Islamic fundamentalism
across its borders with Afghanistan and Iran could spread to Soviet
Moslems.
   When he ordered Soviet troops into Afghanistan in December 1979,
Soviet President Leonid I. Brezhnev said he wanted to counter what
he described as Western efforts to create a foyer of Moslem
fundamentalism at the Soviet Union's doorstep.
   The Soviet troop withdrawl from Afghanistan is nearly complete.
</TEXT>
