<FIRST>u i PM-Israel 3rdLd-Writethru a0540 02-08 0697</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0540,0716</SECOND>
<HEAD>Palestinian Reported Killed in Prison Riot; Two More Die of Injuries</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 1 graf after 7th graf pvs, ``They said...'' to UPDATE
with riot over. Pickup 8th pvs, ``In the...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONI RABIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least one Palestinian prisoner was killed and
14 were injured today when army guards fired tear gas, plastic
bullets and live ammunition to quell a riot in a military prison,
army sources said.
   A Palestinian teen-ager was reported shot to death today in the
occupied lands, and a Palestinian died of injuries suffered earlier
in the uprising.
   Israeli government and military officials rejected the
conclusions of a U.S. State Department report alleging substantial
human rights violations and said the report ignored the context of
the uprising.
   The U.S. report, released Tuesday, says methods used by the army
to halt the 14-month revolt have resulted in ``many avoidable deaths
and injuries.''
   Army sources, who insisted on anonymity, said the unrest at the
military prison in Megiddo, in northern Israel, began outside when
visiting relatives went on a rampage, raising Palestinian flags and
stoning soldiers' parked cars.
   When guards suspended visiting hours, inmates began rioting, the
sources said. ``As prisoners returned to cells, they stirred up
others and a serious riot started inside the cells, which is still
continuing,'' the sources said.
   They said military guards fired tear gas and plastic bullets to
try to end the rioting. When that failed, the guards opened fire
with live ammunition, they said, resulting in the death and injuries.
   An army official later said the riot was brought under control
and an investigation was begun.
   In the West Bank village of Kabatiya, Arab hospital officials
said 16-year-old Jamal Salim Zakarni died after being shot in the
stomach during a clash with troops. A military spokeswoman said she
was checking the report.
   The army confirmed the death of 20-year-old Akram Abu Nahla, a
resident of the Rafah refugee camp in the Gaza Strip who died in a
Tel Aviv hospital.
   A military spokeswoman said the circumstances of the death were
not clear. A Gaza City reporter said Abu Nahla was shot in the head
with a plastic bullet Tuesday during a demonstration.
   The three deaths raised to 377 the number of Palestinians killed
since the uprising began Dec. 7, 1987. Fifteen Israelis have died.
   ``In spite of the constant provocations, the Israel Defense Force
scrupulously maintains moral norms and human rights, and treats any
exceptions with utmost severity,'' the Foreign Ministry said in
reponse to the State Department's annual report on human rights
worldwide.
   ``The report does not take into consideration the overall context
of the events and continuing provocations. The extreme elements ...
directing the events use violence meant to be lethal,'' the
statement said.
   The report alleged that Israel's response to the uprising ``led
to a substantial increase in human rights violations.''
   ``Soldiers frequently used gunfire in situations that did not
present mortal danger to troops, causing many avoidable deaths and
injuries,'' it said.
   It also said troops often arrest Palestinians without warrants
and demolish houses of people suspected, but not convicted, of
anti-Israeli violence.
   Yossi Sarid, a Parliament member of the liberal Citizens Rights
Movement, said the report was generally accurate.
   ``I am so sorry that in order to see our face we need a mirror
held from so far away,'' he said on Israel radio.
   Jonathan Kuttab, co-founder of the human rights monitoring group
Al Haq-Law in the Service of Man, said he hoped the U.S. government
would reassess its $3 billion annual aid to Israel in light of the
findings. ``It's a matter of American dollars not going to a country
that systematically violates human rights,'' said Kuttab, a
Palestinian-American lawyer.
   But the military chief prosecutor, Brig. Gen. Amnon Strashnov,
told Israeli Television the report was ``exaggerated and unjust.''
   Strashnov said that of 21,000 Palestinians arrested since the
start of the uprising, 8,000 have been indicted. Of those, 4,300
have been been convicted and 200 acquitted, Strashnov said. Others
were awaiting trial, he said.
   He said about 50 Israeli soldiers have been tried or are facing
prosecution for violating army orders.
</TEXT>
