<FIRST>r i PM-Lebanon-Israel     02-08 0280</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon-Israel,0289</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israel and Allied Militiamen Ring South Lebanon Village</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli troops and allied militiamen
surrounded a south Lebanon village today and deprived its Moslem
inhabitants of food for refusing to cooperate with the
Israeli-sponsored local administration, a U.N. source said.
   The source said armored personnel carriers, troops and militiamen
of the South Lebanon Army besieged Shibaa, in Israel's
self-proclaimed ``security zone,'' at 6 a.m.
   The source from the U.N. peacekeeping force, who demanded
anonymity, said: ``They are stopping cars and trucks carrying food''
and preventing them from entering the village.
   About 7,000 people, most of them Sunni Moslems, live in Shibaa.
   The nine-nation, 5,800-man U.N. Interim Force in Lebanon polices
a buffer that overalps with the security zone, which Israel set up
in 1985 after withdrawing the bulk of its army from Lebanon. The
security zone is designed to prevent raids into Israel by
Lebanese-based guerrillas.
   Shibaa is in the Norwegian battalion's zone of operations.
   A Norwegian officer, who refused to give his name, said 12
members of his battalion were dispatched to the village to ``study
the condition of the people and see what we can do to help.''
   The other UNIFIL source said the peacekeepers' humanitarian
officer, Col. Sepeeo Elva of Finland, flew by helicopter to Shibaa
from UNIFIL headquarters in the border town of Naqoura.
   Israeli troops and South Lebanon Army militia expelled 40
Lebanese from Shibaa last month for refusing to cooperate with local
administration, which Israel set up to handle day-to-day affairs in
the absence of government authority in the security belt.
   At least 30 others have been deported this year from other
Lebanese villages in the security zone.
</TEXT>
