<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--ReturnLanding     02-08 0139</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Return Landing,0143</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jet Makes Quick Return After Engine Cover Falls Off</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A New York-bound jet with 269 people aboard
lost an engine cover in flight and returned to Los Angeles as a
precaution, Pan Am said.
   ``There was no impact on safety whatsoever,'' Pan Am spokesman
Alan Loflin said of the Boeing 747 that left Los Angeles
International Airport on Tuesday.
   The detachable engine cover, or cowling, dented the landing gear
door and caused minor damage to the underside of the wing before
falling onto the runway, he said. Crew members were informed by
passengers who were looking out the windows, he said.
   ``Cowling separating from an engine isn't an everyday occurrence,
but it's not uncommon,'' Loflin said. ``It doesn't affect the way it
flies.''
   The cause of the mishap was under investigation.
</TEXT>
