<FIRST>r a PM-TurkeyTrot     02-08 0312</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Turkey Trot,0321</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tame Turkeys Perch on Luxury Cars, Chase Away Bird Feeders</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOURNE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Turkeys trotting into traffic and chasing
humans near Plymouth Rock are giving state officials problems the
Pilgrims never dreamed of.
   Wildlife workers trying to restore the wild turkey population
that has been a part of state lore since the first Thanksgiving say
tame turkeys are becoming a nuisance in the suburbs and threaten to
dilute the wild breeding stock.
   ``One chased an old lady at a bird feeder. Some others got onto
Route 128 and almost caused an automobile accident,'' James Cardoza,
head of the state's wild turkey restoration project, said Tuesday.
   Richard Turner said he received a complaint from the owner of a
Mercedes who found a turkey trotting over the hood and roof of his
expensive car.
   Turner said the birds are apparently pen-raised wild turkeys that
have been freed and don't have the wily instincts of their wild
counterparts.
   Although it is illegal, chicks are sometimes sold at county fairs
and ``unsupecting people have bought them thinking it would be nice
to have some wild turkeys in their yard,'' Turner said.
   The problem, according to the biologists, is that the pen-reared
turkeys could breed with the wild turkeys the state is trying to
reintroduce to areas south of Boston.
   In other words, they say, the wild turkeys could become just as
dumb as the tame turkeys.
   Cardoza estimated that the population of tame turkeys on the
loose was less than 50.
   The state's wild turkey restoration effort began in 1972 with the
release in the Berkshires of a few pairs of wild birds captured in
New York. Since then, the number of wild turkeys in the state's
western mountains has grown to about 5,000.
   For the past nine years, the birds have been numerous enough in
some areas to allow hunting.
</TEXT>
