<FIRST>r a PM-Powell     02-08 0220</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Powell,0226</SECOND>
<HEAD>Retired Justice Develops Pneumonia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Retired Supreme Court Justice Lewis F.
Powell Jr. has developed pneumonia and will remain hospitalized
several more days, a medical center spokeswoman said today.
   The 81-year-old Powell, whose pneumonia was discovered through
chest X-rays and a low-grade fever late Tuesday, is being treated
with antibiotics and remains in good condition with no respiratory
distress, said Cindy Hamilton, a Baptist Medical Center spokeswoman.
   ``The new findings do not change his excellent prognosis or imply
any deterioration. Rather, they are part of an evolutionary
progression in a respiratory illness,'' said Dr. Joel Schrank, chief
of cardiology and Powell's physician.
   The justice, who was in Jacksonville as a member of a panel of
the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, was taken to the hospital
Monday after becoming dizzy.
   Powell passed a second day in the hospital Tuesday walking the
halls, taking phone calls and undergoing a battery of tests. Ms.
Hamilton described him as ``our most popular patient.''
   Powell retired from the high court in 1987, citing health
concerns as one reason. He had suffered from prostate cancer. He has
since participated in a number of cases for the Richmond-based 4th
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals.
   He was nominated to the court by President Nixon in 1971,
replacing Hugo L. Black.
 
</TEXT>
