<FIRST>r p PM-ChicagoMayoral     02-08 0546</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chicago Mayoral,0560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: RETRANSMITTING to fix category code.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Far Behind, Challenger Seeks to Light Fire In Chicago's Mayoral Race</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Eugene Sawyer promised to make the debate a
``hot time'' for front-runner Richard M. Daley, but it was an
underdog who tried to light a fire under a mayoral campaign that has
been anything but sizzling.
   Liberal Alderman Larry Bloom needled both his foes as they
squabbled about Sawyer's campaign advertisements. Bloom, a
long-shot, also questioned their independence and said he was the
only candidate who could unify the city.
   ``People say, `White people are voting for Daley because's he's
white ... black people are voting for Sawyer because they think he's
black,''' said Bloom, who is white but represents a predominantly
black ward.
   ``They do not think I'm black, Larry,'' Sawyer retorted. ``They
know I'm black.''
   Sawyer's quick reply earned laughter and loud applause from the
250 people in the audience at public television station WTTW
Tuesday. It was the first and only debate scheduled before the Feb.
28 Democratic primary.
   Polls show Daley, the Cook County state's attorney and son of the
late mayor, holding a commanding lead of 50 percent to 30 percent
for Sawyer and 10 percent for Bloom, with 10 percent undecided.
   When a questioner said Sawyer's ads ``characterized Richard Daley
as dumb,'' and asked whether they were the acts of a desperate
candidate, the mayor denied the suggestion.
   ``The characterization that you make is absolutely untrue. I did
not say that, the commercials did not say that. ... Those
commercials were designed to let people know that he has not been
out (in the communities), that he has not taken the opportunity to
discuss issues,'' Sawyer said.
   Daley said the ads are ``very sad to see. I think people are sick
and tired of this (kind of personal attack) all over the city.''
   Bloom, who carries a toy duck to appearances to dramatize his
claim that Daley is ``ducking'' chances to appear before the same
crowds, interjected with some humor.
   ``Well I've had lots of problems in this campaign. I've had
problems getting noticed by the press ... but there is one problem I
haven't had and that is how to spend money on commercials. I don't
have enough money to put them on.''
   Bloom went on the offensive throughout the 90-minute forum. He
suggested Sawyer was beholden to a City Council clique of
anti-reform aldermen who elected him mayor after Harold Washington's
sudden death of a heart attack 15 months ago, and Daley was beholden
to individuals and companies who have lined his war chest with
contributions of up to $100,000.
   He also said Daley lacked the managerial skills and the ability
to heal racial wounds that the next mayor needs.
   ``Yes, Richie, you could muddle through a term as mayor, just as
Gene has muddled through the past year,'' he said. ``But that's not
good enough.''
   Observers generally agreed, however, that Daley emerged without
serious damage and would be able to maintain a conservative campaign
strategy aimed at protecting his lead.
   ``Bloom was the clear-cut winner,'' said veteran political
analyst Tom Roesser, ``but he overdid it. ... He didn't have to wrap
the kitchen sink around him.''
</TEXT>
