<FILEID>AP-NR-02-08-89 1213EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r k BC-EditorialRdp 3Takes   02-08 0734</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Editorial Rdp, 3 Takes,0771</SECOND>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are excerpts from recent editorials in newspapers throughout
the nation.
   Feb. 7
   The Clarion-Ledger, Jackson, Miss., on the S&amp;L crisis:
   The Bush administration's trial balloon to charge depositors fees
to bail out the faltering savings and loan industry has been
properly shot down.
   However, President Bush's new idea might just fly. The new plan
calls for borrowing, in the form of bonds, to finance the bail out
and repaying the bonds with increased insurance payments from banks
and S&amp;L's.
   Although consumers will help pay eventually in such things as
reduced interest rates, requiring substantial industry payment is
much fairer than a depositor's tax.
   The president also recommended changes in the federal supervision
of the savings and loan industry, and said he would recommend
increased Justice Department investigation of alleged wrongdoing in
faild thrifts.
   The Bush plan is as painless as could be expected and appears to
have industry support.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Feb. 4
   Kennebec Journal, Augusta, Maine, on the S&amp;L crisis:
   There has been so much nonsense in recent days about the savings
and loan crisis that it was good to hear a bit of sense somewhere on
Capitol Hill.
   The nation's 350 insolvent S&amp;Ls, reports the General Accounting
OFfice, should be closed quickly. ``These institutions must be
isolated from the rest of the industry to prevent them from
competing with healthy institutions,'' said comptroller general
Charles Bowsher.
   Bowsher is right on the money. In the present deregulated market,
failing S&amp;Ls are free to continue seeking deposits, paying
above-market rates on money which, sooner or later, will have to be
repaid by the federal government. It's a classic case of throwing
good money after bad. ...
   The 350 failed S&amp;Ls haven't been closed already because there's
no money to pay depositors. Congress and the outgoing Reagan
administration kept postponing the day of reckoning.
   It has now arrived, and one part of the solution, closing all
insolvent S&amp;Ls, is on the table. It doesn't make coming up with the
money any easier, but shows that the longer we wait, the more
painful the bill.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Feb. 6
   The Flint (Mich.) Journal on the number of elected officials:
   The U.S. Census Bureau says there were 504,404 elected officials
in the nation's 83,237 governments in 1987 (its latest figures).
   If you have trouble falling asleep, try counting these people
instead of sheep. At one per second, it could take you 140 hours, or
nearly six days around the clock, just to dispose of the
officeholders.
   Or you could simply decide to stay awake worrying about all your
money they're spending.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Feb. 4
   Houston Chronicle on President Bush's trip to South Korea:
   President Bush has scheduled a visit of several hours in Seoul,
South Korea, later this month. He is likely to get an earful.
   Government and business in South Korea are worried about the
effects of the new trade legislation that could punish the country
for unfair trade practices.
   There is some disappointment in Korean circles over Bush's choice
of Donald Gregg, a former CIA officer who was Bush's national
security adviser as vice president, as ambassador to Seoul.
   There will be efforts to dispel lingering doubts about the
stability of the South Korean government.
   And there will be the noisy radical students who are
anti-government and anti-American.
   Bush might well have postponed his visit (until) a later date.
One thing is certain: He will have to be very careful about what he
says during the Seoul stopover.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Feb. 7
   Tulsa (Okla.) World on the Sino-Soviet summit:
   There was a time when the very thought of renewed relations
between China and the Soviet Union would have scared the daylights
out of Americans. How times change.
   Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev will soon visit China, the
first Russian leader to do so since Nikita Khrushchev met Mao
Tse-tung in 1959. And most Americans aren't greatly concerned.
   The limited renewal of relations between these two giants cannot
be dismissed by American strategic planners, of course.
   But it may even produce some advantages for the free world. It
could shore up Russian confidence in Gorbachev and strengthen his
hand in his reform efforts.
   Stable relations between China and Russia _ once seen as a danger
to the West _ will now be cautiously welcomed by most of the world.
Stability is a highly prized commodity these days.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
