<FILEID>AP-NR-02-08-89 1231EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-APArts:Beatles 1stAdd   02-08 0446</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AP Arts: Beatles, 1st Add,0449</SECOND>
<HEAD>NEW YORK _ ``Ed Sullivan.''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The CBS press release heralding the Beatles' first appearance in
the United States was, in retrospect low-keyed. It identified them
as ``The Beatles of London'' _ a ``wildly popular quartet of English
recording stars.'' They were billed on the show with the comedy team
of Mitzi McCall and Charlie Brill, impressionist Frank Gorshin, a
tumbling act called the four Fays and 37 members of the cast from
the Broadway musical, ``Oliver.''
   Sullivan, more animated than usual, handled the squealing
audience as a father would a hyperactive child. He gently shushed
them and made the girls promise to stay in their seats. He told the
audience Elvis Presley had sent a wire wishing the Beatles ``a
tremendous success'' in our country, introduced a commercial for
Aero Shave and then swept his arm through the air as the curtain
parted.
   There was Paul, 21, wide-eyed and boyish, feverishly working the
bass guitar and singing ``All My Loving'' at one microphone. George,
20, was on lead guitar. John, 23, on rhythm guitar, harmonized at
another microphone. Ringo, 23, sat high above them on a platform,
pounding out beats on the drums.
   Paul soloed on ``Til There Was You'' from the Broadway show,
``The Music Man.'' Later, after a magician did card tricks and
Georgia Brown sang songs from ``Oliver,'' the Beatles returned with
the Lennon-McCartney song, ``She Loves You.''
   They were fresh and school boy neat in their Edwardian jackets,
shirts and ties. Their hair, considered outrageously long at the
time, fell in agreeable bangs across their foreheads and stopped
somewhere mid-neck. The Beatle hair style eventually became as
conservative as a crewcut.
   After the Sullivan show, the Beatles played the Washington
Coliseum in Washington, D.C. On Feb. 12, they played Carnegie Hall,
where fans drowned their music in screams.
   Three years later, the Beatles began to show signs of weariness
and drifting apart. Exhausted from years of concert touring,
McCartney and Lennon had each done some independent film work;
Lennon met his future wife, Yoko Ono, in a London art gallery in
1967, around the time they recorded ``Sgt. Pepper.'' Harrison went
off to India to study sitar under Ravi Shankar. Two months after
``Sgt. Pepper'' was released, Brian Epstein, the Beatles' manager
and stabilizing influence, died. With him went much of the spirit
that had held the group together.
   In 1970, a year after the critically acclaimed ``Abbey Road'' was
released, McCartney came out with a solo LP and a self-interview
critical of the other Beatles. The LP and movie, ``Let It Be,'' came
out and by the end of the year, the group dissolved.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890208-0111 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-08-89 1232EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-GlazeTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0517 02-08 0265</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Glaze Trial, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0517,0267</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Deliberates In Triple Murder Case</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with jury resuming deliberations. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury resumed deliberations today in the case
against a drifter accused of murdering and sexually mutilating three
American Indian women.
   The jurors received the case Tuesday after a prosecutor argued
that Billy Glaze was still savoring the ``ghoulish'' slayings and a
defense attorney charged that Glaze had been victimized by publicity
and vindictive witnesses.
   Glaze, 45, is charged with murdering Kathleen Bullman, 19;
Angeline Whitebird-Sweet, 27, and Angela Green, 26, in 1986 and 1987
in Minneapolis. If convicted, he faces a mandatory sentence of life
in prison. Minnesota has no death penalty.
   Prosecutor Pete Connors said in closing arguments that Glaze, who
pretended to be an Indian, ``hated women and he particularly hated
Indian women.''
   ``He had a fury in his gut. He wanted to hurt them and hurt them
badly and he wanted to kill them and to have them die in anguish,''
Connors said. ``He killed these women in an unbelievably ghoulish
fashion and he's sitting in jail enjoying it.''
   Defense attorney Michael Colich characterized Glaze as a
non-violent drifter who called attention to himself by saying
despicable things about women.
   He said police were not thorough in their investigation of other
suspects because of public pressure to solve the killings.
   ``Not one piece of evidence points to Billy Glaze, but because he
has a bad mouth and because he left town they think he did it,''
Colich said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890208-0112 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-08-89 1232EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-People-Waters     02-08 0259</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-People-Waters,0268</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Hairspray' Filmmaker Gives Collection to University</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIDDLETOWN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Director John Waters, who resurrected
1960s crazes in ``Hairspray'' and scratch-and-sniff cards in
``Polyester,'' is giving his scripts, scrapbooks, costumes and other
memorabilia to Wesleyan University.
   Waters joins other film greats, including Clint Eastwood, Frank
Crapra, Ingrid Bergman and Elia Kazan, who have donated their papers
to the school's Cinema Archives.
   ``We consider Waters a major American artist,'' said Jeanine
Basinger, archives curator and a professor of film studies at
Wesleyan.
   ``It's a massive collection,'' she said of Waters' donation.
``And because he is an active filmmaker, it will continue to come to
us over the years. It will be the most complete collection of a
filmmaker's work ever.''
   Waters, who once described his movies as ``comedies for a special
audience who think they've seen everything,'' has attained cult
status as a quirky, campy and sometimes scatological director.
   Many of his films featured the outrageous female impersonator
Divine, who died last year.
   Waters, 42, achieved mainstream success last year with the comedy
``Hairspray.''
   ``As (Jean) Cocteau said about America, `First you shock them,
and then they put you in a museum,' so that's what we're doing,''
said Basinger.
   Waters made his first movie, ``Hag in a Black Leather Jacket,''
in 1964. His first film to attract national attention was 1972's
``Pink Flamingos,'' which the Museum of Modern Art selected as part
of its salute to American humor in 1976.
   He followed that film with ``Female Trouble'' in 1974,
``Desperate Living'' in 1978 and ``Polyester'' in 1981.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
