<HEAD>Baker Encouraged by Talks with West German Minister on Export Controls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III was
pleased with his talks Wednesday with West German Chancellery
Minister Wolfgang Schauble on controlling the export of components
for nuclear and chemical weapons, the State Department said.
   Baker met with Schauble, who handles special tasks for the
chancellor's office, as part of regularly scheduled talks between
the two allies, said department spokesman Charles Redman.
   The main topic of conversation was the enhancement of West
Germany's export controls, Redman added.
   ``Secretary Baker was encouraged by what he heard,'' Redman said.
   The United States has been pressing West Germany to crack down on
firms selling components that can be used to make nuclear and
chemical weapons, in the wake of reports that West German companies
sold such items to Libya, India, Iraq and Iran.
   Baker met last week with West German Economics Minister Helmut
Haussman on the same subject.
