<FIRST>r w AM-Mitchell-Bush     02-08 0434</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mitchell-Bush,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush-Budget, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Mitchell To Bush: `Time For Deeds To Back Up Words'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell,
speaking on the eve of President Bush's budget address to Congress,
said Wednesday it was time for Bush to deliver ``deeds to match
words'' and promised bipartisan cooperation with the White House.
   Mitchell, in a speech to a United Auto Workers conference,
rattled off a list of Bush campaign proposals on issues, including
the environment, education and child care, and said he would be
listening closely when the president addresses a joint session.
   ``We look forward to his proposals, beginning (Thursday) night,
as to how we should give meaning to those words,'' the Maine
Democrat said. ``These policies, like all others, must begin with
words. But they cannot end with words.
   ``There must be deeds to match words, action to fulfill
intention,'' Mitchell continued. ``We're going to hold the president
accountable to his words and we want to work with him. ... Working
together we can do much.''
   Mitchell also promised passage of legislation to increase the
minimum wage, one of his top legislative priorities as well as
labor's.
   ``If I don't do anything else as majority leader of the United
States Senate, I'm going to see that the minimum wage is increased
this year as it should be,'' he said to a standing ovation.
   The minimum wage, which has been $3.35 an hour since 1981, would
increase 40 cents an hour to $4.55 at the end of three years under
Senate legislation supported by Mitchell. After that, the
legislation calls for the minimum wage to be indexed annually to 50
percent of the average hourly income of U.S. workers.
   Mitchell delivered a lengthy defense of the Democratic Party,
traditionally backed by organized labor, and said Bush's call for a
``kinder, gentler'' America included ideas ``for which we have
worked as Democrats for a half century.''
   But, in an unusual statement nonetheless met with applause,
Mitchell said many of those those who have benefitted from
Democrat-sponsored programs, including union members, have abandoned
the party.
   ``There's a lot of analysis about why Democratic candidates have
lost five out of (the last) six presidential elections,'' Mitchell
said. ``And as a member of the Democratic leadership I say we in the
party share a major portion of the responsibility. But I also say to
you that there are a lot, too many, of your members who have
forgotten where they came from, who because of Democrats began to
live like Republicans and then started voting that way.''
</TEXT>
