<FIRST>r w AM-Tower-Senators     02-08 0463</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tower-Senators,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Tower, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Retransmitting a0625 to CORRECT cycle designator on ``with''
line</HEAD>
<HEAD>Tower's Clients Donated to Several Armed Services Members</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Several members of the Senate Armed Services
Committee received thousands of dollars in campaign contributions
from the same defense contracting firms that hired Defense
Secretary-designate John Tower to lobby for them, records show.
   Tower, a former Republican senator from Texas who headed the
armed services panel until his retirement in 1984, has said he
received over $1 million in a three-year period from firms including
Rockwell International, Martin Marietta Corp., LTV Aerospace and
Defense Co., and Textron Corp.
   Members of the panel, which has put off a vote on Tower's
nomination, have raised questions about whether Tower could remain
impartial at the Pentagon because of his ties to defense contractors.
   Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., the committee chairman, said Wednesday that
the most recent delay in the confirmation process stemmed from the
FBI's investigation into new allegations of a ``financial nature''
involving the nominee.
   Records on file at the Federal Election Commission show that in
1987 and 1988 the political action committees of at least four
defense firms that hired Tower also contributed to panel members.
   Altogether, the PACs gave to more than 100 presidential,
senatorial and congressional candidates. Federal election law
prohibits companies from giving directly to campaigns, but PACs may
contribute up to $10,000 per election cycle to a candidate.
   Sen. Jeff Bingaman, a Democrat who won re-election in New Mexico
last November, was the armed services committee member receiving the
most from the four PACs. He received a total of $18,000, including
the largest single contribution, $10,000 from Textron.
   Other big receivers on the committee were Sens. Pete Wilson,
R-Calif., who got $15,800 from the four firms, and Malcolm Wallop,
R-Wyo., who received $15,700. Wallop is a new member of the panel.
Both men were re-elected last year.
   Sen. Albert Gore, D-Tenn., an armed services committee member who
unsuccessfully sought the Democratic presidential nomination last
year, received $2,000 from LTV and $3,000 from Textron.
   Another member up for re-election, Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass.,
accepted $1,000 from LTV Aerospace, the records show.
   Two senators who do not face re-election until 1992 received
contributions from the defense companies. Sen. Richard Shelby,
D-Ala., accepted $3,000 from Textron, and $1,000 each from LTV
Aerospace and Martin Marietta.
   And Sen. Timothy Wirth, D-Colo., took $2,500 from Textron, and
$1,000 each from Martin Marietta and LTV.
   The PAC set up by LTV Aerospace gave money to 146 candidates,
including $5,000 to President Bush, and spent a total of $173,284.
   Rockwell International's PAC spent about $378,000 on 286
candidates, while Martin Marietta gave $248,000 to 270 candidates,
and Textron contributed roughly $400,000 to 237 candidates.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
