<FIRST>r i AM-China-Art     02-08 0277</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Art,0284</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Release Pair Held in Art Gallery Shooting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police on Wednesday released an artist after
holding her three days for shooting a BB gun at her own sculpture in
an exhibition of avant-garde art, the official Xinhua News Agency
said.
   The exhibit, the largest modern art show in communist China's
40-year history, was closed by police a few hours after it opened
Sunday when Xiao Lu opened fire at her model of a phone booth.
   Xinhua said the Beijing Public Security Bureau ordered Ms. Xiao
and her boyfriend, Tang Songmang, detained five days as punishment
for disturbing public order. Tang, 28, tried to help Ms. Xiao, 25,
smuggle her gun from the China Art Gallery, Xinhua said.
   However, the report said police decided to release them after
three days as a concession in honor of the Lunar New Year holiday,
called Spring Festival. Monday began the new Year of the Snake, but
the official holiday lasts through Wednesday.
   Xinhua said Ms. Xiao acknowledged shooting at her sculpture, but
said it was because she thought it was imperfect and needed
``destructive art.''
   An exhibition organizer, Fei Dawei, said Monday it was Tang who
actually fired at the work. He said they ``were attempting to negate
modern civilization'' and called the action ``performance art.''
Authorities had banned performance art from the show in advance,
saying it might cause chaos.
   Fei said the show might reopen Friday. Xinhua did not comment on
the show's fate.
   Xinhua said Chinese regulations allow detention of up to 15 days
for disturbing public order. Police can impose detention sentences
without trial or opportunity for the accused to appeal.
</TEXT>
