<FILEID>AP-NR-02-08-89 1351EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Parkinson's     02-08 0380</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Parkinson's,0391</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study Shows Modest Improvement From Parkinson's Disease Operation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An experimental brain operation has produced
moderate improvement for some victims of Parkinson's disease, but
surgeons have failed to match dramatic results reported by a Mexican
doctor, a researcher said.
   ``All the patients in our group have said they felt it was
worthwhile, but in no case has it achieved what they hoped it
would,'' said Dr. Christopher G. Goetz of Rush-Presbyterian-St.
Luke's Medical Center in Chicago.
   The operation involves removing tissue from patients' adrenal
glands and transplanting it in their brains. The goal is to provide
the victims' brains with a source of dopamine, an essential
message-carrying chemical that they lack.
   The operation was first reported two years ago by Dr. Ignacio
Madrazo and colleagues at the National Autonomous University of
Mexico and the social security hospital system in Mexico City. They
reported dramatic improvement in two patients, and since then,
surgeons at many medical centers have tried to duplicate their
results.
   ``What came out originally was the sense that this was a
miracle,'' Goetz said. ``This is no miracle.''
   His report combined the results of surgery on 19 patients at his
hospital and at the University of South Florida and the University
of Kansas. The results were published in Thursday's New England
Journal of Medicine.
   Parkinson's disease results from destruction of a part of the
brain called the nigral tissue, which makes dopamine. The adrenal
glands, which lie above the kidneys, also produce this substance.
   Between 500,000 and 1 million Americans, including 2 percent of
everyone over 70, have Parkinson's. They often suffer tremors and
have trouble controlling their movements.
   Drugs can control the disease, but as the illness worsens, the
medicines lose their effectiveness and often don't work for hours at
a time.
   Before the surgery, the patients' drugs worked about half the
time. Afterward, this increased to three-quarters of the time.
   While the drugs are working, the patients are able to move about
and care for themselves with little assistance, although they still
clearly show the effects of the disease. When the drugs are not
effective, they are confined to wheelchairs.
   ``Despite cautious optimism, we conclude that the widespread use
of this procedure outside of research centers is premature,'' the
researchers wrote.
</TEXT>
