<HEAD>Senator Suggests the Stocks for Corrupt S&amp;L Owners</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Barbara Mikulski, D-Md., thinks owners of
some troubled savings and loan associations deserve more than a
taxpayer bailout. Like some time in the public stocks, or at least
tar-and-feathering.
   ``An outrageous fraud has been perpetrated on American savers by
a select group of what I call go-go boys,'' Ms. Mikulski said in a
Senate speech Wednesday.
   ``These go-go boys used deposits to bankroll lavish lifestyles
and invest in crooked deals, and I think they must be punished. ...''
   Ms. Mikulski, whose state has had several S&amp;L failures, chairs
the Senate Appropriations subcommittee that likely would have a hand
in developing a bailout plan. On Tuesday, federal regulators took
control of the insolvent Baltimore Federal Financial, one of the
state's largest thrifts.
   ``Before we approve a single cent,'' to bail out insolvent S&amp;Ls,
she said, ``we need to mandate that there are real reforms and that
this will not happen again.
   ``I'd like to put them in a stock. ... I'd like everybody that's
got a CD (certificate of deposit) or $100 in one of these bad S&amp;Ls
to go up _ whether it's a senior citizen who's saved for his
daughter's or son's college education _ I'd like them to get
together and take a whack at some of them,'' she said.
   ``I would like, right today, for the appropriate federal
authorities to go out there and confiscate the personal assets of
those who are under investigation,'' she said. ``Let's confiscate
their Maseratis. Let's confiscate their yachts.''
   Some savings institutions are in trouble because they were caught
in a squeeze when they had to pay high interest rates to deposits to
remain competitive but were stuck with low-rate, long-term
mortgages, Ms. Mikulski said.
   ``But these other guys ... have perpetrated a fraud,'' she said.
``Two hundred years ago we would have tarred and feathered them and
run them out of town on a rail. Maybe we gotta get back to some
old-fashion justice.''
