<HEAD>Wife Startled When Would-Be Robber is Unmasked</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST VALLEY CITY, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A restaurant employee was surprised
when a would-be robber was unmasked and turned out to be her husband.
   Police would not release the man's name because he had not been
charged, but West Valley City Police Detective Ron Edwards said
charges may be filed Thursday.
   The man waited outside an Arby's restaurant until the employees
locked up and began filing out early Sunday, police said.
   The unarmed man, wearing a pantyhose mask, then grabbed a
17-year-old girl from behind, believing she carried a bank bag.
   But the girl's boyfriend, an 18-year-old high school football
player, leaped from a car and dragged the man inside the restaurant,
police said.
   When the teen-ager pulled off the man's mask, his startled wife
exclaimed: ``It's my husband!''
   Four other employees also recognized the man, who fled. No money
was taken, police said.
   The 20-year-old suspect was found soon after hiding under
blankets in a bedroom at his home, officers said. He was being held
at the Salt Lake County jail for investigation of robbery and
assault.
