<FILEID>AP-NR-02-08-89 1419EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-ForeclosedHomes     02-08 0297</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Foreclosed Homes,270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pilot Program Is Announced; First Sales Set in Texas and Denver</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal National Mortgage Association and
the organization of local housing officials announced a pilot
program Wednesday selling foreclosed homes to local agencies for use
by low- and moderate-income families.
   The first sales will be in four Texas cities and in Denver.
Officials said they hope to expand the program throughout the
country.
   The federally chartered mortgage corporation known as Fannie Mae
agreed to make all its inventory of foreclosed homes in those cities
available for purchase by local housing or community development
agencies.
   The homes will be sold at a discount of 10 percent to 15 percent
from market value, said Patrick O'Neill, Fannie Mae senior vice
president for real estate sales.
   The discount reflects the savings to Fannie Mae in reduced
holding costs and the absence of real estate brokerage commissions
and other fees it must pay to sell the houses on the open market, he
said.
   The program was announced jointly by the Fannie Mae, a private
corporation chartered by Congress to provide financial services for
housing, and the National Association of Housing and Redevelopment
Officials, representing more than 2,500 local housing and
development agencies.
   Richard Nelson, executive director of the housing officials'
group, said local agencies would use money available from bonds,
local appropriations or federal grants to purchase the homes where
practical. The homes will be rented or sold to low- and
moderate-income families.
   Fannie Mae, the nation's largest investor in home mortgages, has
an inventory of 8,000 foreclosed homes nationally and acquires them
at a rate of about 900 a month. It sold 17,000 in 1988.
   The first sales will be in Austin, Dallas, Houston and San
Antonio, Texas, as well as Denver.
</TEXT>
