<FIRST>r a PM-Heart-AssistDevice 1stLd-Writethru a0577 02-08 0408</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Heart-Assist Device, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0577,0414</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Supported For Record 75 Days By Heart Assist Device</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS two grafs with similar device used for a longer time.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man awaiting a heart transplant has been
supported a record 75 days on a stationary device that assists the
heart's main pumping chamber, raising hopes for development of a
portable version, a hospital said today.
   Texas Heart Institute researchers announced that the facility
will be the site of the first human use of a portable,
battery-operated heart assist device.
   Like the artificial heart, it is designed to keep patients alive
until they can receive transplants. It does not appear to cause
clots that lead to strokes, a problem often associated with the
artificial heart, researchers said.
   With Food and Drug Administration approval, the first tests of
the new device will begin early next year, hospital officials said.
   The patient, Louis E. Wilson, 39, of Winnfield, La., has been on
the heart assist device for nearly twice the previous world record.
   Wilson came to the institute Nov. 21 after he began to suffer
liver and kidney failure because of ischemic cardimyopathy, a
degenerative condition in which his heart cannot pump enough blood.
   On Nov. 25, a team led by Dr. O.H. Frazier implanted the heart
assist pump into Wilson's abdomen. The air-powered device has taken
over the pumping activity required to circulate the blood through
the 6-foot, 210-pound man's body.
   The pump, 6 inches long and 2 inches wide, is connected by tubes
that come out of the stomach and are hooked to a machine run by
electricity, forcing the patient to remain in the hospital while he
is using the device.
   Wilson's size and his type B blood have severely limited the
number of appropriate donor hearts, causing him to remain longer on
the pump than any previous patient, institute spokeswoman Joyce
Staton said today.
   Texas Heart Institute, which has used the pump 10 times, held the
previous world record of 41 days, she said. Washington Hospital
Center in Washington, D.C. and England's London Hospital also have
implanted the device.
   A similar device, the Novocor, has been used to support a patient
at Houston's Methodist Hospital for 100 days, said spokeswoman
Brenda Koch.
   She did not know if that was a record for that device, which also
pumps blood but has some technical differences from the one used at
the Texas Heart Institute.
</TEXT>
