<FIRST>r w AM-Drugs-NuclearPlants     02-08 0426</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drugs-Nuclear Plants,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>NRC Moving to Require Random Drug, Alcohol Tests at US Nuclear Plants</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Nuclear Regulatory Commission on Wednesday
moved toward adoption of a regulation that would require random drug
and alcohol testing of employees at all U.S. nuclear power plants.
   The commission heard a briefing by the NRC staff on the proposed
rule, which would apply to all utilities operating or building
atomic power stations.
   Brian Grimes, an NRC official, said it was expected that the
commission will have a final vote on the regulation within about a
month. After that, he said, official publication of the rule would
take another month, followed by a six-month implementation period.
   About a third of the utilities now conduct some random testing,
said Grimes, director of reactor inspection and safeguards.
   The new regulation ``would establish random testing for all
utilities and at a fairly substantial rate _ perhaps at a rate of
100 percent per year,'' he said in an interview.
   If the 100 percent testing rate is implemented, it would require
1,000 random tests per year for every 1,000 employees. Because the
testing is random and the same employee may be tested more than once
per year, this rate would ensure that about two-thirds of all
employees are tested every year.
   ``The deterrent effect is thought to come from the possibility
that any day, any individual may be subject to a test, even though
he may have just had one the week before,'' Grimes said.
   Asked to assess the seriousness of drug and alcohol abuse at
nuclear power plants, he said: ``We've seen increasing evidence over
the past few years that we are getting positive tests and it is
involving reactor operators.
   ``I think last year we had, over the nation, perhaps eight to 10
cases where licensed operators had indications of positive drug
tests _ not of impairment on the job, but some relation to drugs.
   ``So we think it is a problem. It is not a widespread problem.
But I think we're not invulnerable to societal problems in this
industry, as with any other industry,'' Grimes said.
   During the briefing, officials told the commission that the staff
was proposing that the NRC regulation use threshold levels for
marijuana, cocaine and other drugs that have been determined by the
Department of Health and Human Services.
   For alcohol, the staff proposed using the same impairment level _
0.04 percent blood alcohol content _ set by the Department of
Transportation for testing programs involving transportation workers.
</TEXT>
