<FILEID>AP-NR-02-08-89 1424EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Needles     02-08 0228</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Needles,0232</SECOND>
<HEAD>Needle Exchange to Combat AIDS Approved in Vancouver</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VANCOUVER, British Columbia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The City Council has approved
a $100,000 program to provide free hypodermic syringes to
intraveneous drug users in an effort to combat the spread of AIDS.
   The program was adopted Tuesday at the urging of Dr. John
Blatherwick, the city's medical health officer, and calls for
distributing 10,000 needles a month. Health officials have cited the
re-use of needles by drug abusers as a leading cause of the spread
of AIDS among heterosexuals.
   To get a clean needle, a drug user must bring a used one to the
storefront office of the Downtown Eastside Youth Activities Society,
which has been distributing about 3,000 needles a month with funding
from donations.
   The program is similar to one adopted recently in Tacoma, Wash.,
which also began with a private needle exchange. A private group
distributes needles in New Haven, Conn., New York City, New Jersey
and Boston, and another group is trying to start a program to
distribute free needles in Portland, Ore.
   Alderman Don Bellamy, who voted against the proposal, said
Vancouver should stay out of the drug equipment supply business
despite the need to reduce the spread of acquired immune deficiency
syndrome. Authorities should try to control drug problems, rather
than seeming to condone drug abuse by distributing free needles, he
said.
 
</TEXT>
