<FIRST>r i AM-SAfrica-Police     02-08 0575</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SAfrica-Police,0592</SECOND>
<HEAD>Legislator Publishes Book Alleging Police Violence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAHM VENTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An independent legislator has
published a book detailing charges of widespread police abuses,
saying most whites are unaware of government crackdowns against
black activists.
   Jan van Eck, considered the most left-wing member of the white
chamber of Parliament, cites repeated cases of alleged police
attacks on unarmed blacks in his book ``Eyewitness to Unrest.''
   Van Eck visited black townships near his Cape Town constituency
almost daily during the height of black unrest in 1985-86 and based
his book largely on those visits.
   Emergency regulations prohibit unauthorized reports about unrest
and police actions, although enforcement has not been comprehensive.
   Local and foreign reporters have written regularly about the
disturbances, which have calmed considerably in the past two years.
However, television footage of unrest that has appeared overseas has
not been shown on South Africa's state television network.
   ``In South Africa, white people, generally speaking, are totally
uninformed about what is happening (in black areas),'' van Eck said
in a recent interview after his book began appearing at stores.
``They do not know how (blacks) have been beaten, tear-gassed and
tortured.''
   In his book, van Eck cites an Aug. 10, 1985, incident in which
police used sjamboks, or whips, to break up a crowd attempting to
attend the funeral of a slain black activist.
   ``The sight of 50 sjambok-wielding policemen charging at 500
defenseless men, women and children and beating people left, right
and center froze me into semiparalysis,'' van Eck wrote. ``A more
peaceful crowd of 500 would have been difficult to find.''
   He also was present May 18, 1986, when black vigilantes attacked
homes of black anti-apartheid activists in a Cape Town township.
   ``(There) were virtually unanimous eyewitness accounts that the
security forces had not interfered when the vigilantes started their
attack,'' van Eck wrote. ``Witness upon witness reported that
(security forces) actively helped burn down shacks ...
   ``At every attempt by the (township residents) to move toward
their homes being torched by the vigilantes, the police would use
tear gas or buckshot to disperse them. I saw it myself,'' he wrote.
   Van Eck frequently raises controversial issues not discussed in
the mainstream of white political debate.
   He acknowledges much of his book violates emergency regulations,
but said he made no attempt to abide by them because ``the emergency
regulations are trying to prevent the truth from being told, from
people knowing the excessive amount of violence that is being used
by the state.''
   Van Eck accuses Law and Order Minister Adriaan Vlok of lying when
confronted with allegations of police misconduct.
   ``Once you have reached a situation in which a minister
repeatedly lies to Parliament, you have to start questioning the
whole system and whether you aren't in an early stage of anarchy,''
van Eck said.
   Local newspapers have reported the publication of the book, but
there's been no public response from the government. When asked for
comment, Law and Order Ministry spokesman Lt. P.F. Botma said the
ministry was aware of the book but had no comment about it.
   If the government bans his book, van Eck said he will read it
aloud in Parliament, where members are immune from prosecution for
statements made during official sessions.
   But van Eck said he believed the government ``will probably try
and ignore it and hope it will not be read by too many people.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
