<FILEID>AP-NR-02-08-89 1435EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Korea     02-08 0498</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea,0517</SECOND>
<HEAD>North's Demands for End to Military Exercises Bog Down Meeting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By M.H. AHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANMUNJOM, Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   North Korean demands that South Korea
halt joint military maneuvers with the United States blocked
agreement Wednesday on holding further high-level talks.
   The communist government also said it will postpone talks
scheduled Friday between legislators of the two Koreas until the
military exercise ends.
   Teams led by vice ministers agreed to only one thing Wednesday _
to meet again March 2 in this Panmunjom truce village to try again
to negotiate the meeting of their prime ministers. Those talks would
be the highest level held between the rivals and are aimed at ending
44 years of confrontation since the peninsula was divided.
   Wednesday's meeting bogged down when the communists demanded an
``immediate halt'' to annual joint military exercises North Korea
claimed are ``an obstacle to dialogue.''
   Testy debate over the ``Team Spirit'' maneuvers clouded attempts
to discuss procedural matters or an agenda.
   Official Pyongyang Radio, monitored in Tokyo, said the
disagreements jeopardize future talks, and announced North Korea
will postpone a Friday meeting of legislators from both sides until
the exercises end.
   In Seoul, officials acknowledged hearing the broadcast but said
they have not received official notice postponing Friday's talks.
Nor did they know whether the March 2 meeting will be affected.
   Chief North Korean delegate Paik Nam Jun demanded soon after the
meeting opened that the joint exercise be stopped ``immediately and
unconditionally,'' charging they were ``war preparations.''
   South Korea's chief delegate, Song Han-ho, countered the
exercises are ``defensive'' and intended to prevent a ``possible
invasion.'' North Korea invaded South Korea in 1950, starting a
three-year war.
   Song appealed to delegates to settle their differences.
   ``In the past 40-odd years, we have wasted national potentials as
we waged a war and persisted in confrontation and frictions despite
our being the same brethren,'' he said.
   There was a similar appeal from South Korean opposition leader
Kim Dae-Jung, who said in Rome that he is ``carefully optimistic''
about the talks.
   ``Both sides need to be more flexible,'' urged the leader of the
Party for Peace and Democracy. He said he is cultivating political
and economic contacts in Italy.
   After Wednesday's meeting, Paik and Song accused each other of
insincerity at separate news conferences.
   Song said he believed Pyongyang is trying to make its call for an
end to the joint maneuvers, a precondition for the prime ministerial
meeting.
   Paik said: ``The South Korean side did not show sincerity at
today's meeting. We hope they will come to the next meeting with a
sure answer.''
   This year's military exercises reportedly began last week,
athough there has been no official confirmation. About 200,000 U.S.
and South Korean troops took part in last year's maneuvers. The
exercises usually start in February and last about two months.
   Pyongyang long has called for a withdrawal of the 42,000 troops
the United States maintains in South Korea under a mutual defense
pact.
</TEXT>
