<FIRST>r a AM-PayRaises-States     02-08 0565</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pay Raises-States,0579</SECOND>
<HEAD>Americans Usually Tough When Legislators Want a Pay Hike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THEASA TUOHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress found out the hard way what many of its counterparts in
state capitals across the country already knew: Walk softly when
you're trying to stick a big pay raise in your pocket.
   True, legislators in Hawaii recently got a 73 percent increase,
but lawmakers in New Hampshire make $100 a year and haven't gotten a
raise since 1889.
   In Alaska, legislators got their pay cut in half to $22,140 in
1987, although they now get reimbursed for expenses. The same year,
Massachusetts voters rolled back a $10,999 legislative salary hike.
   In New Mexico, where legislators make $75 a day, they have
received only four raises since statehood in 1912, when the
compensation was $5 a day. In Rhode Island, the pay is still $5 a
day, and no one seems to know if or when there ever was a raise.
   The problem for lawmakers is summed up by state Rep. Bob Brawley
who tried unsuccessfully to double legislative pay in North Carolina
to $21,375.
   ``Everybody's going to use it for political fodder rather than
the realities of the pay scale,'' Brawley said.
   Asked if he would resurrect the issue, he joked, ``You want to
see everybody turn pale around here?''
   Congress, whose members are paid $89,500 a year, backed down on a
proposed 51 percent raise Tuesday after being set upon by
consre considered part-time. They
often supplement their legislative pay with salaries from regular
jobs. Still, they usually don't have time to earn outside money
while their legislature is meeting, and sessions are generally
getting longer.
   New York legislators are the highest paid in the nation at
$57,500, thanks to a 33.7 percent hike that went into effect this
year.
   Angry Massachusetts voters who rolled their legislators back to
$30,000 in 1987 did not remove them from the elite in legislative
pay. Only eight other states have scales above that: Illinois,
California, Michigan, Ohio, Oklahoma, Pennsylvania, Wisconsin and
New York.
   Hawaii's 73 percent increase last November took lawmakers from
$15,600 to $27,000, based on recommendations by a state salary
commission.
   In several states, such as Florida, legislative salaries are tied
to salaries of other state employees, so legislators get the same
average increase.
   The Florida system went into effect in 1986 to avoid the kind of
uproar that engulfed Congress. There was some controversy in 1985,
when salaries were raised for the first time in 16 years from
$12,000 to $18,000. Florida legislators now get $20,748.
   In California, where legislators are considered full-time, the
constitution allows a 5 percent salary increase a year. Legislators
make $40,816 a year plus $87 a session day for expenses, or about
$15,000 a year. They also get a state-leased car and gasoline credit
card. The other full-time legislatures are Massachusetts, Michigan
and Pennsylvania.
   Contrast that with neighboring Nevada, where legislative pay is
$130 a day, plus $66 for living expenses, but only for the first 60
days of the session. If the Legislature meets longer, they don't get
paid. The Nevada Legislature meets every other year and sessions
have run as long as 150 days.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
