<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     02-08 0474</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PIERRE, S.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state House committee shot down a
tongue-in-cheek bill calling for 100 of the geese that winter on the
lake outside the Capitol building to sacrifice their lives to
finance a fancy legislative retreat.
   ``I think you could call this a golden goose of legislation,''
Rep. Roger Porch, a sponsor of the joke bill, said Tuesday as fowl
puns and charges of featherbedding flew higher than migrating geese.
``I hope the committee will take a good gander at this bill.''
   The measure called for a special hunting season that would allow
100 out-of-state residents to pay $10,000 apiece for licenses
permitting them to kill a Capitol Lake goose. The revenue would be
used to build a hunting lodge for lawmakers on nearby Oahe
Reservoir, Porch said.
   By the end of each legislative session, lawmakers need a retreat
because they suffer from shaking hands, ringing ears and blurred
vision and are just basically down, said Porch.
   ``It's known as goose down. Some people actually quack up,'' the
lawmaker said.
   The bill's other sponsor, Rep. Ed Olson, said he had polled the
geese on the lake and they assured him they were willing to take
part in the special season. To back Olson's claim, a woman dressed
up in a goose costume urged the House Agriculture and Natural
Resources Committee to approve the special hunting season.
   ``If anyone is dumb enough to pay $10,000 for a hunting license,
are they going to be able to shoot any of us?'' said the goose,
introduced as Gloria Gander. ``I don't think so.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>VANCOUVER, British Columbia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two black bear clubs
apparently abandoned by their mother are thriving on goat's milk,
baby formula and lots of human attention.
   The week-old female cubs, about the size of a palm, were
discovered by loggers Mike Dumoulin and Carman Watson two weeks ago
after a falling tree disturbed their den near Terrace, about 430
miles northwest of Vancouver, British Columbia. The mother never
returned.
   ``They would have died if we hadn't taken them,'' Dumoulin said
Tuesday.
   Each logger took one of the blind, bald cubs home with him, with
Watson christening his Little Bear and Dumoulin naming his Baby.
   The bears' bare bottoms are wrapped in diapers, and they are fed
goat's milk and baby formula every four hours.
   ``When Mike brought this bawling baby home I just had to help it
fight for its life,'' said Dumoulin's wife, Melanie.
   ``The cub sounds and responds just like a baby. She likes her
tummy rubbed. And there are dirty diapers to wash, of course.''
   It is illegal to take an animal from the wild, but ``in Mike's
case he had a valid reason,'' said Terrace conservation officer
Terry McGunigle.
   The cubs will be sent to the Vancouver Game Farm next month.
</TEXT>
