<FILEID>AP-NR-02-08-89 1545EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Vietnam-US     02-08 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Vietnam-US,0342</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Teens Start Educational Tour in Vietnam</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seventeen Maine high school students on Wednesday
began a 13-day visit to Vietnam to learn about the country and the
war in which some of their fathers fought.
   ``The students will be questioning people on the streets,
visiting schools and hospitals. ... They'll have free time to go out
and get information on their own as well,'' Stephen Knight, a
history teacher from Fairfield, said in a telephone interview from
Hanoi.
   ``No one's telling them if the war was right or wrong. They'll
make that decision for themselves,'' he added.
   He said the visit to Vietnam by American students is one of the
first of its kind.
   The United States has no diplomatic relations with Hanoi's
communist government, whose forces defeated the U.S.-backed former
South Vietnamese government in 1975.
   Knight said about half of the students' fathers had fought in
Vietnam.
   ``I've been teaching about the Vietnam War for some time and it's
the one thing the students want to learn about most,'' Knight said.
   For the American teen-agers, ``the Vietnam War really is
meaningful'' as a chapter of American history that textbooks rarely
include, he said.
   ``American textbooks are awful. They don't deal with the war at
all,'' Knight said.
   The students, who arrived in Hanoi on Wednesday, will be
collecting material on subjects ranging from education and rice
farming to the effects of the herbicide Agent Orange, sprayed over
Vietnam by the U.S. military, he said.
   The students, who average about 17 years old, have been studying
Vietnam for a year in a special accredited history class taught by
Knight on weekends. They come from four different high schools in
the Portland, Maine, area.
   Knight made arrangements for the tour during a visit to Hanoi a
year ago and through the Vietnam Mission at the United Nations in
New York. Two other teachers, three Vietnam War veterans and a
college student also are on the tour.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
