<FIRST>r w AM-TradeMission     02-08 0154</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Trade Mission,150</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trade Mission Planned to Egypt and North Yemen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. trade mission to Egypt and North Yemen
is being planned for spring to help promote agricultural trade and
development, an Agriculture Department official said Wednesday.
   Undersecretary Roland S. Vautour said the actual dates for the
trip still have to be negotiated with the two countries.
   The mission will include representatives from the Agriculture
Department, State Department and the U.S. Agency for International
Development. Three to six representatives from outside government
also will be named to the team, he said.
   Congress authorized the missions program in December 1987 to
encourage greater U.S. private and foreign country participation in
agricultural trade and development activities.
   A previously announced mission will visit Kenya and the Ivory
Coast in March, and one recently returned from Algeria and Tunisia.
Last year, visits were made to the Philippines, Indonesia, Hong
Kong, Singapore and Mexico.
