<FIRST>r a BC-Kodak-Movies CORRECTIVE   02-08 0134</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Kodak-Movies, CORRECTIVE,0134</SECOND>
<HEAD>Members who used b0767, BC-Kodak-Movies, sent Feb. 2 under a ROCHESTER,
N.Y. dateline, for use Sunday, Feb. 5, and thereafter, are asked to use
the following story.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Associated Press erred Saturday in
reporting the length of film used in an average movie. The error
occurred in a story about the 100th anniversary of Eastman Kodak
Co.'s motion-picture film products.
   The average movie film, at 90 feet of film per minute, is about
9,000 to 12,000 feet long.
   Kodak estimates filmmakers use at least 20 times more negative
film than the finished product requires, which means an average
movie might use 180,000 to 240,000 feet of film. If 1,000 prints are
needed, a studio must buy 9 million feet to 12 million feet of print
film.
</TEXT>
