<FIRST>r a AM-ElephantAggression     02-08 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Elephant Aggression,0351</SECOND>
<HEAD>Killer Elephant To Be Sold; Victim's Widow Would Rather It Be Killed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Asian bull elephant that crushed to death
a trainer at Busch Gardens will be spared, but will be sold to a
facility better equipped to handle a growing, three-ton pachyderm.
   Officials at the African theme park have agreed to sell Casey,
the 17-year-old elephant that killed handler Joe Allen, 34, Sunday
as he led the elephant back to its pen.
   ``We certainly don't want to handle him here anymore,'' park
public releations director Glenda Gilmore said Tuesday.
   Gilmore said Casey's owner, Roman Schmitt, will try to find
someone interested in buying him.
   Allen's widow, Mattie Allen, expressed some satisfaction over the
decision,
   ``Thank God he's leaving,'' she said. ``I'd rather they'd killed
it, but if they ship it away from Busch Gardens, I'm glad.''
   Witnesses say Allen either tripped, or was pushed down by the
elephant's trunk. The bull dipped his head, placed it against the
handler's chest and pushed down.
   Federal Occupational Safety and Health Administration officials
are investigating, but didn't immediately determine whether Busch
Gardens should be held accountable, to an OSHA spokesman.
   But some specialists say it will not be easy to find a buyer for
a male pachyderm that has killed a person.
   ``The best way to handle these bull elephants _ the only safe way
_ is to keep them separate, and don't handle them,'' said Mike
Schmidt, a veterinarian who works with elephants at the Washington
Park Zoo in Portland, Ore. ``A lot of those bulls are like ticking
clocks, waiting to go off. It's a calculated risk.''
   Portland officials often get up to $50,000 for a 2-year-old
female calf, and less for the unpredictable bull calves, Schmidt
said. An older bull may be worth even less, especially if it has
killed someone.
   Schmitt brought the elephant to Busch Gardens four months ago as
a second breeding bull. He bought it last year from a Texas man who
used Casey for rides at circuses.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
