<FIRST>r w AM-Cuba-NorthKorea 1stLd-Writethru a0638 02-08 0468</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cuba-North Korea, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0638,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Official Designates Two Communist Countries as Most Repressive</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New grafs 7-8, bgng ``The Cuban,'' with Cuban response to rights
criticism</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   North Korea and Cuba were designated Wednesday
by a top State Department official as the world's worst human rights
violators in 1988 because of their efforts to convert their people
into ``automatons'' through repressive mechanisms.
   ``What we are talking about here is total repression,'' said
Assistant Secretary of State Richard Schifter, who spoke on the
occasion of the release of the State Department's annual human
rights report.
   At a news conference, Schifter likened North Korea to a
``nightmare state'' where ``the government tries really to turn
people into automatons.''
   ``As far as Cuba is concerned, there is an effort there to try to
achieve the same thing in terms of total penetration of the country
by secret police truly spying on every citizen,'' he said.
   Schifter acknowledged that other analysts who judge regimes by
the number of government-sponsored killings of political opponents
would be less critical of Cuba.
   He conceded that he is unaware of any such killings in Cuba in
1988. The country with the largest number of killings in 1988, he
said, was Sudan, where there was large-scale starvation because
government and opposition forces refused to allow emergency food
deliveries to refugees in contested areas.
   The Cuban diplomatic mission here said in reply to Schifter's
comments that the ``United States has no international mandate and,
even less, the moral authority to judge or give opinions about the
internal situation in Cuba.
   ``We therefore attribute no importance to the opinions that the
State Department may have about our country.''
   President Fidel Castro has said that Cuba has the world's most
enviable human rights record because of the gains Cuba has made in
such areas as health and education and in maintaining unemployment
at low levels.
   Castro also has said that a vigilant attitude among his people
must be maintained because of numerous U.S. threats against Cuba and
the many American-sponsored sabotage and assassination attempts.
   The section on North Korea in the human rights report said North
Korea subjects its people to rigid controls.
   The report said the regime establishes security ratings for every
resident that determine access to employment, schools, medical
facilities and stores as well as admission to the ruling party.
   The report added that the government imprisons people ``who fail
to conform to the dictates of the state and often exiles them
together with their families to remote villages.''
   On Cuba, the report said mass organizations attempt to extend
Cuban government and Communist Party control over each citizen's
daily activities at home, work and school.
   ``Citizens are exhorted to ensure ideological conformity and to
report deviation,'' it said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
