<DOCNO> AP890208-0157 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-08-89 1647EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Turtles     02-08 0369</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Turtles,0378</SECOND>
<HEAD>Studies Find Devices Effective In Saving Sea Turtles Caught In Nets</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM E. SCHULZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUNSWICK, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Trap doors on shrimp nets save the lives of
sea turtles, but they also cause a significant reduction in the
shrimpers' catch, studies show.
   The studies presented at a sea turtle conference Wednesday showed
the Turtle Excluder Devices, called TEDs, are effective in releasing
sea turtles from shrimpers' nets, but led to a loss of about 8
percent in the shrimp catch.
   State regulations mandating use of the devices went into effect
in many inshore waters Feb. 1, while federal regulations making TEDs
mandatory go into effect May 1.
   The preliminary results of the studies were presented at the 9th
annual Workshop on Sea Turtle Conservation and Biology, being held
through Saturday on Jekyll Island. Fourteen nations are represented.
   A TED is a barrier in the narrow neck of a shrimper's
funnel-shaped net which guides things too large to get through, such
as large fish or sea turtles, out a trap door in the top or bottom
of the net. Shrimp pass through the barrier to be trapped in the
basket at the bottom of the funnel.
   In a National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration study, no
sea turtles were captured in nets equipped with TEDs, while 24
turtles were caught in nets without the devices, said Ed Klima of
the agency. Two of the 24 died before they could be released.
   Observers who have spent 307 days on shrimp boats along the
Atlantic Coast and in the Gulf of Mexico, near the midpoint of the
projected 700-day project, also found the devices resulted in an
average loss of about 8 percent of the shrimp catch.
   But, Klima added, ``I see that coming out pretty close to zero
with experience by the fishing crew.''
   In a separate study by the University of Georgia Marine Extension
Service, scientists found an 8{ percent reduction in the shrimp
harvest, said D. Kendall, who was optimistic shrimpers will find a
solution to the problem.
   ``Sea turtles are something shrimpers don't want to catch,''
Kendall said. ``They're a pain to have to deal with on the deck of
the boat.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
