<FIRST>r w AM-US-Refugees     02-08 0279</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Refugees,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Says Soviet Jews and Vietnamese Not In Competition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. officials sought to assure Congress
Wednesday that Soviet Jews and people from Vietnam are not in
competition for admission to refugee status in America.
   ``Numbers are not going to be a problem,'' and East Asian
refugees are not going to be pitted against East European refugees
for U.S. entry, said Ambassador Jonathan Moore, U.S. coordinator for
refugee affairs.
   Rep. Stephen J. Solarz, D-N.Y., chairman of the House Foreign
Affairs Committee's subcommittee on Asian and Pacific affairs,
raised the issue at a hearing.
   Solarz asked Moore if he meant that ``not a single Vietnamese
will be obliged to remain behind who otherwise would have been able
to leave'' his homeland but for the transfer of 6,500 U.S. refugee
entry slots from Asians to East Europeans at the end of last year.
   ``That's correct,'' Moore replied. He said the Vietnamese
government is processing emigrants under its ``orderly departure
program'' at a pace that rendered the 6,500 slots surplus at the end
of 1988. They were used for Soviet and East European refugees after
the Soviet Union relaxed its departure rules for Jews and others
long waiting to leave.
   Rep. Nancy Pelosi, D-Calif., told the subcommittee that she and
others in Congress have written to President Bush and Secretary of
State James A. Baker III opposing reductions in resettlement
programs involving Vietnamese.
   The 1989 ceiling of 19,500 Vietnamese entrants compares with
7,000 last year. ``Thus movements out of Vietnam will increase
dramatically over those of last year,'' said Moore.
   The 1989 U.S. refugee quota has been set at 94,000 worldwide.
</TEXT>
