<FIRST>r a AM-WoundedEagle     02-08 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wounded Eagle,0341</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wounded Golden Eagle Being Nursed Back to Health After Surgery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOPKINSVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A wild golden eagle was recovering
Wednesday from surgery on both wings after it was found shot, and
veterinarians concentrated on building up the feeble bird's strength.
   State and federal authorities sought the public's help in
determining who shot the bird in southern Kentucky.
   ``It's in a very poor nutritional state,'' said Dr. Loran Wagoner
of the Skyline Animal Clinic. ``It apparently had been shot for
about a week before it was caught.''
   The adult male, 10 pounds with a 6-foot wingspan, was found
Tuesday by three state highway department employees near Sharon
Grove. The workers turned the wounded bird over to Sgt. Gerald
Barnett of the state Department of Fish and Wildlife in Elkton.
   Four veterinarians performed surgery on the eagle at the animal
clinic.
   ``The upper bones in both wings were broken'' when the eagle was
hit with buckshot, Wagoner said. ``We have intramedullary pins
holding the bones tight. It will be a matter of him strengthening
his bones again before he can fly.''
   Of more immediate concern to Wagoner is building the eagle's
strength so it can be taken to the Louisville Zoo for recovery.
   ``Right now, we're trying to feed him chicken parts and beef,''
he said. ``We've managed to get a little bit down by force-feeding
him.''
   Wagner said it's important that the eagle be transferred to the
zoo soon.
   ``They lose the will to live,'' he explained. ``Even though the
zoo has a controlled environment, it is more familiar to the bird.
It's important not to handle them any more than necessary.''
   Although the bird is weak, its ability to perch is a good
indicator that it may recover, Wagoner said.
   Barnett said a substantial reward would be offered for
information on the shooting. Shooting a golden eagle or a bald eagle
carries a federal penalty of up to a $100,000 fine or one year in
prison.
</TEXT>
