<FILEID>AP-NR-02-08-89 1615EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Germany-Magazine     02-08 0489</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Magazine,0506</SECOND>
<HEAD>Venerable Opposition Magazine Gets Temporary Reprieve</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIRARD C. STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A financially troubled magazine of the
nation's leading opposition party on Wednesday got a chance to keep
espousing leftist causes when party leaders delayed a plan to close
it.
   Two weeks ago, leaders of the Social Democratic party said the
112-year-old publication, which outlasted bans by Bismarck and
Hitler, was losing too much money and would have to be shut down.
The decision prompted an angry outcry from inside and outside party
ranks.
   In the wake of that criticism, party leaders gathered Wednesday
and decided to delay the shutdown of the weekly magazine
``Vorwaerts,'' which means ``Forward.''
   The magazine's editor, Guenter Verheugen, said closing the
publication ``would silence an important voice in the history of
social democracy.''
   The publication's last issue was delivered Feb. 4, and employees
were ordered to abandon this week's edition.
   Under Wednesday's agreement, party leaders will allow
``Vorwaerts'' to continue publication until officials meet again
later this month to weigh the magazine's future.
   ``We'll work around the clock for the next two days if we have to
in order to get the issue out on time,'' said Gode Japs, the
magazine's executive editor.
   Earlier in the day, nervous employees huddled in small groups in
the magazine's cluttered editorial officies in Bad Godesberg to
await the decision.
   ``There hasn't been much to do here,'' said Japs. ``We've been
answering mail, organizing our files and discussing what to do
next.''
   Japs said 47 people could lose their jobs if the magazine folds.
   But he said employees were determined to fight to keep the
publication going. He said morale also was boosted by a ``flood of
letters from readers expressing support and several hundred
spontaneous new subscriptions.''
   Party officials announcing the decision to shut down the magazine
said they saw little hope of boosting the circulation of 46,000 by
50 percent. They said the new subscriptions are needed to cover
rising costs and operating shortfalls.
   Founded in 1876 by Wilhelm Hasenclever and Wilhelm Liebknecht,
the magazine was forced into a 12-year hiatus when Chancellor Otto
von Bismarck banned the Social Democrats in 1878.
   ``Vorwaerts,'' which took a strident anti-Nazi line, was banned
by Adolf Hitler after he came to power in 1933. Its staff went into
exile but continued to publish in Prague and then Paris until German
troops invaded France in 1940.
   The magazine reappeared in 1948 as the official organ of the
Social Democratic Party in West Germany. In its latest edition, it
covered a broad range of topics, including the election of
extreme-right candidates to the West Berlin Parliament and
developments in the Soviet Union, Israel, Italy and Yugoslavia.
   Party officials say the glossy magazine could revert to a
newspaper format in an effort to cut costs. Estimates of its
operating deficit from party and magazine sources vary, ranging from
$2.6 million to $295,000.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890208-0165 </DOCNO>
