<DOCNO> AP890208-0167 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-08-89 1659EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Katyn     02-08 0395</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Katyn,0408</SECOND>
<HEAD>Communist Official Calls for Polish Version of Katyn Massacre</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A legislator wrote in a state newspaper
Wednesday that Poland should publish its version of the World War II
massacre of Polish officers in the Katyn forest, and not wait for
the conclusions of Soviet historians.
   Ryszard Wojna, the Communist Party caucus leader in the Sejm, or
parliament, said Soviet historians have had Poland's secret report
and unpublished documents on the massacre for more than a year and
have not responded.
   A joint Polish-Soviet historical commission has been reassessing
the massacre since April 1987 as part of efforts to remove ``blank
spots'' in the history of the two nations.
   Officially, Poland and the Soviet Union blame the massacre of the
4,300 Polish officers on the Nazis. But historians in the West and
most Poles believe the officers taken into Soviet custody soon after
the outbreak of the war were killed by Soviet security police on
Josef Stalin's orders.
   The victims found at Katyn were among 15,000 Polish military
prisoners who disappeared after being interned by the Soviets. Among
them were 8,300 officers _ half the Polish army's prewar officer
corps.
   The fate of Polish officers and enlisted men held at two other
camps has never been revealed.
   Soviets say the officers at Katyn fell into the hands of
advancing Nazi troops while on a road-building mission near
Smolensk, and were killed by the Gestapo, the Nazi security police.
   Public revelation of the killings by the Nazis in 1943, and a
Polish request for an international investigation, created tensions
and led the Soviet government to break relations with the Polish
government-in-exile in London.
   Shortly afterward, Stalin set up his own Polish committee in
Moscow that became the seed of Poland's postwar communist government.
   Publication of Wojna's article in the government daily Republic
indicated his proposal already has official approval.
   ``By publishing the expertise of Polish scientists, we shall
weaken the painful burdens on Polish-Soviet relations,'' said
Wojna's article.
   ``The information on the stance taken by Polish scientists ...
cannot be reserved any longer only for the Soviet members. The
entire Soviet society has the right to know this stance and the
newly revealed documents.''
   He said the Soviets ``should know that such painful matters
cannot be kept under the cover of scientific discretion for they may
make the cover explode.''
</TEXT>
