<SECOND>AM-Amin,0295</SECOND>
<HEAD>Idi Amin Allowed Back to Saudi Arabia, Diplomats Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALY MAHMOUD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Saudi Arabia has readmitted former Ugandan
dictator Idi Amin to exile after he slipped back into East Africa
for three weeks, Arab diplomats in the kingdom said Wednesday.
   But one diplomat said Amin ``will doubtless lose his last
refuge'' if he continues political activities and statements.
   The diplomats, reached in Jiddah by telephone, said Amin returned
to the Red Sea port city about a week ago.
   The burly, 61-year-old Amin fled to Libya after he was ousted in
April 1979 by his main political rival, Milton Obote. When Libyan
leader Col. Moammar Gadhafi rejected him eight months later, he was
granted political asylum by Saudi Arabia.
   In later months, Amin was joined by one of his two wives and his
22 children.
   ``Idi Amin has been accepted again in the kingdom as a political
refugee, on the explicit condition that he keep his mouth shut and
cease meddling in politics,'' one Jiddah-based diplomat told The
Associated Press on condition of anonymity. ``He also promised not
to leave here surreptitiously again.''
   Amin left his home in suburban Jiddah with one of his sons on
false passports and surfaced on Jan. 3 in Zaire, where the
government quickly expelled him.
   At first, he shuttled between Zaire and Senegal when it became
clear he had also become persona non grata in Saudi Arabia. Amin had
displeased his Saudi hosts with impromptu political statements and
telephone interviews about African politics, primarily his frequent
declarations that he would return to Kampala and recapture power in
his East African country.
   The diplomats said Saudi authorities have posted guards at Amin's
home.
</TEXT>
