<HEAD>Doctor Wins Hospital Suit, Awarded $19 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pathologist who sued a hospital he
said was more interested in profits than patients has been awarded
$19 million.
   Dr. Zbigniew Scheller was awarded the money Tuesday by a state
Circuit Court jury for hardships, including the loss of business
contacts, he has endured since the start of his 10-year legal battle.
   In the lawsuit, Scheller claimed officials at American Medical
International Inc. and Palm Beach Gardens Medical Center, a hospital
owned by AMI, sabotaged his business relationships with other
doctors because of his leading role in organizing medical staff
protests of AMI policies.
   In 1979, the hospital fired Scheller from his post as director of
the pathology lab.
   Scheller also claimed the hospital overbilled Medicare and
private insurance companies for pathology work on hundreds of
patients who entered the medical center from 1980 to 1986.
   AMI lead attorney Mercer Clarke was unavailable for comment
Wednesday. His secretary, who identified herself only as Teresa,
said Clark was on vacation and his co-counsel in the case, James
Polkinghorn, was not in the office.
   Jack Scarola, Scheller's attorney, said an appeal is expected.
   During the five-week trial, Clarke denied AMI cared less for
patients than profits, and said neither the corporation nor the
hospital ever targeted Scheller for harassment.
   Scheller had sought damages of $132 million _ which Scarola
estimated to be 10 percent of AMI's net worth.
</TEXT>
