<FIRST>r w AM-Drugs-Military     02-08 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drugs-Military,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Says No Plans to Send Troops to Fight Drugs _ for Now</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush and a Pentagon official on
Wednesday denied any plans to send U.S. troops to destroy South
American drug laboratories, but Bush said he wouldn't rule it out in
the future.
   Asked about an NBC News report that such an effort was being
prepared, Bush said, ``Nobody's discussed that with me,'' and added
that he is ``very wary of committing U.S. troops overseas.''
   He said he would never take such action ``until I've given it a
lot of thought.''
   Bush added, ``There could be times, working cooperatively with
leaders in the hemisphere, that American assistance would be sought
and American assistance would be granted in wiping out insidious
factories that send poison in to poison our kids ... so you don't
rule something out.''
   NBC reported Tuesday that the administration was preparing a
major drug interdiction plan that would put ``several hundred''
Special Operations commandos into several South American nations.
   ``There isn't any such plan,'' said Maj. David Super, a Defense
Department spokesman. ``We've spent all day batting down the
report.''
   Super said he didn't know if that might be one of the options
being tossed around as part of possibly greater involvement by the
military in the drug war.
   One official involved in the anti-drug effort said various
options will be considered but that reports on such options could
hurt the effort by giving information to drug operators.
   The official, who spoke only on condition of anonymity, also said
discussing potential cooperative arrangements with foreign
governments could be harmful.
   ``The one thing that will make these host governments very
nervous and less likely to cooperate is if they think something by
American forces is going to be done to them without their
knowledge,'' the official said.
   Bush made his comments during an Oval Office photo session with
William Bennett, whom he has nominated to become director of
National Drug Control Policy.
   Bennett said Tuesday that ``there's a lot of discussion going
on'' about increased involvement by the military. In the past,
Bennett has called for such involvement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
