<FIRST>r w AM-SeatBelts     02-08 0382</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Seat Belts,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Safety Agencies Divided Over Safest Way to Buckle Child in Car</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Transportation Safety Board on
Wednesday urged another regulatory agency to change its
recommendation on the safest way to buckle children in a car.
   The board's criticism came in comments on a proposal by the
National Highway Traffic Safety Administration to require rear-seat
lap-and-shoulder belts in passenger vehicles.
   At issue was whether looping the shoulder restraint on a
lap-and-shoulder belt over a child leaves the child vulnerable to
neck injuries in the event of an accident.
   The highway administration, in proposing the regulation, said
that when a child is buckled in, the shoulder portion of the belt
``should be routed behind the child, and the child should be
protected only by the lap belt.''
   The safety board, however, said it strongly disagreed.
   ``We know of no evidence that children are endangered by using a
lap-shoulder belt, whether it crosses the neck or not,'' NTSB said.
``Indeed, we have cited to the NHTSA several studies demonstrating
that these systems provide good protection to children.''
   The use of lap-belts alone places children in danger of serious
and possibly fatal injury to the abdomen, spine and head, the safety
board said.
   Its response otherwise endorsed the heart of the highway
administration's proposal, which was generally in line with a 1986
safety board recommendation to manufacturers.
   The highway agency rule would require the lap-and-shoulder
combination in the two rear window positions in passenger cars
except convertibles manufactured beginning Sept. 1 and in
convertibles, light trucks, multipurpose vehicles and light buses
made from Sept. 1, 1991.
   Regulations presently require lap-and-shoulder belts in the two
front-seat positions but require only lap-belts in rear seats.
   The National Transportation Safety Board also urged the National
Highway Traffic Safety Administration to consider requiring
lap-and-shoulder belts in the center rear-seat position but
recommended against delaying the overall regulation to meet
technical difficulties with that requirement.
   The highway admininstration, in its proposed regulation, said the
center lap-and-shoulder belt would provide ``small safety benefits''
at substantially greater cost.
   The safety board also urged its fellow agency to require
crash-testing of the rear-seat belts, particularly because the
highway administration regulation would allow belt designs that
critics assert allow excessive slack.
</TEXT>
