<FIRST>r p AM-BRF--PrimaryReform     02-08 0146</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Primary Reform,130</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dixon Proposes Regional Presidential Primaries</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Alan Dixon, D-Ill., introduced legislation
Wednesday to create five regional presidential primaries.
   His proposed groupings would be the Northeast plus Puerto Rico,
the Great Lakes states, the Midwest, the Southeast and the Virgin
Islands, and the West including Guam.
   There would be primaries for each party beginning on the second
Tuesday in March of a presidential election year and continuing, one
each month, through July. The Federal Election Commission would
determine the order by drawing lots 70 days before the first round.
   ``It would no longer be in a candidate's best interest to tailor
his or her message to a small group of voters,'' Dixon said. ``In
addition, since the first primary would be chosen at random, each
region would get a fair chance to be in the spotlight'' on the early
events.
</TEXT>
