<FIRST>r w AM-Terrorism     02-08 0478</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Terrorism,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anti-Terrorist Plan In Force</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Michehl, 2nd graf, is CQ</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government and electric utilities have
quietly implemented an anti-terrorist program, even though weather
is considered a greater threat to U.S. energy supplies than any
terrorist group, an industry official told Congress on Wednesday.
   Michehl R. Gent, president of the North American Electric
Reliability Council, said the program was implemented about six
months ago. But he said ``skepticism was rampant'' among planners
that a multi-site terrorist attack ever would be carried out against
U.S. electric facilities.
   Gent told the Senate Governmental Affairs Committee the program
involves an ``ongoing working relationship'' between the FBI and the
council, which he said represents virtually all U.S. and Canadian
electric suppliers.
   He said that because of fear of tipping off terroristsabout the
plan, it was conceived as a ``quiet'' program.
   ``Quiet means that we have struck a deal with the Department of
Energy and the National Security Council: They don't talk about this
program in public, and we don't talk about this program in public,''
Gent said.
   ``My testimony today is the first, and I hope the last, public
utterance of our program,'' Gent said, adding he would be willing to
discuss specifics of the program in a closed committee session.
   Committee Chairman John Glenn, D-Ohio, said that could be done.
He noted that oil and natural gas pipeline representatives had cited
concerns over publicity in declining to testify before the committee.
   Gent said that despite the concerns about terrorism, the U.S.
electric system is resilient and redundant and natural events such
as hurricanes could cause more damage than terrorists. ``And we've
shown we can handle hurricanes.''
   Another witness said there had been 283 documented cases of
sabotage against American energy systems since 1980.
   But Robert K. Mullen, a terrorism expert, said he saw no evidence
of an increasing terrorist threat in the United States and that most
previous acts of sabotage had been incidents such as shooting at
power lines or arson against gasoline station owners or operators.
   ``There are no indicators of which I am aware ... that would
suggest to me the threat to energy assets here is substantially
different from what the recent historical record indicates,'' Mullen
said.
   But Gent acknowledged that ``our concern is not the events that
we're experiencing now but the potential capability that's been
demonstrated to us by the Department of Energy.''
   In earlier testimony, the committee was told that the increasing
high-tech nature of the U.S. telecommunications systems and a trend
towards centralization of facilities was making the networks more
vulnerable to ``catastrophic'' terrorist attack.
   The Energy Department has been advising U.S. companies privately
of a growing threat of ``techno-terrorism'' attack on vital domestic
energy facilities and it is pressing them to fortify their defenses,
The Associated Press reported this week.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
