<HEAD>Vast Kingdom of Candillia Triumphs Over All</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 8th graf, The prizes, with prize data; edits 9th graf
to conform.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE FEINSILBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jeffrey ``Scott' Campbell, 15, won first prize
in a Nintendo contest Wednesday with a plot for a video game far too
complex for anyone over 16 to follow.
   It involves ``the vast kingdom of Candillia, a peaceful and
futuristic world,'' that has been ``ruled by the LockArm Dynasty for
ages'' and whose secrets are locked in a ``Sword of Power.'' It
involves a queen who bore Siamese twins who were given robotic arms.
   It involves the gate to Fifth Dimension, alien invaders who fall
from the skies in a cosmic exchange of civilizations, a rocky
terrain crawling with mutants and Okra, a six-armed king.
   The judges declared that Scott's design for a new game, carefully
mounted in a notebook and illustrated with hand-lettered text and
drawings, was the most ultimate among the 10,134 entries submitted
by youngsters aged 8 to 15 _ 80 percent of them boys.
   ``I had lots of ideas and I like to draw,'' said Scott, after
winning. He is from Aurora, Colo.
   Second place went to Michael Krier, 13, of South Bend, Ind., in
whose design for ``Anatomic Commando'' white blood cells are the
heroes and viruses the villains. In his game, gamma globulin
missiles fight off Attack Bacteria, Monster Bacteria and Virus
Clusters.
   Phil Loring, 13, of Londonderry, N.H., won third prize with an
idea for a new kind of peripheral equipment to accompany the
computer game. It would simulate a climate and an environment
appropriate to whatever game is being played _ offering, perhaps,
the suggestion of swirling dark clouds when things go wrong in Scott
Campbell's LockArm Dynasty.
   The prizes were $3,000, $2,000 and $1,000 savings bonds. Nintendo
said it had no plans to put the prize-winning games into production.
   The finalist entry which really caught Washington's political eye
didn't win. It was ``Voyage to the White House,'' submitted by Kate
Bellamy, 12, of Toccoa, Ga.
   In Kate's game, ``George Bush has been elected president and now
must journey to the White House to take his place as president. On
the way, he must fight Democrats by jumping on them and collecting
cash. At the end of Level 5, Bush and (Dan) Quayle will fight
Michael Dukakis and if he wins goes to the White House where the Tax
Deficit is lowered and everything is fine.''
   In addition to Kate, the other finalists were: Scott Clark and
Jeff Kiesel, both 15, a team from Crestwood, Ky.; Justin Balthrop,
10, of Albuquerque, N.M.; Norm Becht, 15, of Bellingham, Wash.;
Damon Fontenot, 13, of Borger, Texas; Alex Jizrawi, 13, of San
Carolos, Calif., and Chris Maycock, 10, of Malvern, Pa.
