<FIRST>r a AM-SniperTrial     02-08 0372</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sniper Trial,0382</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rhode Island Sniper Trial Goes To Jury</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The case of a man accused in a string of
sniper assaults went to the jury Wednesday after the defense
attorney told jurors his client said he was the sniper only to get
attention.
   Peter T. Trepanier was a ``jokester, a prankster,'' and
prosecutors failed to link him to any of the shootings, break-ins
and arsons, John J. Hardiman argued.
   Trepanier faces six counts of assault with intent to commit
murder and six counts of conspiracy to commit murder in the string
of sniping attacks in Cumberland and North Smithfield in December
1986 and January 1987. He also is charged with a series of
burglaries and housefires in Burrillville and Glocester from April
to June 1987. Trepanier, 25, faces a possible life sentence if
convicted on the arson charges.
   Prosecuting attorney Eva Marie Mancuso told the 16 jurors that
the prankster argument was an insult to their intelligence.
   ``The defense wants you to think this was an attention-getting
statement,'' said Mancuso. But, she told the jury, Trepanier had
told both his friend, Paula Laliberte, and police that the gun used
in the attacks was in a local pond and a gun was actually found
there.
   ``Who picked up the rifle each and every time and looked in the
scope and pulled the trigger and watched the people fall?'' Mancuso
asked the jury.
   Trepanier was reckless, and ``reckless is intent to murder,'' she
said.
   The jurors retired to a downtown hotel Wednesday afternoon after
asking to see the exhibits in the case and to have the definition of
the crime assault with intent to commit murder read back to them.
   Hardiman spent much time rebutting the statements of Laliberte,
who gave detailed testimony about how the defendant confessed to the
shootings on Oct. 7, 1987, before they both went to Woonsocket
police.
   ``They really are attention-getters,'' Hardiman said of the
statements. He said Laliberte had described Trepanier as ``a
jokester, a prankster, a kind of guy who would kid around.''
   Hardiman said police had not been able to test the .22-caliber
rifle, so they could not link the bullets recovered at the shooting
scenes directly to the weapon.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
