<FIRST>r w AM-CancerStudy 1stLd-Writethru a0679 02-08 0568</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cancer Study, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0679,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: First 5 grafs new with comment from Tobacco Institute; picks
up 5th graf pvs, Another federal.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Cancer Panel Calls for New Pressure to Eliminate Smoking</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tobacco should be classified as a drug and
regulated by the Food and Drug Administration, a move that could
lead to a ``tobacco-free society by the year 2000,'' a presidential
panel said Wednesday.
   The National Cancer Advisory Board, which conducted a series of
public hearings on cancer prevention, also recommended that smoking
be banned on all airlines and other public transportation and in the
workplace, public buildings and schools.
   Smokeless tobacco, the report said, should be banned in schools
as well and called on professional athletic organization to campaign
against its use.
   Congress should pass legislation declaring tobacco to be a drug
and place it under the control of the FDA, a move that would help to
``intensify the pressure and activity in America to eliminate
smoking and tobacco use, creating a tobacco-free society by the year
2000,'' the report said.
   Gary Miller, assistant to the president of the Tobacco Institute,
said the recommendation by the cancer advisory board was ``just
another attempt to create a prohibition of tobacco,'' which he said
``already is one of the most regulated substances in America.''
   Another federal study of tobacco use found that Australia has had
the sharpest decline of smokers, when compared with other major
western industrialized nations including the United States, but that
Australia's smoking rate among men still remains high.
   In a study in the American Journal of Public Health, Australia
has had the sharpest drop in smoking since a campaign began in 1983,
with the percentage of smokers among men 20 and older dropping from
38.9 to 32.9 percent.
   Smoking rates among men in the U.S., Great Britain, Canada,
Norway and Sweden have declined steadily since 1974 and rates are
lower than Australia in the United States, Canada and Sweden.
   John Pierce, chief of the epidemiology branch of the Public
Health Service, said the decline of smokers in Australia ``is
impressive,'' but that the Pacific Ocean nation is ``still playing
catchup.''
   The report by the presidential board was based on information
gathered in public hearings in Los Angeles, Atlanta, Dallas, Miami
and Philadelphia. The study said that a third of all testimony dealt
``entirely or in part with smoking and related subjects and their
relationship to the prevention of cancer.''
   As a result, the board said its report emphasizes ``that
eradication of tobacco use is essential and would have measurable
results in reducing cancer mortality.''
   Other recommendations from the presidential board included:
   _ Increased accessibility and affordability of cancer detection
procedures, particularly for breast, cervical and colorectal cancer.
   _ Expanded accessibility of cancer prevention information to the
poor, elderly, blacks, Hispanics, Asian-Americans and native
Americans.
   _ Expanded involvement of the private sector in cancer prevention
with work site programs.
   _ Expanded cancer education efforts in the media and in
professional and civic organizations.
   _ Encouraging participation of the nation's schools in cancer
prevention and detection.
   _ Enhanced involvement of state and local governments in cancer
prevention and screening, and the control of environmental cancer
risk factors.
   The National Cancer Advisory Board was named by President Reagan
as part of the National Cancer Institute's effort to reduce cancer
by half among Americans by the year 2000.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
