<FIRST>u w AM-McArtor-FAA     02-08 0276</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-McArtor-FAA,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>FAA Administrator Stepping Down After Montreal Conference</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Allan McArtor will step down as head of the
Federal Aviation Administration after he returns from a meeting on
international terrorism in Montreal next week, an FAA spokesman said
Wednesday.
   Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner, who will lead the U.S.
delegation to the special session of the Council of the
International Civil Aviation Organization Feb. 15-16, announced on
Tuesday that McArtor would be replaced.
   Skinner said McArtor had asked to return to private business. The
new transportation secretary said he has ``one or two'' good
candidates for FAA administrator but would not say whom he might
recommend. The post is a filled by presidential appointment and
requires Senate confirmation.
   McArtor, 46, has been FAA head since July 1987. He was a
decorated Vietnam War combat pilot. Prior to his appointment, he was
a senior vice president of Federal Express, the overnight parcel
delivery service.
   McArtor has not announced his plans after leaving office. FAA
spokesman John Leyden said the administrator's resignation would
tentatively take effect Feb. 17.
   Relatives of people killed in the Dec. 21 bombing of Pan Am
Flight 103 over Scotland, which killed 270 people, had called for
McArtor's resignation earlier in the week. They blamed the FAA for
failing to secure the flight and warn passengers of threats against
it.
   McArtor, however, had indicted earlier that he would be leaving.
   The Montreal meeting, called by the United States and Britain and
expected to include high-level representatives of 31 other nations
on the council, was prompted by the destruction of Flight 103 and is
to discuss ways to protect aviation from terrorists.
</TEXT>
