<FIRST>r i AM-Pope-AshWednesday     02-08 0188</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pope-Ash Wednesday,0193</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pope Urges Christians To Avoid Hypocrisy, Ideologies And Fads</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II urged Christians at the
beginning of Lent on Wednesday not to fall prey to hypocrisy,
ideologies and worldly fads.
   Lent, a period of fasting and penitence before Easter, should
bring a ``purification of the heart,'' he said in remarks at his
general audience.
   John Paul's observation of Ash Wednesday, the opening day of
Lent, included an afternoon Mass at the fifth century Saint Sabina
Church on the Aventine Hill.
   The pope said purification of the heart means purification of
thoughts, intentions, desires and passions ``so that our external
behavior is really sincere and not the fruit of that hypocrisy and
`human glory' against which Christ was so severe.''
   ``The subtle temptation, for us Christians, is that of appearing
Christian without really being so, stooping to pacts with ideologies
and with the fads of this world,'' the pope told several thousand
pilgrims and tourists in Paul VI Auditorium.
   ``May this penitential season of Lent be for us an occasion for a
sincere examination of conscience,'' John Paul said.
