<FIRST>r w AM-US-PLO 2ndLd-Writethru a0717 02-08 0617</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-PLO, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0717,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Meets with PLO Over Clash with Israelis</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts new graf 11, bgng ``Diplomatic sources,'' to update
on Arad-Baker meeting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States has formally notified the
Palestine Liberation Organization of its ``serious concern'' over
the PLO's clash with Israelis in southern Lebanon, the State
Department announced Wednesday.
   Robert Pelletreau, the U.S. ambassador to Tunisia, registered the
U.S. view at a meeting in Tunis with Hakam Balloui, a PLO
representative, department spokesman Charles E. Redman said.
   Israel has charged five guerrillas from the PLO were attempting
to infiltrate when they were intercepted and slain Saturday in a
security zone Israel has established across its border in southern
Lebanon.
   Accusing the PLO of terrorism, the Israeli government took the
position the United States should break off its three-month-old
dialogue with the PLO, which was based on a renunciation of
terrorism by Chairman Yasser Arafat.
   Redman declined to say whether the State Department considered
the incident an act of terrorism or to give details of Pelletreau's
discussion with Balloui.
   ``I'm not going to be able to give a readout on those meetings,''
Redman said. ``I'm just going to confirm that Ambassador Pelletreau
met with the PLO's representative in Tunis and raised our serious
concern over the incident in Lebanon.''
   Meanwhile, Israeli Ambassador Moshe Arad called on Secretary of
State James A. Baker III and then told reporters: ``We feel this
whole dialogue was not warranted by the realities and by the
behavior of the PLO, and we keep to the same position and the same
view.''
   The Israeli government takes the position that the clash Saturday
violated Arafat's renunciation of terrorism.
   ``In our view,'' Arad said, ``the actions of the last few weeks
indicate that they haven't changed their character, they haven't
changed their involvement in terrorist acts. The incident last week
along the Israeli-Lebanese border was just another demonstration of
their continuous involvement in terrorist acts.''
   Arad declined to say what Baker had told him about the U.S. stand
on the PLO, but the Israeli ambassador said he was pleased with the
meeting.
   Diplomatic sources said Baker assured the ambassador the United
States had taken note of the incident and was looking into it. The
sources, declining to be identified, said Baker was noncommittal
about future U.S. relations with the PLO.
   The department said Tuesday it was investigating the incident and
that Pelletreau had been instructed to take the matter up
immediately with PLO officials.
   Pelletreau is the designated U.S. contact with the PLO, which
makes its headquarters in Tunis.
   Former President Reagan broke a 13-year ban last December on U.S.
talks with the PLO after Arafat made a statement renouncing
terrorism and recognizing Israel's right to exist. Former Assistant
Secretary of State Richard W. Murphy and other senior U.S. officials
cautioned the dialogue would be suspended if the PLO violated the
pledge.
   Identification carried by four slain Palestinians and one
Lebanese involved in the clash Saturday indicated they belonged to
two radical factions of the PLO.
   Redman had reserved judgment Tuesday on whether the Arafat pledge
had been violated. But he was critical of the PLO, saying ``we take
this incident very seriously. It can have a negative impact on the
U.S.-PLO dialogue and the atmosphere necessary for a positive
Palestinian-Israeli dialogue.''
   The department has released its annual human rights report to
Congress containing sharp criticism of Israel's treatment of
Palestinian Arabs living on the West Bank and in Gaza.
   Several other countries were accused of widespread human rights
abuses, but attention has centered on Israel and the report's
accusations.
   The Israeli government has denounced the charges as exaggerated
and unjustified.
</TEXT>
