<FIRST>r i AM-UN-Iran-Iraq     02-08 0339</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Iran-Iraq,0348</SECOND>
<HEAD>Security Council Prods Iran and Iraq on Peace Negotiations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Security Council urged Iran and Iraq on
Wednesday to make progress toward a peace agreement and authorized
U.N. peacekeepers to continue monitoring the truce.
   By unanimous vote, the 15-member council called on the Persian
Gulf neighbors to ``immediately implement Security Council
Resolution 598,'' passed in July 1987, which provides for a
cease-fire, withdrawal from each other's territory, prisoner
exchange and peace talks.
   Wednesday's resolution extended through Sept. 30 the mandate of
the U.N. Iran-Iraq Military Observer Group, the 350 peacekeepers who
monitor a cease-fire that took effect Aug. 20 after nearly eight
years of war.
   Peace talks opened in Geneva Aug. 25, but became deadlocked
almost immediately over Iraq's demand that Iran allow dredging of
the Shatt-al-Arab waterway, which forms their southern frontier.
Whether the border runs down the middle of the Shatt or on the
Iranian bank is a major point of contention.
   Iran rejects preconditions and insist on immediate troop
withdrawal. Iraq still occupies an estimated 260 square miles of
Iranian territory captured just before the truce.
   Diplomats in Baghdad, capital of Iraq, said privately Wednesday
that Iraqi and Iranian officers would meet under U.N. sponsorship
near the Iranian town of Qasr-e Shirin in the border no-man's land.
   They said 10 officers from each side would take part in the
meeting organized by special U.N. envoy Jan Eliasson in an effort to
spur the negotiations.
   Eliasson, the Swedish U.N. ambassador and Secretary-General
Javier Perez de Cuellar's representative at the peace talks, visited
Baghdad and Tehran late last month but no progress on major issues
was evident.
   The foreign ministers of Iran and Iraq are expected to meet with
Perez de Cuellar this wek. Tariq Aziz of Iraq is in New York and Ali
Akbar Velayati of Iran was expected Thursday.
   Velayati said Monday in Tehran he expected a new round of direct
peace talks to begin soon, but did not mention a date.
</TEXT>
