<FILEID>AP-NR-02-08-89 2122EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-PhoneRates     02-08 0328</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Phone Rates,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>FCC Says Cost of Phone Service Rose 1.3 Percent Last Year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The cost of telephone service rose 1.3 percent
in 1988, far less than the 4.4 percent overall increase in
inflation, the Federal Communications Commission said Wednesday.
   The FCC said residential phone service cost an average $12.33 in
October 1988 for unlimited calling, excluding long-distance rates.
The same service cost an average $12.44 in October 1987 and $12.58
in October 1986, the FCC said.
   When subscriber line charges and taxes are included, the average
rate for unlimited calling in October was $16.59.
   The FCC said Bureau of Labor Statistics figures show that the
real cost of telephone service, including long-distance, dropped
about 3 percent in 1988 when inflation is taken into consideration.
   In 1987, the cost of telephone service also dropped 1.3 percent,
compared with a 4.4 percent increase in inflation, for a real
decline of nearly 6 percent.
   The figures were reported in the FCC's Telephone Rates Update, a
twice-yearly survey of phone costs in 95 cities.
   The survey found that local service rates increased 4.5 percent
on average, while state toll rates decreased 4.2 percent. Interstate
long-distance rates also dropped 4.2 percent on average.
   The agency said that for the first time its survey included local
business telephone service.
   It found that single line business customers paid an average of
$40.06 per month for local touch tone service, including subscriber
line charges and taxes, and 200 short calls in cities where
unlimited calling was not offered.
   The FCC said lower-priced options for phone service, such as
Lifeline and Link Up, were provided in 92 of the 95 cities surveyed.
The average monthly price for the lowest priced, generally available
service was $9.20, including subscriber line charges and taxes.
   Subscriber line charges _ currently $2.60 a month for residential
customers _ are the fees local telephone companies charge to connect
customers with long-distance networks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
