<FIRST>r w AM-HUDSettlement     02-08 0200</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-HUD Settlement,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Manufactured-Home Producer Settles Federal Suit for $945,000</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's largest producer of manufactured
homes, Fleetwood Enterprises Inc., has agreed to pay $945,000 to
settle a federal suit charging it failed to meet federal
construction and safety standards, the government said Wednesday.
   The Department of Housing and Urban Development said the
agreement settles a suit filed by the government in U.S. District
Court in Wilmington, Del., in 1988 alleging that 20,000 Fleetwood
manufactured homes built in 1983 and 1984 failed to meet such
standards.
   HUD, in a prepared statement, said its investigators concluded
the homes had substandard walls and roof restraints, making them
subject to damage.
   Glenn Kummer, president of Fleetwood Enterprises in Riverside,
Calif., said that in making the payment the company ``hasn't
admitted that the homes violated any standards.'' Company vice
president and general counsel William Lear said the settlement ended
a series of disputes over ``engineering interpretations.''
   The settlement also covered a case in which an administrative law
judge found similar violations of federal construction and safety
standards in 4,000 homes produced by Fleetwood Homes of Texas
between 1980 and 1984, according to a statement issued by HUD
Secretary Jack Kemp.
</TEXT>
