<FILEID>AP-NR-02-08-89 2102EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-SEC-PennyStocks     02-08 0378</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SEC-Penny Stocks,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>SEC Proposes to Crack Down on High-Pressure Phone Tactics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission on
Wednesday proposed new rules that would crack down on stockbrokers
who use high-pressure telephone tactics to sell penny stocks.
   The stocks typically sell for less than $3 a share. Some are
issued by legitimate companies, but many are sold by companies with
an erratic earnings history.
   The stocks can be thinly traded and it is often difficult for an
investor to accurately judge their value. Brokers sometimes take
extra-large commissions on penny stock sales.
   The SEC rule, proposed by a 5-0 vote, would not entirely ban
unsolicited ``cold calls.'' However, it would require brokerage
firms to sign a written agreement with a new customer before
completing a transaction.
   Brokers would also have to interview new customers to determine
if they were suitable for risky investments and keep the suitability
documents on file for inspection by regulators.
   Final action could come in 30 to 60 days after the agency reviews
public comment.
   The president of a group representing state regulators, the North
American Securities Administrators Association, praised the proposal
as ``a meaningful effort to provide front-end protection against
some of the worst abuses and fraud in the penny stock market.''
   ``The commission is signaling to the industry and the little guy
that it intends to proceed in a very serious fashion,'' said John
Baldwin, president of the association and director of the Utah
Securities Division.
   The SEC has identified six areas where penny stock fraud is
prevalent: south Florida, New Jersey, Nevada, Los Angeles, Denver
and Utah.
   Last October, SEC Chairman David S. Ruder established a task
force on penny stock manipulation. According to the agency's staff,
about 325 brokerage firms sell penny stocks, up from 55 a few years
ago.
   The proposed rules apply to so-called ``pink sheet'' stocks,
issued by companies with fewer than $300,000 in assets. The pink
sheets are published by the National Quotation Bureau Inc., a
private firm.
   Stocks traded on exchanges or through the automated system of the
National Association of Securities Dealers would be exempt from the
rule. Also, brokers could sell to large institutional investors
without meeting the stricter requirements for individual investors.
</TEXT>
