<FIRST>r a AM-ArmenianCatholicos     02-08 0285</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Armenian Catholicos,0295</SECOND>
<HEAD>Church Head Says Religious Situation Brighter In Soviet Armenia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Christianity's chief leader in Soviet Armenia
said Wednesday that under Soviet reforms ``the spiritual life and
authority of the church has become more influential among the
people.''
   There is now ``total respect for the church,'' said Catholicos
Vasken I of Etchmiadzin, whose title is supreme patriarch and
Catholicos of all Armenians.
   ``This is is only a beginning,'' he added in an interview. ``We
will have the opportunity to progress in this cause.''
   The catholicos, or pontiff, said policy changes under Soviet
leader Mikhail Gorbachev have enabled the opening and renovation of
churches and monasteries, increased baptisms and ``general interest
in spiritual life has developed.
   He said clergy now are permitted to visit hospital patients to
pray with them and read passages of the Bible.
   ``The doctors suggest priests visit more often because the visits
are helpful in hastening recovery of patients,'' he said.
   Vasken, in the United States on a nine-day pastoral visit to help
develop plans for rebuilding earthquake-ravaged northern Armenia,
meets with President Bush on Thursday.
   He was accompanied by Catholicos Karekin II of Cilicia, based in
Beirut, Lebanon, the second-ranking Armenian see. It has had
prolonged jurisdictional friction with the ``mother see'' at
Etchmiadzin.
   However, Vasken said ``the situation is better. We are in
conversation toward creating cooperation.''
   He said talks had been going on before the earthquake disaster,
but it had further solidified relations. ``It gave us the
opportunity to come together and plan,'' he said.
   ``We already were brothers. But there were problems to be
resolved. Together we have agreed on taking certain steps toward
cooperation.''
</TEXT>
