<SECOND>AM-Bush-Cabinet,140</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush To Remain Two Councils</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush has decided to retain two
Cabinet-level councils set up by former President Reagan, one
dealing with domestic and the other with economic policy, the White
House said Wednesday.
   A statement issued by the office of White House Press Secretary
Marlin Fitzwater said that Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady would
generally preside over the the Economic Policy Committee and
Attorney General Richard Thornburgh over the Domestic Policy Council.
   The economic unit is made up of the secretaries of State,
Treasury, Agriculture, Commerce, Labor, budget director, the U.S.
trade representative and the chairman of the Council of Economic
Advisers.
   The domestic unit is made up of the secretaries of Interior,
Health and Human Services, Housing and Urban Develop, Energy,
Education, Veterans Affairs, the budget director and the
Environmental Protection Agency.
