<FIRST>r i AM-SouthAfrica-Reform     02-08 0496</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Africa-Reform,0510</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Party Leader Pledges Black Rights, White Segregation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The governing National Party's new
leader, F.W. de Klerk, said Wednesday he is committed both to equal
rights for blacks and to whites-only communities.
   Foreign Minister R.F. Botha said criticism of South Africa's
human rights record by the U.S. State Department was ``one-sided and
unsubstantiated.''
   De Klerk told Parliament, in his first major address since being
chosen as party chief last week, the government must develop a
constitution that protects the rights of both whites and blacks.
   ``I want to state unequivocally that the National Party is
against domination of any one group by others,'' he said. ``White
domination, in so far as it still exists, must go.''
   He also said the government remains committed to segregated
neighborhoods, schools and other facilities under the principle of
``group rights.''
   ``A strong emphasis on group rights, alongside individual rights,
is based on the reality of South Africa and not on an ideological
obsession or racial prejudice,'' he said.
   Under South Africa's apartheid policy of racial segregation, the
5 million whites maintain political and economic control over the
country's 26 million blacks, who have no vote in national affairs.
   At a briefing for foreign journalists after the Parliament
speech, de Klerk declared support for gradual and limited race
reforms.
   ``The crux of what I wanted to get across was to commit the
National Party to the very same road which ... President P.W. Botha
has taken the party on,'' he said.
   He visited Botha at his Cape Town residence Wednesday but would
not give details of the meeting.
   Botha relinquished the party leadership after suffering a stroke,
and de Klerk, 52, was chosen Feb. 2 to succeed him. The National
Party has governed South Africa since 1948 and made apartheid into
law.
   The president has indicated he will resume official duties when
he recovers. De Klerk is considered heir apparent. Chris Heunis, the
constitutional development minister, now is acting president.
   De Klerk is seen as a cautious pragmatist who supports gradual
expansion of black rights while keeping real political power in
white hands. Although he said Wednesday the government is ready to
negotiate a new constitution with blacks, few black leaders agree to
talk without further reforms.
   Pressure on the right comes from the Conservative Party, which
sees Botha's limited reforms as capitulation to the black majority.
   Foreign Minister Botha, no relation to the president, said the
State Department ``ignores the government obligation to maintain law
and order against terrorism in South Africa while at the same time
it is silent on the acts of terrorism perpetrated by the ANC,'' the
African National Congress guerrilla movement.
   In its annual report on the state of human rights around the
world, released Tuesday, the State Department said South Africa
further curtailed rights last year by clamping down on opponents of
the government and banning peaceful anti-apartheid groups.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
