<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Environment     02-08 0419</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Environment,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Wants to Clean Up Environment Without Stifling Economy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said Wednesday he wants to
develop a consensus among industry and environmental interests in an
effort to find ways to clean up the environment ``without stifling
the economy.''
   Americans are impatient for results on environmental cleanup,
Bush said at swearing-in ceremonies for Interior Secretary Manuel
Lujan Jr. and Environmental Protection Agency Administrator William
K. Reilly, the two top officials who will guide his administration's
environmental efforts.
   ``They won't accept excuses anymore and they won't accept
finger-pointing. They want us to get all the sides together and find
a way to achieve both their goals,'' he told a gathering at EPA
headquarters where Reilly was sworn in.
   His comments came the day before his address to Congress in which
he will deliver budget proposals on his spending priorities on the
environment as well as other matters.
   Bush's visit to EPA was the first by a president since the agency
was created in 1970. Reilly noted this when he made his remarks
following his swearing in.
   ``You are not dreaming. This is the president of the United
States,'' said the former head of the Conservation Foundation and of
the U.S. affiliate of the World Wildlife Fund.
   He said Bush came because ``he cares urgently about protecting
the environment.''
   ``Isn't it encouraging to have an environmentalist in the White
House who comes here to signal his close and public commitment to
the work of the Environmental Protection Agency?'' he said.
   Bush said he wants to build a consensus among environmental and
industry interests to ensure a clean environment.
   ``I believe doing that requires finding ways to clean up the
environment without stifling the economy,'' he said. ``More often
than not there is common ground if the parties will make an effort
to find it,'' he added.
   Bush said Americans want both economic growth and a clean
environment.
   At the Interior Department, Bush said that Lujan, a former
congressman from New Mexico, agreed with him in sharing the
sentiments of former President Theodore Roosevelt who said, ``A
grove of giant redwoods or sequoias should be kept just as we keep a
great and beautiful cathedral.''
   Bush called for conservation and ``wise management'' of public
land.
   During last year's presidential campaign, Bush promised to deal
aggressively with such issues as global warming, toxic waste
disposal and acid rain.
   Reilly said public demand for a clean environment ``has probably
never been firmer.''
</TEXT>
