<FIRST>r i AM-Germany-Rocket     02-08 0508</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Rocket,0527</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Shelves Research On Rocket With Reported Nuclear Potential</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said it shelved secret
research on a short-range conventional missile on Wednesday, a day
after a televised report that the rocket could also carry nuclear
warheads.
   West Germany's chief government spokesman, Friedhelm Ost,
repeated official denials that the proposed missile, researched by a
U.S. and a West German company, had nuclear potential.
   Ost said shelving the ``Technex'' project was in response to
recent ``positive signals'' in disarmament efforts, including
planned troop reductions by the Warsaw Pact and agreement to begin
East-West conventional weapons talks in March.
   But he said the research could resume if the talks are
unsuccessful.
   The government's move also appeared aimed at heading off any
anger among West Germans after Tuesday's disclosure of the Technex
research project and a claim by the ARD television network that the
weapons system could carry a nuclear warhead.
   Because of a popular perception that the East bloc is no longer a
military threat, there is a growing anti-military mood in West
Germany. That has led to widespread opposition against any move that
could torpedo disarmament efforts and good relations with the East
bloc.
   East Germany's official Communist Party newspaper lashed out at
its Western neighbor over the weapons research.
   The newspaper, Neues Deutschland, said any government doing such
research is not seriously interested in seeing success at the
upcoming Vienna conventional weapons talks.
   ``These parties are at the most using (these talks) to cover up
major disarmament projects,'' the newspaper said in a commentary.
   Ost told reporters that Chancellor Helmut Kohl and Defense
Minister Rupert Scholz made the decision to shelve the Technex
project following ``long talks.''
   ``But both agree that this option should only be completely
abandoned if the conventional weapons talks result in a conventional
balance at a reduced level,'' he added.
   NATO maintains that the Warsaw Pact maintains a strong military
superiority in a number of areas.
   Defense Ministry spokesman Winfried Dunkel on Wednesday said the
U.S. rocket manufacturer Martin Marietta and
Messerschmitt-Boelkow-Blohm, a West German aerospace company,
participated in the $54.6 million study.
   He said the two firms were researching the feasibility of a
rocket system with a range of up to 310 miles fitted with a special
conventional warhead to destroy enemy air bases in times of war.
   Udo Philipp, a Messerschmidt spokesman, said the rocket would not
be able to carry a nuclear warhead.
   ``Because of factors of weight, aerodynamics and size, the
warheads would not be interchangeable,'' he said.
   But ARD on Tuesday reported it obtained Defense Ministry
documents showing the weapon would have dual capability.
   Dunkel did not specify what the Technex research achieved but
said it was only a ``technical study,'' that no prototype was built
and no companies were contracted to produce it.
   Dunkel rejected claims by some opposition party members that they
were kept in the dark about the Technex project, saying the
parliamentary defense committee had known about it since June 1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
