<FIRST>r i AM-FrigidMexico     02-08 0399</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Frigid Mexico,0409</SECOND>
<HEAD>Death Toll Reaches 26 In Northern Mexico's Cold Wave</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAM ROSSIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTERREY, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An unusual invasion of freezing Arctic
air has killed 26 people in northern Mexico, including a 65-year-old
invalid burned to death when an open fire ignited her bed, according
to reports Wednesday.
   Growers in Nuevo Leon's vast citrus region south of Monterrey
have been conducting an emergency harvest of oranges, grapefruit and
tangerines since the so-called Alaskan Express moved in last
Saturday.
   Schools in Nuevo Leon state have been closed all week, and the
Mexico City newspaper La Jornada said officials in neighboring
Chihuahua and Tamaulipas states also ordered schools closed.
Temperatures in urban areas dipped to 18 degrees Tuesday night.
   Drivers unaccustomed to icy roads lost control of their vehicles,
and more than 100 minor accidents were reported in the Monterrey
metropolitan area Tuesday. Police reported no serious injuries.
   Maria del Refugio Oliva de Saucedo burned to death in her tiny
shack in Monterrey when an open fire she was using to ward off the
cold ignited the blankets as she slept, Monterrey newspapers
reported.
   El Porvenir quoted state police as saying 25 more people in the
region, most of them children, died of weather-related causes. It
said most of the deaths were caused by pneumonia or other bronchial
illnesses.
   The Nuevo Leon governor's office reported that, despite the cold,
only 350 people spent Tuesday night in 21 emergency shelters
established for indigents.
   Citrus growers said it was too early to estimate freeze-related
damage to 110,000 tons of oranges ready for harvest next month in
Montemorelos, hub of the Nuevo Leon citrus region about 50 miles
southwest of Monterrey.
   Alberto Escamilla Elizondo, the state agriculture secretary, was
quoted in the federal government newspaper El Nacional as saying the
crop could withstand temperatures of 18 degrees for up to 24 hours.
Much of the citrus grown in Nuevo Leon is exported to the United
States.
   A freeze in 1983 destroyed half the state's 8 million citrus
trees and production levels have just begun to reach former levels.
   About 300 head of cattle died because of the cold in Tamaulipas
state, the government news agency Notimex reported Wednesday. It
said budding crops of corn, beans and sorghum were affected, but did
not give loss estimates.
   The Agriculture Department meteorological service said the freeze
could last through Thursday.
</TEXT>
