<DOCNO> AP890208-0218 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-08-89 2005EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-NorthTrial 3rdLd-Writethru a0791 02-08 1038</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-North Trial, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0791,1070</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Rejects Justice Department's Motion On Additional Safeguards</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 2nd graf to show ruling will be appealed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The judge in Oliver North's trial on Wednesday
denied a Justice Department demand for more stringent controls over
any state secrets the former national security council aide might
try to use in his defense.
   Before he ruled, U.S. District Judge Gerhard Gesell invited the
Justice Department to take its demand to the U.S. Court of Appeals.
David Runkel, a Justice Department spokesman, said after the Gesell
ruling that the decision would be appealed.
   Earlier in the day, the department brought North's Iran-Contra
trial to a temporary halt by demanding a court order that North
``disclose no classified information in any form'' except with the
approval of the court and the Justice Department.
   Gesell was angry over the delay on the eve of opening arguments
and said jury selection would resume Thursday.
   ``I want to do my level best to protect the national secrets of
this country,'' Gesell told Deputy Assistant Attorney General
Stephen A. Saltzburg. ``I want to do even more to give this man a
fair trial. This is not a trial of national security; it's a trial
of Oliver North.''
   At issue is a Jan. 19 order in which Gesell outlined what
classified information North will be allowed to present in his
defense in open court.
   U.S. intelligence agencies have indicated worry that portions of
the order are too broad and would allow North to introduce secrets
that could harm national security.
   ``You can't ride this horse in both directions,'' the judge said.
``You can either move to protect national security or you can move
to a fair trial. Congress says that if push comes to shove, a trial
judge has one option, to move toward a fair trial.''
   The Justice Department said in a motion filed Wednesday that
North, a former National Security Council aide, ``has made no effort
to assist the court in dealing responsibly with classified
information.''
   The department said North has provided ``totally useless or at
best minimally informative'' notices of the documents he wants to
disclose.
   When the matter came up, Gesell had just finished qualifying 35
women and 10 men to be on the panel from which the jury will be
chosen. He sent the prospective jurors home and held an afternoon
hearing in the unusual situation that confronted him _ the Justice
Department stepping into an area the independent counsel previously
had handled.
   ``For a month I asked the attorney general to these hearings and
he never came,'' Gesell told Saltzburg. ``Now you come to the
conclusion that we start at square one all over.''
   Specifically, the department asked Gesell to forbid North
disclose any classified information to which it had any objection.
The proposed order would also say that Gesell must rule any
classified information was relevant and admissible before it could
be brought before the jury.
   In court, the judge said he wasn't going to tolerate a ``cuckoo
clock trial'' which would be constantly interrupted with reviews of
classified material before it is introduced in the courtroom.
   ``We have no wish to impose a cuckoo clock trial,'' responded
Saltzburg. ``We have an obligation to protect'' classified material
that could harm national security and ``there is some information
that cannot be put back in a bottle.'' He said having jurors sit
through such interminable delays ``is not a trial. That is a farce.''
   Independent counsel Lawrence Walsh opposed the Justice Department
request, telling the judge, ``We're ready to go to trial and we
don't want delays.'' He said he trusted North attorney Brendan
Sullivan not to ``trick or trap this court at the expense of
national security.''
   The department said in its written motion that ``At this stage,
the United States faces a trial at which important classified
information is at risk ... there is every reason to believe that
irrelevant or immaterial classified information might be revealed
during the trial.''
   The case of North, a former Marine lieutenant colonel attached to
the National Security Council who is charged with 12 criminal counts
stemming from the Iran-Contra affair, is being prosecuted not by the
Justice Department but by lawyers who work for Walsh.
   The argument is only the latest in a long legal trail over the
secrets North says he must disclose to adequately defend himself
against charges that he concealed from Congress his efforts on
behalf of the Nicaraguan Contras and of covering up from the
attorney general the National Security Council's role in diverting
money from the Iran arms sales to the Contras.
   Two major charges, conspiracy and theft, were dropped last month
after the Reagan administration said it could not declassify
documents that Gesell had ruled would be needed for North to get a
fair trial on those counts.
   The department said in its motion that Gesell has issued only
``general guidance'' on the relevance and admissibility of secret
information so ``the parties are left to their own devices to
determine in opening statements, direct examination, and
cross-examination as to what classified information to mention.''
   It also said the 1980 Classified Information Procedures Act set
guidelines to permit prosecutions to go forward, but ``the
procedures adopted by the court ... fail to implement the most
important features of CIPA.'' He said, ``Additional procedures are
required.''
   Gesell disclosed in court that he had been holding a request from
North's lawyers not to apply that law in the case, waiting for
developments. Now, he said, if the appeals court goes along with the
Justice Department ``my strong inclination would be not to apply
CIPA at all.''
   Under the act, the attorney general may file an affidavit
objecting to disclosure of classified material and the court must
then order that the defendant not disclose the information.
   The judge said he was a layman in national security matters and
would leave decisions on what would breach security to the
government.
   ``I'm going to stay out of your turf, but I am not ready to let
you run mine,'' he told Saltzburg. ``I'm going to have a fair trial
or we won't have a trial.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
