<FIRST>r i AM-Paraguay     02-08 0536</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Paraguay,0551</SECOND>
<HEAD>Central Bank Moves to Recover Funds Funneled To Officials Of Ousted
Goverment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE HANDLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Central Bank tightened control over
withdrawals by some government agencies Wednesday, apparently to
recover funds diverted before the ouster of President Alfredo
Stroessner.
   Stroessner, toppled last week in a military coup led by Gen.
Andres Rodriguez, was accused Tuesday of personally controlling at
least two accounts funded by public money.
   The Central Bank, Paraguay's equivalent of the U.S. Federal
Reserve Board, said the reason for the measure was ``to obtain
better control and greater clarification of the destination, and
correct application, of public funds.''
   It said the action could cause delays in the payment of some
government checks but that the withdrawal control would last ``a
short time.'' It did not elaborate.
   In separate developments, the ex-director of the post office,
Manuel Esquivel, shot and wounded himself in the head in an apparent
suicide attempt after the new government announced an investigation
of the post office, newspapers reported Wednesday.
   Education Minister Dionisio Gonzalez Torres said teachers no
longer will be required to be members of the ruling Colorado Party
as a condition of employment. During the nearly 35-year Stroessner
regime, which came to an end Friday, all public employees were
required to belong to the party.
   Stroessner, 76, reportedly ailing, was sent Sunday into exile in
neighboring Brazil.
   Gen. Juan Antonio Caceres, minister of public works and
communications until Rodriguez took over as provisional president
and fired the Cabinet, said Tuesday that Stroesner had personal
signature power over two accounts totaling more than $4 million. The
money came from highway tolls and gasoline taxes.
   Caceres said he didn't know what Stroessner used the money for,
but he said the funds generally were not available for use by his
ministry.
   Charges of personal corruption under Stroesser during his nearly
35 years in power were widespread. Opposition politicians,
persecuted under Stroessner but now allowed to speak freely, have
called for the creation of a special commission to recover
government money that was misallocated under the old regime.
   Aldo Zuccolillo, publisher of the newspaper ABC Color, closed by
Stroessner but now prepared to reopen, supported the Central Bank
action.
   ``This was taxpayers' money being administered as though it were
a personal checking account,'' Zuccolillo said in an interview.
``There must be dozens more accounts like this linked to other
government ministries in state-run companies.''
   The publisher said he had no proof that such was the case but
expected the Central Bank review of withdrawals will reveal some.
   In other developments, attorney Pedro Abilio Rolon has filed a
citizens' suit with the Supreme Court against three ex-government
ministers and Stroessner's longtime personal secretary, Mario Abdo
Benitez.
   The suit filed Monday accused the four of using public funds and
accepting bribes to obtain mansions, apartments, and autos worth
much more than they could afford on public salaries; and sought to
embargo their local bank accounts.
   Benitez is under arrest. Among the three others, ex-Interior
Minister Sabino Montanaro was given a safe conduct out of the
country. Ex-Justice Minister Eugenio Jacquet and ex-Public Health
Minister Adan Godoy Jimenez were believed to be out of the country.
</TEXT>
