<FIRST>u a AM-ChildrenBurned 1stLd-Writethru a0734 02-08 0473</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Children Burned, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0734,0482</SECOND>
<HEAD>Father Sets Torch to Self, Two Children, Sheriff Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with names of victims, details; adds byline.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY EYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FLOWOOD, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A father poured gasoline over himself and
his two children, then set them ablaze, according to investigators
who found all three bodies in the man's locked truck.
   ``I certainly think it was deliberately set,'' said Deputy George
McKay, an arson investigator for the Rankin County sheriff's
department. ``Someone poured the gasoline on them. ... I would have
to say the adult poured the gasoline.''
   McKay said investigators also were looking into the possibility
that the children were slain before the father pulled into the
parking lot of Woman's Hospital in Flowood, where his ex-wife was
working.
   ``I don't know anybody's children who wouldn't scream and holler
... if someone was rendering these children helpless. Someone would
have heard them scream. There are people in this parking lot all the
time and on the road,'' he said. ``We feel they had met their demise
before they ever came to this parking lot.''
   Lt. Johnny Watkins, a criminal investigator with the Flowood
Police Department, said the ex-wife reported the couple hadn't been
arguing.
   ``They had spoken earlier in the day but there was nothing
indicating what was ahead,'' Watkins said. ``He was not violent on
the phone and there was nothing out of the ordinary.''
   County Coroner Jimmy Roberts identified the dead as 29-year-old
Benny Bilbrew; his son, Benny Carl Bilbrew, 6, and his daughter,
Fecia Bilbrew, 5, all of nearby Jackson. Bilbrew was a self-employed
concrete worker.
   Watkins said there were no witnesses to the 12:30 p.m. fire and
that Bilbrew and the childen died immediately.
   McKay said hospital personnel noticed the fire only after the
explosion of some shotgun shells sitting in the burning truck. He
said no gun was found in the truck, although a knife was recovered.
He also said no gasoline container was recovered.
   The children's mother, Connie Bilbrew, was at work in the
hospital cafeteria when the fire occurred. Watkins said she had to
be sedated after being told of the deaths. He said she wouldn't be
questioned at length until Friday at the earliest.
   However, he said Mrs. Bilbrew indicated in a brief interview
immediately after the fire that the couple had divorced about two
years ago, but had lived together for about a year until they split
up again a few weeks ago.
   Watkins said Mrs. Bilbrew had custody of the children, but she
said they had been visiting their father since Monday because an ice
storm had closed schools this week.
   Hospital Administrator Tom Fitz said the explosion didn't damage
the hospital and the incident didn't disrupt services.
   But he said, ``People are really upset here. It's been really
emotional.''
</TEXT>
