<FIRST>u i AM-UN-CentralAmerica 3rdLd-Writethru   02-08 0606</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Central America, 3rd Ld-Writethru,a0804,0624</SECOND>
<HEAD>Central Americans Ask U.N. For Inspectors To Prevent Subversion</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with Costa Rica saying observers
will be military. Pick up 8th pvs, `A joint...' with minor editing to trim</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five Central American nations that have
signed a regional peace accord asked the United Nations on Wednesday
to send inspectors to verify that none of their countries supports
subversion against a neighbor.
   Foreign Ministry officials from Nicaragua, Honduras, Guatemala,
El Salvador and Costa Rica asked U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez
de Cuellar to send West German, Spanish and Canadian inspectors to
their nations.
   They also asked that Latin Americans be included in the
inspection team.
   ``All the people who participate in this process will be military
(observers), but they are not going to be armed,'' said Foreign
Minister Rodrigo Madrigal Nieto of Costa Rica.
   ``It will not be a large group of soldiers; they are just
observers.''
   Perez de Cuellar, who met Central American Foreign Ministry
officials on Wednesday, told reporters he is considering sending
military observers.
   The Central American proposal, submitted in a letter in Spanish
on Wednesday to the U.N. chief, breathes new life into the peace
plan initiated by President Oscar Arias of Costa Rica, who received
the Nobel Peace Prize for his efforts in 1987.
   Plans for the force have already been drafted, U.N. officials
said on condition of anonymity, and Spain, Canada and West Germany
have agreed to contribute observers.
   A joint U.N.-Organization of American States team that went to
Central America in 1987 recommended unarmed civilian inspectors,
possibly backed with military advisers, and the ministers' letter
urged Perez de Cuellar to rely on its recommendations.
   Honduras, a key U.S. ally where the Contras have bases to launch
raids into neighboring Nicaragua, blocked the 1987 plan by refusing
to allow inspections of military sites.
   Now Honduras has backed the plan. Some observers say Honduras is
afraid the presence of the Contras will prompt Nicaragua's superior
forces to cross into Honduras.
   The United States has accused Nicaragua of aiding leftist rebels
fighting a U.S.-backed government in El Salvador.
   In their letter, the Central American Foreign Ministry officials
specified that the inspectors would make sure no country harbors
rebels fighting another government or aids an insurrection in
another country.
   The U.S. Mission to the United Nations will not comment on such a
force until after the latest round of talks end Thursday, said
Helene Mahoney, a U.S. spokeswoman.
   Wilfredo Montalvan, one of seven directors of the Nicaraguan
Resistance, an umbrella group of rebels, said in Miami on Wednesday,
``The position of the secretary-general is incomplete. . .. It
doesn't to any good to send military groups to the Nicaraguan border
when people inside the country are rebelling against aggression.''
   He said the United States should also try to ensure the
democratization of Nicaragua and not just check on rebels at the
borders.
   ``We are at this time readying a new peace plan that includes
disarming the Nicaraguan Resistance, but only when there is proof of
democracy inside Nicaragua,'' Montalvan said.
   He said that peace plan will be ready by Sunday.
   The foreign ministers of the five nations reached basic agreement
on the inspection plan when they met for presidential inaugurations
in Mexico in December and Venezuela last week.
   West Germany would have to send civilian observers because its
constitution prohibits sending military forces abroad, said a West
German diplomat on condition of anonymity.
   The presidents of the five Central American nations are to hold a
two-day summit in El Salvador beginning Monday.
</TEXT>
