<FIRST>r a AM-MoscowMoney     02-08 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Moscow Money,0358</SECOND>
<HEAD>Director of U.S.-Soviet Group Denies Wrongdoing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The director of a U.S.-Soviet cultural exchange
group denied federal charges Wednesday that he tried to conceal
money provided by a Soviet organization the FBI has called a
Communist Party front.
   Alan Thomson, 57, accused the FBI of scare tactics in making the
criminal charges and said the agency falsely described his
organization, the National Council of American-Soviet Friendship, as
a pro-Soviet propaganda group.
   ``What's behind this is an accusation of espionage that they
don't dare make,'' said Thomson. ``Because they can't. They know
there's no basis.''
   Thomson was arrested Tuesday on an indictment charging that he
tried to evade bank reporting requirements on $17,000 he received in
Moscow from the USSR Society for Friendship and Cultural Relations
with Foreign Countries.
   The FBI has said the society directs activities of Thomson's
group and in turn is run by the Soviet Communist Party to distribute
``disinformation,'' or propaganda meant to enhance the Soviet
Union's image.
   Thomson called that ``nonsense,'' saying his group was a
non-partisan, independent organization involved in U.S.-Soviet
visitor exchanges. ``We have no political line,'' he said in a
telephone interview.
   He refused to discuss the criminal charges, but denied wrongdoing.
   Thomson said his group has an agreement with the USSR Friendship
Society under which the groups send each other tourists and
exhibits. He said he did not know if the Communist Party runs the
society, but called that FBI charge ``scare language'' that could
neither be proved nor disproved.
   Such charges ``are part of the operation that goes way, way back
that anybody who doesn't agree with the administration must be
sinister,'' Thomson said. ``They're trying to put a scare into the
peace movement.''
   The indictment alleged that Thomson had the $17,000 deposited in
a Buffalo bank in two transactions each under $10,000, evading the
requirement that the government be notified of transactions of
$10,000 or more.
   He was released after his arrest on a $100,000 personal
recognizance bond. The charges carry a maximum of five years in
prison and a $250,000 fine.
</TEXT>
