<DOCNO> AP890208-0234 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-08-89 2344EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-AIDSTesting 1stld-writethru a0739 02-08 0457</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS Testing, 1st ld-writethru, a0739,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 1st graf to CORRECT Day of week to Wednesday, sted Tuesday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Food and Drug Administration has scheduled
a public hearing for early April to more closely examine the
prospects for AIDS antibody testing kits which could be used in the
home, officials said Wednesday.
   The issue of home AIDS testing has been surrounded by
controversy, and the FDA has been concerned that the tests be
accurate and that adequate counseling could be incorporated into a
home-testing system for the fatal disease.
   ``The whole Public Health Service is very much concerned that you
have a system that gives adequate results and that the results can
be explained to people,'' said Paul Parkman, director of the FDA
office that regulates the materials used in the test kits.
   ``It also has implications for behavior,'' he said. ``If people
are indulging in high-risk behavior and want to be tested, they
should have some contact with people to tell them they should not
run those risks.''
   On the other hand, the Public Health Service, of which FDA is a
part, also feels AIDS testing should be widely available, ``and
there are some people who don't want to go to the doctor and be
tested'' but would test themselves at home, he said.
   The dilemma has so far kept home-testing kits off the market.
   The FDA last April turned back requests by manufacturers who
wanted to market an AIDS test kit, and the agency said research on
such kits would have to be done in hospitals, clinics and other
traditional health care settings.
   Parkman said he knew of no manufacturers who had applied for
permission to conduct market research as restricted by the FDA.
   The FDA also said at the time it would hold a public hearing in
the future, which could lead the agency to revise its policy against
the tests.
   The hearing is scheduled for April 6.
   The kind of test that has the greatest chances of meeting with
FDA approval would allow someone to puncture a finger, extract a few
drops of blood that would be absorbed by a piece of filter paper and
send the sample to a laboratory. The same tests currently used by
doctors, hospitals and clinics would be performed on the sample to
detect the presence of AIDS antibodies.
   The person would get the results of the test by calling the lab
and giving a personal code number.
   But Public Health Service guidelines say any testing should be
accompanied by appropriate counseling, and health officials are
concerned that telephone contact may not be enough to deal with the
emotional impact of learning one has a life-threatening disease.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
