<HEAD>Aerial Search Resumed for Missing Japanese Fishermen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WELLINGTON, New Zealand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An air force plane on Thursday
resumed a search for 15 missing Japanese fishermen whose trawler
caught fire in the South Pacific a week ago.
   The aerial search was called off Wednesday but was continued at
the urging of the Japanese Embassy, said External Relations director
for North Asia, Christopher Butler.
   Twenty-two ships were to continue the search even after the
aerial search was called off, said air force spokesman Doug Bray.
   Butler said the stricken vessel, the 299-ton Sankichi Maru No.
18, was sighted drifting about 400 miles west of Auckland. Rescuers
found the body of one crewmember on the ship Sunday.
   Searchers believe the rest of the crew escaped in a life raft
when the vessel caught fire Feb. 2 in the Tasman Sea about 480 miles
off northwestern New Zealand.
   The search has covered thousands of square miles of ocean and no
trace of the crew has been found, officials said. Winds of 70 mph
and heavy seas have hampered the search effort.
</TEXT>
