<FIRST>u a AM-StrandedDancers 1stLd-Writethru a0829 02-08 0478</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Stranded Dancers, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0829,0487</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stranded Soviet Dancers Stage Fund-Raising Performance To Save Tour</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 3rd graf with two grafs to UPDATE with proceeds.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM PAUL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet ballet troupe, lacking the financial
backing to continue its debut U.S. tour, staged a free performance
Wednesday that enticed hundreds of dance lovers to fill a wicker
suitcase with cash and checks.
   Officials still were not sure whether the Donetsk Ballet dancers
would be able to complete their 15-city tour, which originally was
scheduled to run into April.
   ``We have a meeting after this performance and we'll have to work
it out at that time,'' Lyric Opera president Robert M. Pomory said
just before intermission.
   Pomory said later that the benefit had brought in about $4,000
that will be used to provide food and shelter for the dancers.
   The troupe's financial troubles began when a group of California
and Mexican investors withdrew $200,000 last week upon learning that
dancers from well-known Soviet troupes couldn't leave the Soviet
Union to join the tour.
   Arts patrons, Pomory and the Howard Gilman Foundation of New York
responded by donating meals and cash so the dancers could be put up
in a Baltimore hotel while the tour's future was sorted out.
   Wednesday's benefit drew an enthusiastic crowd of more than 600
people who paid no admission, but were asked to donate cash to help
the tour continue.
   ``It's tragic what's happened,'' said John Talbott just after he
dropped a check in the wicker suitcase at the entrance to the Lyric
Opera House. ``A lot of America is going to miss a really exciting
classical troupe if they are not supportive.''
   Talbott and his wife, Susan, said they remembered seeing the
famed Bolshoi Ballet when it made its first U.S. tour in 1959. They
had high reviews for the Donetsk troupe, most of whom are under 25.
   ``They really are marvelous. I'm ashamed that the place is not
overflowing,'' Susan Talbott said.
   Several times during the performance, the crowd broke into
applause and shouts of ``Bravo!''
   ``I wanted to support them. I think it's important that a
community respond to a human need such as this when they're such
fine artists,'' said Martin Siegel of Columbia.
   The performance Wednesday was as much an expression of thanks by
the dancers as it was a way to raise money, Pomory said.
   ``The dancers want the people of Baltimore to know this is from
the bottom of their hearts,'' he said.
   The troupe had performances booked in Detroit, Chicago and
Columbus, Ohio. The dancers arrived in late January and their first
performance was Feb. 2 in Baltimore.
   Soviet dance star Vadim Pisarev was allowed to join the troupe
but several other well-known dancers were not, said organizer Jan
Urdzik of California-based Heart of the Art Inc.
</TEXT>
