<DOCNO> AP890208-0240 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-08-89 0804EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a w PM-WalterMears ADV09   02-08 0749</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Walter Mears, ADV 09,0771</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv 09</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Thurs Feb 09 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>When In Doubt, Nominate a Senator</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WALTER R. MEARS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Even in times of trouble or political
controversy about a Cabinet choice, nominating a senator _ past or
present _ usually opens a smooth, fast track to Senate confirmation.
   Not this time.
   Secretary of Defense-designate John Tower is the problem nominee
in President Bush's Cabinet class of '89, although a 24-year Senate
career has so far enabled him to withstand challenges that probably
would have undone an outsider.
   While it is evident that some among Tower's former colleagues
would have preferred a different Pentagon choice, President Bush and
his spokesmen almost surely are correct in maintaining that in a
Senate vote, he would be confirmed.
   No newly elected president has been denied confirmation of a
nominee to his first Cabinet. And the administration insists there
has been no thought of withdrawing the selection Bush announced
nearly two months ago, after a preview round of controversy.
   Tower and Louis Sullivan, the black educator nominated to head
the Department of Health and Human Services, are the last Cabinet
nominees awaiting confirmation.
   Their cases illustrate the advantages of a Senate resume.
   The Tower nomination has been delayed by investigations involving
his personal life _ women and whiskey in Texas parlance.
   That overshadowed the question of his high-priced consulting work
for defense contractors after he left the Senate in 1985. There are
no restrictions on such activities by former members of Congress as
soon as they leave office.
   Tower's consultant fees totaled more than $763,000.
   ``That's heavy bucks,'' Sen. Alan Simpson, R-Wyo., said Sunday.
``I think that's more of a conflict than anything with regard to his
personality.''
   Sullivan is taking unpaid leave from Morehouse University School
of Medicine in order to join the Bush Cabinet. In the process, he is
forfeiting $297,000 in sabbatical leave pay earned over 13 years as
president of the Atlanta medical school in order to avoid any
appearance of a conflict of interest.
   The school gets about $5.8 million a year through the Department
of Health and Human Services.
   That's small change in the world of defense contracts.
   Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., chairman of the Armed Services Committee,
told Tower he was concerned about the perception of those consultant
fees. ``I know you to be an honest person,'' he told Tower, a former
chairman. ``But I do worry about the perception.''
   The Tower confirmation hearings may also stir some worry among
other consultants about customer perceptions of their services.
Tower said he got the fees for ``enlightened guesswork,'' and for
being available when clients called.
   ``I gave them sort of academic advice on what could happen,'' he
said. ``Any number of think tanks in town could have given them more
detailed analysis.''
   That kind of candor could spoil things in the business Tower left
behind when he canceled his consultant contracts on Dec. 1, a day
after Bush aides contacted him about possible Pentagon appointment.
   Tower has said that the consultant fees would not influence his
Pentagon decisions, and he has denied that his personal habits are
out of line. He said he has no drinking problem and that a secretary
of defense must at all times be capable of exercising the duties of
his office.
   President Bush said the Senate is performing properly by looking
into every question involving Tower, even though ``The process is
taking a little longer than I would like.'' Confirmation hangups are
not customary for senators who need approval of their former
colleagues.
   That's one reason Senate names have been sent to the Senate in
times of political strain.
   After the Saturday night massacre in 1973, Richard M. Nixon
needed an attorney general to succeed Elliot L. Richardson, who quit
in defiance of White House orders to fire the special Watergate
prosecutor. Nixon chose Sen. William B. Saxbe of Ohio, who was
confirmed by the Democratic Senate with a minimum of Watergate
debate.
   In 1980, Secretary of State Cyrus R. Vance resigned because he
disagreed with President Carter's attempt to rescue the American
hostages in Tehran by force. Carter chose Sen. Edmund S. Muskie of
Maine to succeed him, gaining Senate approval without refueling the
controversy.
   Former Sen. Tower brought controversy with him.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Walter R. Mears, vice president and columnist for
The Associated Press, has reported on Washington for more than 25
years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890208-0241 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-08-89 1315EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a PM-OntheMoney Adv09   02-08 0585</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-On the Money, Adv 09,0601</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv 09</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Thurs. Feb 9</HEAD>
<HEAD>Tax Filing The High-Tech Way</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Get your tax refund fast, the high-technology way!
   That's the pitch offered by increasing numbers of tax preparers
and financial institutions trying to attract customers in the 1989
income tax filing season.
   To deliver on their promise, they use the Internal Revenue
Service's electronic filing system, through which individual returns
are filed directly by computer over telephone lines, rather than
through the mail.
   Last year 500,000 of the approximately 107 million returns
received by the IRS were filed electronically, according to Wilson
Fadley, an IRS spokesman.
   This year the service expects the number to reach 2 million.
``It's kind of a wave of the future,'' Fadley says.
   Electronic filing is available in 36 states this year through
some 4,000 IRS-approved data transmitters, including tax-preparation
firms and computer service bureaus that work with banks and other
financial institutions.
   Plans call for the system to operate nationwide next year at this
time, Fadley says.
   To find out if and where electronic filing is available in your
state, the Arthur Young Tax Guide advises inquiring at your local
IRS Taxpayer Service or the toll-free national information number
1-800-424-1040, and asking for the ``electronic filing coordinator.''
   Judging from several test calls made on a recent weekday morning,
getting through on the toll-free number may take patience and
persistence.
   Electronic filing isn't available to individuals using their own
personal computers, though it may be someday. Thus, you can expect
to have to pay someone to provide it for you, either in the form of
an explicit charge or built into a tax preparer's fee.
   For example, the Dollar Dry Dock Bank in the New York
metropolitan area charges $45.
   What are the benefits? The most tangible is faster access to your
federal tax refund _ especially if you have a large amount due you.
   But there are other pluses as well. As your return is processed
for electronic filing, any mathematical errors you may have made are
likely to be detected.
   With electronic filing, you get a confirmation from the IRS that
your return has been received.
   The IRS likes the system too, since it reduces the costs of
processing returns.
   People who owe additional taxes can't use the system as it is set
up now. If you're in this position, you're probably in no rush to
pay anyway, unless you were underwithheld in 1988 by so much that
you are threatened with penalties and interest charges.
   Before you deal with a bank or other financial institution that
promotes electronic filing services, investigate all the trappings
of the arrangement.
   A bank may even offer to deposit the amount of your refund on the
spot into an account in your name.
   If this involves opening a new account, it makes sense to inquire
what sort of an account it is, what interest it will pay, and
whether there are any restrictions on withdrawing the money and
closing the account.
   Would-be electronic filers might feel leery of getting involved
in direct dealings with the IRS's computers. The process strikes
some people as the sort of high-profile activity that invites extra
scrutiny from the IRS and its auditors.
   Not so, the authorities say. The Arthur Young Tax Guide offers
the solemn assurance that ``electronic filing neither increases nor
decreases the possibility that your return will be audited.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Thurs. Feb 9.</NOTE>
</DOC>
