<FIRST>a w AM-Diplomat'sWife Adv13   02-08 0581</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Diplomat's Wife, Adv 13,0597</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv13</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Mon AMs, Feb. 13, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Austrian Ambassador's Wife Launches Own War on Drugs</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Claire Hoess, wife of the Austrian ambassador,
does her share of tea-pouring at diplomatic receptions, but her real
passion lies elsewhere: she's determined to fight the war on drugs.
   ``You can't beat this problem from above ... you have to shock
the kids,'' says the English-born Mrs. Hoess, a lanky woman who
wears her blonde hair cropped short and likes to relax in jeans.
   Soon after she moved here about a year ago, Mrs. Hoess vowed
she'd do something constructive to fight drugs in a city which last
year had the highest murder rate in the country.
   Police blame much of the crime on the drug dealing that takes
place in neighborhoods just a few miles away from Mrs. Hoess'
residence.
   On a trip to New York, Mrs. Hoess visited Daytop Village, a
leading drug treatment center where former addicts performed a
gritty, improvisational play based on their experiences in the
depths of a depraved drug world.
   So impressed was Mrs. Hoess with the play, entitled, ``The
Concept,'' that she decided to bring it to Washington for two
performances.
   ``I'm not doing this as a social event,'' Mrs. Hoess said in an
interview. ``I want it to have an impact.''
   To that end, Mrs. Hoess arranged for the District of Columbia
school system to have high school seniors attend a scheduled
performance Monday at a local theater.
   Members of the diplomatic corps and other Washingtonians have
been invited to a second performance.
   ``We think it's a great idea,'' said Marilyn Tyler Brown, an
assistant school superintendent. ``The students will get to see
people who have been through a substance abuse program.''
   Mrs. Hoess' initiative is ``more unusual than typical'' in the
diplomatic circuit where some women do volunteer work, but few
launch out in their own projects, according to Phyllis Moyer,
executive director of The Hospitality and Information Service, a
non-profit group that helps foreign diplomats adjust to Washigton.
   Mrs. Hoess, who sometimes spends her free time driving around the
city to get a first-hand look at the seamier parts of town, raised
money to bring the troupe to Washington and then convinced a
hotelier to donate rooms for two nights. She even got inmates at a
local prison, the Lorton correctional complex, to print the
invitations.
   Mrs. Hoess was awakened to the drug problem in the early 1970s.
   ``I saw what was happening to the friends and their children,''
she said, citing one case in which a 12-year-old walked through a
window.
   Back in Vienna, headquarters of the U.N. narcotics bureau, Mrs.
Hoess plunged into fighting drugs on an international level. She
studied the problem and learned about the drug culture.
   Since coming to the United States, she has toured drug
rehabilitation centers in New York and Atlanta, and talked to
business leaders and bankers about devoting more money to such
facilities.
   Mrs. Hoess said she likes to be personally involved in issues.
While visiting Zaire once, she traveled to a leper colony in the
bush that had been set up by Albert Schweitzer.
   The staff wanted to give Mrs. Hoess the hands-off tour for
dignitaries, but she rejected that idea.
   ``I put on my dirty old jeans and started cleaning the floors
like the other people,'' she recalled.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for AMs Mon, Feb. 13</NOTE>
</DOC>
