<FIRST>a w AM-PresidentsCashIn Adv13-1stAdd   02-08 0373</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Presidents Cash In, Adv13-1st Add,0378</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv13</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Mon AMs, Feb. 13, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>WASHN: the offer.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Lyndon B. Johnson donated profits estimated at $1.5 million from
his memoirs, ``The Vantage Point,'' to support the LBJ library in
Austin and the LBJ School of Public Affairs, according to library
archivist Claudia Anderson. Johnson also was paid a reported
$300,000 for three hour-long interviews with CBS; Ms. Anderson said
she could not determine whether this money also went to support the
library and school.
   As for Reagan, the former film star was asked during his flight
home to California on Jan. 20 whether, with the White House behind
him, he might make any more movies. He replied, ``No, there is kind
of a lingering feeling that would look a little bit like trying to
cash in on this job that I've had.''
   Six days later, Simon &amp; Schuster announced that Reagan had signed
a contract for the two books. Terms were not disclosed, but industry
sources said the former president could easily command $5 million.
   The next day, Bernie Swain, a partner in the Washington Speakers
Bureau, said he was signing both the former president and his wife,
Nancy, to a contract making the bureau their exclusive lecture
agent. Again the terms were not announced, but sources said Reagan
should get about $40,000 a speech.
   During Senate hearings in recent years on legislation to limit
ex-presidents' office allowances, concern was expressed that staff
paid by the taxpayers could be used to help them write for profit.
   Nixon aide Taylor said, ``He has always taken pains to maintain
separate accounting and make sure that all expenses having to do
with the personnel and equipment used to assist him in his research
are paid for from his own funds.''
   Barrett, speaking for Ford, also said, ``We kept everything very
separate.''
   Stuart Applebaum, director of public relations for Bantam Books,
which published ``Keeping Faith,'' said Carter ``writes his books
himself.''
   Weinberg, asked if staff paid out of Reagan's office allowance
would be involved in preparation of his memoirs, said, ``No, nobody
here has done anything of that nature so far, and I haven't heard
any discussion of it.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, Feb. 13</NOTE>
