<FILEID>AP-NR-02-08-89 1316EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a w BC-Afghan-US Adv00   02-08 0491</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Afghan-US, Adv00,0506</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>Adv for Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>US Hoping for Non-Aligned Government in Kabul</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Part of a package of Afgahn War stories for release anytime.
Items already moved are BC-Afghan Adventure, b0796; ^BC-Afghan-Toll, b0797;
BC-Afghan-Quotes, b0798, and BC-Afghan-Future, b0799, which moved Feb.
7.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Peering through an admittedly cloudly crystal
ball, the Bush administration hopes the departure of Soviet troops
from Afghanistan will produce a friendly non-aligned government that
logically would remain on good terms with Moscow.
   It wouldn't disturb U.S. officials either if the U.S.-armed
guerrillas absorbed some remnants of the Kabul regime into the new
government in an effort to promote unity and avert a bloody
last-ditch defense of Kabul by followers of President Najibullah.
   But the realistic prediction at the State Department is that the
rebels will try to lay siege to Kabul after the last Soviet troops
leave, while the defenders will put up a vigorous, though
short-lived, defense because prospects of amnesty are slim.
   The rebels will continue to receive U.S. arms through Pakistan,
though the flow may slacken because they have recovered a powerful
arsenal from defectors and departing Soviet troops.
   ``There could be a peaceful transfer,'' said a well-placed State
Department official. ``But I doubt it seriously.''
   Ever since the Red Army rolled into Afghanistan in December 1979,
the overriding U.S. policy objective was to force them to go home
again.
   Nearly all of the more than 100,000 troops who backed the
pro-Moscow regime in Kabul are gone. The remants are expected to
depart just before the Feb. 15 deadline set in the Geneva accords of
last April.
   The U.S. objective will soon be met. And U.S. policy is entering
a less anxious phase.
   ``It's still important to have a stable Afghanistan,'' the
official said in an interview Tuesday in which he barred use of his
name. ``We'd like it to have reasonably friendly relations with its
neighbors, first of all our good friend and ally Pakistan.''
   And the United States wishes to have friendly relations with the
new government, as well.
   At the same time, in the U.S. view, economics and geography both
point toward good Afghan relations with the Soviet Union next door.
   The Soviets buy Afghanistan's natural gas and the country is a
major trade route with Pakistan, as well.
   ``Certainly, there isn't going to be an antagonistic regime in
Kabul, although we don't see any Communist regime as prospering,''
the official said.
   But the rebels are divided between ardent Moslem fundamentalists
and less militant guerrillas who reflect the Sunni majority in
Afghanistan. The rebels are also divided on whether to rally around
the former king, Zahir Shah.
   Because of all the uncertainty, the Bush administration is mostly
enjoying the Soviet exodus and keeping its fingers crossed _ and the
weapons flowing.
   ``We don't have a clue how it will play out,'' the official
acknowledged.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
</DOC>
