<FIRST>a a BC-BehindtheWheel Adv18-19   02-08 0671</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Behind the Wheel, Adv 18-19,0686</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv18</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv19</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, Feb. 18-19, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Mazda 929 Glories in Understated Luxury and Convenience</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto and LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN M. JOB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>For The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The 1989 Mazda 929 is a study in understated luxury and
convenience.
   It's easy to see why Mazda is so proud of this, its flagship
vehicle. The 929's 3-liter V-6 _ an 18-valve, fuel-injected
powerplant that produces up to 158 horsepower at 5,500 rpm _ was
smooth and flawless with the four-speed overdrive automatic
transmission. Just touch the accelerator and you felt the car pull
itself together, and zoom, you were off.
   The trunk lid was heavy and there was a solid thud upon closing
the doors, indicative of a solid, well-built car. Inside, the
four-door sedan felt roomy. The optional leather seats were
comfortable and looked plush, yet elegant. Dashboard instruments
were arrayed impressively over two-thirds of the dash but were
clearly marked and easy to read.
   But what do you expect when you lay out $25,000? In the test car,
you could expect more. It had the optional feature that allows
changes in the way the auto rides.
   By touching a button on the center console, the driver can select
soft, sport or automatic suspensions. The soft adjustment puts front
and rear shock absorbers at the normal setting. The sport adjustment
puts them at the firm setting and automatic adjusts their firmness
according to the car's speed.
   I preferred the sport setting and found it to be a nice
compromise between some of the more punishing sport suspensions of
racier cars and the floating sensation on some bigger luxury cars.
   Overall, handling on the 929 was admirable. The car felt nimble
and maneuvered as easily as some smaller cars in tight spaces. The
test 929's transmission also could be switched from economy to power
mode when great acceleration was needed.
   This is accomplished by delaying the shifting to higher speeds
than under the economy mode. The economy mode helps on fuel economy,
however.
   Buyers also should note that the 929 ranked third last year in
having the least number of complaints from new buyers (the Toyota
Cressida and Chevrolet Nova were first and second, respectively.)
   The 1988 Initial Quality Survey, by California marketing firm
J.D. Power and Associates, noted that with the 1988-model 929 _ the
first 929 to appear in the United States _ Mazda had successfully
avoided the quality pitfalls that befall many automakers with new
models.
   I found only one, very minor flaw in the fit and finish of the
test 929. One of two metal flanges for the lid of the center storage
space kept coming out of its slot, making the lid difficult to close
fully.
   Also, because the 929 was rear-drive, it tended to fishtail a bit
on slick road conditions. Mazda said it sold 6,913 of these cars in
calendar 1987 _ the 929's first full year here _ but that rose to
more than 24,250 last year. A spokeswoman said there were no
projections for calendar 1989.
   Typical buyers are what Mazda calls middle-aged parents. Median
age is 45, 70 percent of the buyers are male and 83 percent are
married. The median annual income is $63,900, and 61 percent have
college education.
   Mazda ranked the Acura Legend and Audi cars as major competitors
to the 929 because they are similar in price and size. Because of
the newness of the 929 to the United States, Consumer Reports
magazine had no report of owner complaints.
   A final note: The 929 may not be the last word from Mazda in the
luxury market.
   The company reportedly has been studying whether to follow its
Japanese competitors, Honda, Nissan and Toyota, and bring out new
luxury, performance car products.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Ann Job, former executive business editor of The
Detroit News, writes biweekly automobile reviews for The Associated
Press. She has covered the automobile industry for seven years.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Feb. 18-19</NOTE>
</DOC>
