<HEAD>Yields Rise on Three-Year Notes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yields on three-year Treasury notes rose at
auction to the highest level since August 1985.
   The average yield at Tuesday's auction was 9.18 percent, up from
8.59 percent at the last auction on Nov. 8, 1988.
   It was the highest rate since three-year notes averaged 9.53
percent on Aug. 6, 1985. The notes will carry a coupon interest rate
of 9[ percent with each $10,000 in face value selling for $9,985.90.
   A total of $9.76 billion in notes were sold out of bids totaling
$31.3 billion.
