<DOCNO> AP890208-0257 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-08-89 0201EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-InterestRates Bjt   02-08 0668</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Interest Rates, Bjt,0691</SECOND>
<HEAD>Short-Term Rates Edge Above Long-Term Rates In 7-Year Switch</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A seven-year switch in the pattern of Treasury
bond yields could be a sign of declining inflation but rising
short-term interest rates, economists say.
   On Tuesday, for the first time since April 1982, short-term
interest rates rose above long-term interest rates by a widely
followed measure.
   Economists said the high short-term rates reflected the
tight-money policies of the Federal Reserve, which is trying to
wring inflation out of the economy by discouraging borrowing.
   The economy-watchers said rates on mortgages and consumer loans
could rise in the weeks ahead, but in the long run the tight money
should bring down inflation and interest rates.
   ``The ultimate message is that markets expect future inflation to
be lower than current inflation,'' said Lawrence Kudlow, chief
economist of Bear, Stearns &amp; Co.
   Some other analysts said the switch could spell trouble, noting
that past flip-flops in short- and long-term rates often reflected
credit crunches that led to recessions.
   If banks raise their prime lending rate to cope with the squeeze
by the Fed, a whole range of consumer rates that are tied to the
prime automatically would rise. The prime rate is 10.5 percent and
many analysts predict it soon will be raised to 11 percent.
   Long-term rates are ordinarily higher than short-term rates
because investors demand higher yields in return for the risk of
keeping their money locked up for longer periods.
   But for the last year, short-term rates have been rising and
long-term rates falling, trends that culminated in Tuesday's
flip-flop.
   The rise in short-term rates has been brought about by the
Federal Reserve, which uses the higher rates to discourage
borrowing, cool off the economy and prevent inflation from getting
out of hand.
   Meanwhile, the Fed's tactics have won the confidence of
inflation-wary investors. Because they are no longer demanding such
a big premium to keep their money tied up in bonds, long-term rates
have fallen.
   The so-called inversion of the yield curve occurred Tuesday
morning. By the end of the day, the yield on the Treasury's
three-month Treasury bill was at 8.82 percent and the yield on the
benchmark 30-year bond stood at 8.79 percent.
   By some other measures _ say, comparing yields on the 30-year
bond and the one-year note _ the inversion in yields had already
occurred.
   Kudlow said the inversion in yields signals a decline in
inflation that will be good for both stocks and bonds.
   Skeptics say the Federal Reserve does not have a delicate hand on
the tiller of the economy and is very likely to cause a recession by
pushing short-term rates too high.
   Since the Civil War, all 22 times the yield curve has inverted
there has been a recession or a ``growth'' recession, in which
industrial production declined, according to Raymond Dalio,
president of Bridgewater Associates in Wilton, Conn.
   Dalio said Tuesday that a flat yield curve is necessary for now
because the United States needs high short-term rates to attract
foreign money and prop up the value of the dollar. But, he said, if
the Fed overdoes the tightening, which he expects, there will be ``a
deep downturn emerging at the end of '89 or the beginning of '90.''
   The current situation perplexes money managers, who have to
decide whether to put money into short-term or long-term debt
securities, said Dale Krieger, managing director of Carnegie Hill
Asset Management in New York.
   On one hand, managers can get guaranteed annual returns of 9
percent by putting money into short-term instruments. But by doing
so they miss the chance to get in at the start of what some believe
will be a bull market in bonds brought on by declining inflation.
   Krieger said his firm's clients are playing it safe, passing up
speculation in the bond market and pulling in unusually high yields
on short-term debt. ``For us, this is a gift,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890208-0258 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-08-89 0203EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Networks-Advertisers Bjt   02-08 0653</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Networks-Advertisers, Bjt,0677</SECOND>
<HEAD>Network Execs Solicit Advertisers' Support for Regulation Relaxation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The three major commercial television networks
want relief from regulations limiting how much prime-time
entertainment they can produce for themselves.
   The networks, who say rising program costs have forced them to
boost their ad rates, also want to be able to invest in some of the
shows produced for them, and share in money the shows make after
completing their network run.
   The network executives disclosed Tuesday that they plan to resume
their long-running talks with Hollywood producers aimed at reaching
a compromise on those issues.
   The chief executives at the three networks _ Thomas S. Murphy of
Capital Cities-ABC Inc., Laurence A. Tisch of CBS Inc. and Robert C.
Wright of National Broadcasting Co. _ appealed for support as they
fielded questions for 90 minutes before the Association of National
Advertisers.
   The executives said rising programming costs is the main reason
they have had to boost ad rates.
   The regulation suggestion infuriated independent television
station owners, who say viewers would have fewer choices if the
networks had greater financial interests in programming.
   ``This is a naked attempt by the networks to regain their former
position of total domination of the broadcast television business,''
said Preston Padden, head of the Association of Independent
Television Stations.
   DeWitt Helm Jr., president of the Association of National
Advertisers, said an ANA committee was studying the matter.
   The network trio's appearance came as the networks' combined
share of the viewing audience has fallen due to the rise of
independent stations, cable networks, pay television and
videocassette recorders.
   Tisch said the networks' share of the prime-time viewing audience
slipped to 68 percent last year from 90 percent a decade ago, but
that he expected it would bottom out at about 64-65 percent over the
next few years.
   ABC's Murphy conceded, ``We are not as good as we once were but
we are still the best buy in town.''
   Murphy said the networks are hurt because they are limited to
producing no more than five hours of entertainment programming each
week for the 22 hours in their prime-time schedule, and cannot share
in any of the financial rewards of programs sold for reruns after
completing a network run.
   Murphy said the networks were proposing that they be allowed to
produce or have a financial interest in 11 hours of prime-time
programming a week.
   NBC's Wright said the federal restrictions tie the networks'
hands even as they must compete for programs with nearly two dozen
cable networks unconstrained by program ownership limits.
   Jack Valenti, head of the Motion Picture Association of America,
said the program producers have offered a compromise that would
allow the networks to own a half share in a limited number of
programs.
   Without an agreement, Valenti said the restrictions on network
ownership of programs is due to expire starting in late 1990.
   Valenti said the restrictions, in effect since 1970, have served
the consumer by encouraging the proliferation of independent
stations and program choices.
   ``The key issue is maintaining the balance of power in the
marketplace,'' he said. He declined say whether a compromise with
the networks is near.
   On other issues, the network executives were asked whether the
NBC and ABC alliances with cable in recent years amount to
consorting with the enemy.
   NBC's Wright said the cable ventures are ``a logical extension''
of what his network does. Murphy, whose company also cable
interests, said Capital Cities-ABC took that position as well.
   But CBS's Tisch said he has found ``less there than meets the
eye'' and said CBS is better off to focus all its efforts on
broadcast operations.
   Murphy and Tisch said they would be open to considering an
advertiser-produced series. But Wright said a potential problem is
the ill will created if the network cancels the series because of
poor ratings.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
