<FILEID>AP-NR-02-08-89 0206EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-EEC-USMeat Bjt   02-08 0556</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-EEC-US Meat, Bjt,0574</SECOND>
<HEAD>Europeans Ready To Protest U.S. Retaliatory Sanctions</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Lead prospects uncertain.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   European officials plan to up the ante
in a trade battle that has been brewing for weeks over stiff tariffs
imposed by the United States in retaliation for a ban on
hormone-treated meat from America.
   Officials of the 12-nation European Economic Community will press
to have the duties declared in violation of international trade
rules at a meeting today of the General Agreement on Tariffs and
Trade in Geneva. The 96-nation GATT offers a forum for settling
trade disputes among its members.
   Meanwhile, a flurry of visits among high-level officials from the
United States and the Common Market trading bloc were scheduled in
the coming weeks, giving both sides a fresh chance to resolve the
stubborn dispute.
   Frans Andriessen, the EEC's top trading official, was scheduled
to travel to Washington Feb. 17-18 for talks with the new Bush
administration, while the community's agriculture chief, Ray
MacSharry, was planning a trip later in the month, spokesmen said
Tuesday.
   The new U.S. secretary of state, James A. Baker III, was slated
to stop in Brussels on an upcoming swing through Western Europe.
   The officials will no doubt discuss the troublesome dispute
sparked Jan. 1 when the Europeans imposed a ban on imports of meat
from cattle treated with growth hormones, a common U.S. practice.
   The United States has refused to comply with the prohibition,
which the Europeans say was drawn up for health reasons. In
retaliation for the ban, the Reagan administration set 100 percent
tariffs on European boneless beef, pork hams and shoulders and a
variety of other European products. The sanctions are worth about
$100 million.
   The trading bloc protested the retaliatory measures and filed a
complaint with GATT, saying that the ``unilateral action'' taken by
the United States ``is not compatible with GATT rules and
procedures.''
   It asked the international body ``to examine this matter and ...
make a ruling on the legal issues and recommend appropriate action.''
   GATT members could rule on the dispute at Wednesday's meeting,
but officials said such a quick decision was unlikely. They raised
the possibility that the issue could be referred to a three-member
panel for study. The panels generally take about six months to reach
a finding.
   Foreign ministers representing the EEC nations warned last month
that they would impose counterretaliatory measures on imports of
U.S. walnuts and dried fruit if the two sides failed to move quickly
to end the dispute.
   The ministers delayed implementing the sanctions to give more
time to settle the conflict. They are scheduled to meet Feb. 20 on
the matter.
   The hormone ban was set to go into effect Jan. 1, 1988, but the
EEC agreed to a one-year delay. It refused additional U.S. appeals
for postponement.
   The Europeans contend the growth stimulants pose a health risk, a
contention the United States disputes.
   The prohibition is expected to block the importation of about
$100 million worth of U.S. beef and beef byproducts.
   The disputed goods represent a small chunk of the estimated $166
billion in trade last year between the United States and the
community, whose members are: France, West Germany, Italy,
Luxembourg, Belgium, the Netherlands, Denmark, Greece, Ireland,
Portugal, Spain and the United Kingdom.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890208-0260 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-08-89 0211EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-OPECSummit Bjt   02-08 0753</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-OPEC Summit, Bjt,0777</SECOND>
<HEAD>OPEC May Plan Summit Of Heads Of State, Possibly in 1990</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subroto, full name, cq.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   OPEC oil ministers appear to be leaning
toward holding a summit of their countries' leaders, possibly next
year to mark the 30th anniversary of the founding of the
organization, analysts say.
   Subroto, secretary-general of the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries, said recently that key oil ministers would
discuss the proposal at a meeting scheduled for late next month in
Vienna.
   Venezuela's newly inaugurated president, Carlos Andres Perez, has
reportedly urged in recent trips to the Middle East that a summit be
held.
   In his inaugural speech last week, Perez said he had found
``receptivity to the idea of celebrating, at a convenient date, a
meeting of sovereigns and chiefs of state.''
   He said a ``meeting of OPEC chiefs of state is considered
propitious to give approval to a strategy that will orient the
organization during the 90s.''
   An OPEC summit was last held in March 1975 in Algiers.
   The oil ministers of Ecuador, Iraq, Saudi Arabia and Venezuela
met last week in Venezuela. Afterward, Subroto said, ``Everybody
present at the meeting expressed the need for the holding of an OPEC
summit.''
   Subroto, according to the OPEC News Agency, said the proposal
would be discussed by the eight oil ministers attending next month's
meeting in Vienna. The news agency said the ministers, members of a
monitoring committee, would discuss the time, place and theme of the
proposed gathering.
   Analysts cautioned that scheduling a high-level meeting would
raise hopes that the leaders would act to strengthen the oil market.
Failure to do so, they said, would deliver a sharp blow to the
financial markets.
   ``There's not a great deal they can do,'' said London-based
analyst Paul McDonald. ``I think it (a summit) would be about the
most disastrous thing they could do. I cannot imagine what on earth
they could find to talk about.''
   Oil prices have tended to climb in advance of recent OPEC
meetings and often tumbled afterward when expectations of strong
steps were dashed.
   Fergus MacLeod, an analyst at Barclays de Zoete Wedd in London,
said he doubted a meeting of the heads of state would be scheduled
this year. But he said there was a ``reasonable chance'' of one in
1990 to mark OPEC's startup.
   Bahman Karbassioun, a consultant in Vienna, agreed. ``There may
be a summit, maybe next year,'' he said.
   He said OPEC had planned a 20th anniversary summit in September
1980. But the meeting was canceled when war broke out between bitter
enemies Iran and Iraq.
   By holding a 30th anniversary gathering, MacLeod said, the heads
of state would have ``a reason to meet'' and hold down expectations
in the markets.
   The cartel was formed in September 1960 by Iran, Iraq, Kuwait,
Saudi Arabia and Venezuela. It currently has 13 members.
   The officials would likely review the goals of the organization
and plot their strategy in the coming decade, analysts said.
   A 1990 summit would give the cartel time to assess the fresh push
to restore discipline among its members and the impact of the August
cease-fire between Iran and Iraq.
   At a November meeting in Vienna, the oil ministers fashioned a
new production accord in an effort to curtail their output and lift
prices. They set an overall production ceiling of 18.5 million
barrels a day for the first six months of 1989, sharply under the
levels at the end of last year.
   The International Energy Agency estimated in its Monthly Oil
Market Report that OPEC crude production in January was 19.4 million
barrels a day, off 3.4 million barrels a day from December.
   Saudi Arabia, the world's No. 1 oil exporter, slashed production
last month by more than 2 million barrels a day to an average of 4.5
million barrels a day, according to the newly released report.
   Crude prices have generally been rising since the output
agreement was struck, a pickup tied to optimism that the OPEC
countries intend to stick to the individual output targets set in
the accord. Prices, though, are still under the cartel's benchmark
of $18 a barrel.
   As part of the accord, the oil ministers set up the monitoring
committee to watch prices in the market and members' adherence to
their new quotas. Panel members represent Algeria, Indonesia, Iran,
Iraq, Kuwait, Nigeria, Saudi Arabia and Venezuela.
   Other OPEC members are Gabon, Ecuador, Libya, the United Arab
Emirates and Qatar.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890208-0261 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-08-89 0220EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-S&amp;L-WallStreet Bjt   02-08 0728</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-S&amp;L-Wall Street, Bjt,0749</SECOND>
<HEAD>As Insider Trading Gained Publicity, S&amp;L Crisis Languished</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wall Street's inside traders drew the attention
while a much larger financial crisis _ the disintegration of a good
part of the nation's savings and loan industry _ received little
notice, observers say.
   ``I don't think the S&amp;L crisis has gotten nearly as much
publicity, particularly in going after the crooks, as Ivan Boesky
and those types,'' said Edwin Gray, head of the Federal Home Loan
Bank Board from 1983-87. ``It's almost a crime in its own right.''
   Experts said the securities fraud scandals of the 1980s pale in
comparison with the troubles in the trillion-dollar thrift industry,
which this week prompted a $90 billion plan to staunch $100 billion
in losses at hundreds of savings and loans.
   ``I think the harm has been broader in the S&amp;L problem, not from
the criminality per se but from the compounding of all the problems
and the waste of economic resources,'' Bert Ely, a financial
consultant in Alexandria, Va., said Tuesday. ``I think the Wall
Street stuff is small change.''
   But the combination of shady dealings, the allure of the stock
market and an aggressive federal prosecutor in New York combined to
overshadow _ at least in the public eye _ a scandal that may have
grown unchecked for lack of enforcement in the mid-1980s.
   President Bush's plan to rescue the savings and loan industry
includes $50 million more for the Justice Department to attack
fraud. It would deploy extra investigators on 200 cases and add
about 80 federal fraud prosecutors.
   In addition, federal regulators would be given broader powers,
civil penalties would be increased to fines of up to $1 million per
day, and criminal penalties would grow to 20 years or more in prison.
   But some officials said the plan _ which comes two years after a
stepped-up federal probe in Texas that resulted in 33 indictments _
may be too little, too late. Gray said the bank board was uncovering
fraud as early as 1983.
   While doubling the number of examiners at the board, which
regulates the nation's 3,100 thrift institutions, Gray said he was
stymied by the Office of Management and Budget and the U.S. Justice
Department in pressing criminal prosecutions.
   ``There were and are a lot of crooks down there,'' said Gray, now
president of Chase Federal Bank in Miami. ``The problem is all of
this is so late. We all knew there was a problem in 1983 and '84.''
   In New York, meanwhile, then-U.S. Attorney Rudolph W. Giuliani
actively prosecuted securities fraud cases involving characters like
Boesky, the now-jailed speculator who paid $100 million in fines and
illicit profits to answer securities charges.
   A handful of other cases _ from the arrest of a 24-year-old
inside trader to the recent record $650 million settlement with
investment giant Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. _ also have drawn wide
attention.
   In contrast with the notoriety of insider trading, the bank
board's earlier probes of S&amp;Ls often were kept quiet to avoid
creating public panic. A former bank board attorney said the board
operated under the belief it was defending the industry it was
designed to regulate.
   Hal Levi, who left the agency in 1982 after 10 years, said the
idea of giving bank board examiners greater investigative power was
shot down as early as 1972, when one official feared they would
become ``junior Dick Tracys.''
   ``Clearly I think there was an absence of prosecution of those
kinds of cases in the late '70s and early '80s, even for ones that
were referred'' to the Justice Department, he said. ``It was a
never-ending source of frustration to me.''
   Rosemary Stewart, the bank board's current enforcement director,
said the Justice Department has not had enough prosecutors to handle
the number of referred bank fraud cases.
   ``Just because a bank failed last year it's unreasonable to
expect that the owners who drove it into the ground will be in jail
this year,'' she said. ``Criminal enforcement work always follows
these problems. Certainly it's not too late.''
   Added Gray: ``You've got to put your money where your mouth is if
you want to go after these guys. They have the sharpest attorneys,
the crookedest accountants. They're slimy like snakes and they know
how to do these things.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
