<FILEID>AP-NR-02-08-89 0752EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Regina     02-08 0308</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Regina,0319</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vacuum Cleaner Maker Says It's Seeking Possible Buyer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RAHWAY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Financially troubled Regina Co. Inc. says it
will consider bids from potential buyers.
   Malcolm L. Sherman, chairman and chief executive officer of the
Rahway-based vacuum cleaner company, said Regina would agree to be
sold, ``if people are interested and willing to pay a price that is
fair and will satisfy our stockholders.''
   Sherman said in a telephone interview Tuesday that no specific
price has been set.
   ``The company is under-financed,'' Sherman said. Regina's
recently hired consulting firm, Bear Stearns &amp; Co., ``felt that a
sale might be the best way to make it stronger,'' he said.
   There is no timetable for the sale, and the company will continue
to operate on its own if no suitable buyer is found, the chairman
said.
   ``We cannot ignore that consumer product companies are sought
after today, and that Regina has one of the historically strong
names in the consumer products market. We have asked Bear Stearns to
go forward,'' Sherman said.
   The company released a revised financial statement in early
January that showed the company's net loss for the 15-month period
ending Sept. 30, 1988, as $16.8 million on sales of $190.3 million.
   The company in September withdrew its initial financial
statements showing a $10.9 million profit on sales of $181.1 million
after calling them materially inaccurate. Peat Marwick, Main &amp; Co.
was hired to complete an audit, and at about the same time chairman
Donald D. Sheelen and Vincent P. Golden, chief financial officer,
resigned.
   Analysts say Regina's past problems were linked partly to the
quality of its Housekeeper line of vacuum cleaners, introduced about
three years ago. The company has introduced an updated version of
the Housekeeper vacuum.
   Regina is facing several shareholder lawsuits, filed in federal
court in Newark, over its financial reporting.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
