<FIRST>r f PM-HollyFarms     02-08 0283</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Holly Farms,0293</SECOND>
<HEAD>Holly Farms Board Calls For ConAgra Merger Support</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Holly Farms Corp.'s board of directors is
urging company stockholders to enter a merger agreement with ConAgra
Inc. and reject overtures from Tyson Foods Inc.
   Holly Farms spokesman Ted Bailey Tuesday said the company would
mail statements to shareholders soon seeking their approval of the
ConAgra deal. The company said a stockholders meeting would be
convened as soon as possible to vote on a merger with ConAgra.
   Two-thirds of both Holly Farms' and ConAgra's shareholders would
have to endorse the merger in order for it to take place.
   The board of the Memphis-based chicken producer said ConAgra's
stock-swap offer had less strings attached than the Tyson proposal
to pay $63.50 per share for Holly Farms stock.
   ConAgra's stock trade deal has been valued at about $1.06
billion, and Tyson's $1.09 billion.
   The Holly Farms board said Tuesday that there were reasons to
doubt that a deal with Tyson could be completed.
   Plus, the board said an opinion from investment banker Morgan
Stanley &amp; Co. concluded the terms of the ConAgra agreement were fair
to Holly's share owners.
   ``The company, since its board meeting of Jan. 20, had invited
Tyson and ConAgra to improve the terms of their respective
proposals,'' the Holly Farms statement said.
   ``ConAgra had made no changes. Tyson had added a condition to
theirs, and that, along with the prospect of litigation between
Tyson and ConAgra had led the board to conclude that their concerns
over the Tyson proposal were even more acute than before.''
   ConAgra, an Omaha, Neb., food and poultry processor, and Tyson,
of Springdale, Ark., have been courting Holly Farms for months.
</TEXT>
