<FIRST>r f PM-BritainStocks     02-08 0181</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain Stocks,0188</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shares Sharply Firmer At Midday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices were stronger in moderatly active
trading early today.
   Prices pushed higher from the onset of trading, buoyed by healthy
gains overnight in Tokyo and New York, traders said. They also
claimed that the market's recent shortage of stock persisted,
provoking a clamor for stock at any price.
   ``Overall, the market's moving higher on the sole reason that
there's a squeeze,'' a market maker said.
   Dealers awaited guidance from Wall Street later in the session,
to determine whether further gains were justified. If New York opens
lower, said a trader, ``I think you'll see most of this morning's
gains severely diminished.''
   At about 12:30 p.m. in London, the Financial Times-Stock Exchange
100-share index was up 22.1 points, or 1 percent, at 2,094.9, below
its intraday best level of 2,100.2 but better than the midmorning
low point of 2,088.9.
   Dealers did not attach much significance to the index's inability
to pierce the 2,100-point barrier.
   Turnover jumped to 470.9 million shares compared with 335.4
million shares traded at midday Tuesday.
</TEXT>
