<FILEID>AP-NR-02-08-89 0927EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-GMStockSplit     02-08 0543</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-GM Stock Split,0565</SECOND>
<HEAD>Will Stock Split Attract Small Investors to GM?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp. surprised automobile industry
analysts by declaring a 2-for-1 stock split designed to attract
small investors to the automaker's stock.
   Analysts were split on whether the split would work.
   Charles Brady of Oppenheimer &amp; Co. of New York has been bullish
on GM's stock and thinks that small investors will head toward it
once the split takes effect March 31.
   David Healy of Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. of New York took a
different view.
   ``I wouldn't bet the ranch on it,'' he said.
   And stock analyst Deal Gulis of William C. Roney &amp; Co. of Detroit
said even with the split, which doubles the number of shares but
cuts their value in half, GM's stock prices will remain high.
   ``When it splits it will be $45 or $50 and even that is not a
prime retailing price,'' Gulis said.
   GM common stock closed Tuesday at $93.87{, up $1.37{ from the
open. GM's announcement about the split and a 20 percent dividend
increase to $1.50 a share came after the stock market closed Monday.
   GM sparked a rally among blue-chip stocks that pushed the Dow
Jones average of 30 industrials up 26.07 points Tuesday to its
highest close since the Oct. 19, 1987, stock market crash.
   ``I think it is a big part of the rally today,'' Gulis said
Tuesday. ``It's a GM rally.''
   The dividend announcement was anticipated on Wall Street. The
split wasn't.
   ``I was expecting they would do it, especially since Ford did
it,'' automobile analyst Kathleen Heaney of Nikko Securities Co.
International Inc. said of GM's dividend announcement.
   On Jan. 12, Ford Motor Co. announced a 25-percent increase in its
dividend, moving it to 75 cents a share, but did not split its stock.
   GM Chairman Roger Smith said in a statement released with news of
the dividend and split that the actions would make the company's
common stock more affordable for individual investors by dropping
the per-share price.
   But some analysts questioned whether such a move would lure small
investors back to the stock market, which many have avoided since
the October 1987 crash.
   ``I think they're afraid of the market in general, it doesn't
matter what company it is,'' Heaney said.
   But Brady said he was pleasantly surprised by the dividend, its
size and the split, and thought the split would attract small
investors.
   ``They'll get another 5 (percent) to 10 percent of the people
looking at the shares just because of the split,'' Brady said.
``It's much more in line with a retail (stock) presentation than it
was at $90 a share.''
   Brady, who said the last time GM split its stock was in 1955,
said Monday's announcements were the latest in a series of good-news
statements from the company.
   Also on Monday, GM announced it was reinstating hearing and
vision care for its active and retired salaried employees. The
benefits had been withdrawn a year earlier.
   ``What they really did here in that whole string of events is
just exude optimism,'' Brady said.
   Smith has said 1988 will prove to be GM's best year in history
when earnings are announced next week.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
