<FIRST>r f PM-PepsiTown     02-08 0329</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pepsi Town,0342</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pikeville Pepsi Plant May Close Despite Top Consumption Ranking</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PIKEVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For 16 years Pikeville has led the nation
in per capita consumption of Pepsi Cola, but that might not be
enough to keep the doors open at the local Pepsi bottling plant.
   Charles ``Buddy'' Boston, manager of East Kentucky Beverage Co.'s
bottling plant in Pikeville, said Monday that a decision to close
the plant might be made in several weeks after a series of meetings
with union officials
   ``Right now, it's just in the discussion stages,'' Boston said.
``No firm plans have been made and we will be negotiating with our
union on that topic later this week.''
   Boston said the company would discuss the situation with the
United Steelworkers of America, which represents some of the plant's
100 employees.
   The problem is with the plant and not with the local consumption
habits that have boosted Pikeville to the top of the nation's Pepsi
consumption standings, Boston said.
   Although the machines inside the plant north of Pikeville are
``very modern,'' they are designed to package Pepsi in returnable
bottles, Boston said.
   Times and tastes change and it's now cheaper and more convenient
for customers to use non-returnable containers such as plastic
bottles and alumnum cans, company officials said.
   Pepsi plants nearby in West Virginia and Virginia and elsewhere
in Kentucky already are equipped to produce the drink in
non-returnable containers, Boston said. But converting the Pikeville
plant to non-returnable production was still being discussed, he
said.
   Boston said he was confident of one thing regardless of the
plant's future: Pikeville will keep on drinking Pepsi whether it
comes from the local plant or from across state lines.
   ``We don't expect that to change, no matter what we do,'' he said.
   Two other eastern Kentucky cities, Hazard and Corbin, rank No. 2
and No. 3 respectively in per capita Pepsi consumption. Pepsi does
not release figures on exact volume consumed per person.
</TEXT>
