<FIRST>r f PM-PartsProbe     02-08 0277</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Parts Probe,0288</SECOND>
<HEAD>Airplane Makers Told to Check for Inadequately Tested Fasteners</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Boeing Co. and McDonnell Douglas have been
asked to determine whether inadquately tested nuts, bolts and rivets
made by Voi-Shan Aerospace Products were used in making aircraft.
   The request stems from an investigation into reports that test
documents on the fasteners were falsified at a laboratory of the
Fairchild Industries subsidiary in Chatsworth, Calif., near Los
Angeles, Mitch Barker of the Federal Aviation Administration said
Tuesday.
   A day earlier, in discussing a weekend search of the plant, U.S.
Attorney Gene S. Anderson and others said no crashes had been linked
to the disputed parts, which investigators said were listed as
approved by a phantom ``Inspector 11.''
   Discovery of untested parts on aircraft could result in fines for
the manufacturer, Barker said.
   ``It's certainly a safety concern,'' he said. ``It's a concern to
the U.S. attorney's office, and it's a concern to us.''
   He said FAA staff in district offices had been told to work with
manufacturers to determine whether the fasteners were shipped and
whether they were used by the European consortium Airbus Industrie.
   Airlines are not being required to check their planes, Barker
said.
   ``The manufacturers will be checking and reporting back to us,''
he explained. ``They are held accountable for the parts that go into
their aircraft.''
   Fairchild's annual report said the fasteners are used on almost
every military and commercial aircraft.
   Jack Gamble of Boeing said records of Voi-Shan shipments and
parts use and distribution would be checked by company and FAA
officials, after which ``the FAA will make a determiniation about
what needs to be done.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
