<FILEID>AP-NR-02-08-89 1046EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Italy-AT&amp;T     02-08 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Italy-AT&amp;T,0300</SECOND>
<HEAD>AT&amp;T Clears Major Hurdle In Partnership Bid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The proposed partnership of American Telephone &amp;
Telegraph Co. with Italy's state-owned telecommunications
manufacturer has cleared a major hurdle.
   Societa Finanziaria Telefonica Stet, the state-controlled holding
company for the telecommunications industry, announced Tuesday that
it has endorsed the U.S. giant as a partner for Italtel.
   The announcement, which was widely expected, ended 14 months of
preliminary talks between Italtel and four foreign candidates for
the partnership. Siemens AG of West Germany, Alcatel NV of France
and Sweden's Telefon AB L.M. Ericsson were the candidates rejected
by Italtel.
   By entering into a partnership with Italtel, AT&amp;T will gain
access to the Italian telecommunications market. SIP, the telephone
company controlled by Stet, has planned $27 billion in investments
over the next five years and Italtel is likely to mong Sip's major
suppliers for phone gear.
   A spokeswoman for Stet said the executive committee examined and
``unanimously approved Italtel's proposal to begin negotiations for
a possible global agreement with AT&amp;T.''
   The decision to enter formal talks still requires approval by the
government and Istituto per la Ricostruzione Industriale (IRI), the
giant industrial state holding that owns Stet.
   IRI's management board is expected to give its endorsement on
Thursday, after which the Minister of State Industry Carlo
Fracanzani will review the matter. Although Fracanzani has made it
no secret in the past that he preferred a European ally for Italtel,
he isn't expected to block the choice of AT&amp;T.
   The final form of the partnership hasn't yet been determined, but
it is expected to involve a swap of stock between the two companies.
Sources indicated that one of the advantages of AT&amp;T's proposal was
that it guaranteed the independence of Italtel.
</TEXT>
