<FIRST>r f PM-Pepperell     02-08 0245</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pepperell,0255</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pepperell Sets Feb. 15 Deadline For Bids</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST POINT, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West Point-Pepperell Inc. said today it
has set a deadline of noon Feb. 15 for bids for the giant textile
company, which was put up for sale by its directors last week.
   The company also announced that a special shareholders meeting to
consider a hostile takeover bid by Chicago-based Farley Inc. has
been postponed from Feb. 25 to March 2, with Farley's agreement.
   Farley spokesman Jack Albertine confirmed that his company agreed
to the delay, but he declined comment on Pepperell's bid deadline.
   Farley's latest offer for Pepperell _ $52 per share, or more than
$1.5 billion _ is set to expire at midnight Feb. 15.
   West Point-based Pepperell, the nation's largest publicly held
textile company, has been fighting Farley's takeover attempt since
it was announced in October. Farley originally offered $48 for each
of Pepperell's outstanding shares, but sweetened the offer to $52
last week.
   Pepperell's directors announced Friday that they would sell the
company, ``assuming that an acceptable proposal is received.'' The
board said it had considered Farley's new offer and decided that
``values in excess of $52 per share could be realized in a sale of
the company.''
   In early trading today on the New York Stock Exchange, Pepperell
was up 37{ cents a share at $55.50.
   Pepperell spokeswoman Toni Cauble declined today to say whether
any bids other than Farley's have been received since Friday's
announcement.
</TEXT>
