<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 11am,0270</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices edged upward today, getting a little
more mileage out of Tuesday's advance that carried the market to new
post-crash highs.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, up 26.07 on Tuesday,
rose 1.97 to 2,349.11 by 11 a.m. on Wall Street.
   Gainers slightly outnumbered losers in nationwide trading of New
York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 609 up, 573 down and 565
unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 69.76 million shares at
midmorning.
   The market's rally that began in late November showed signs of
flattening out in the first few sessions of this month.
   It revived on Tuesday, however, in response to General Motors's
announcement of a dividend increase and plans for a 2-for-1 stock
split.
   Analysts said demand for stock was particularly strong at
investing institutions where money managers had built up large cash
reserves in the aftermath of the October 1987 crash.
   Rising stock prices have put pressure on many of these money
managers to increase their stock holdings or run the risk of missing
out on what could amount to a significant market advance.
   General Motors shares were unchanged at 93~ after jumping 4]
points Tuesday.
   Elsewhere among the blue chips, Ford Motor rose ] to 56\;
American Telephone &amp; Telegraph was steady at 32[, and General
Electric slipped ] to 48.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks lost
.03 to 167.99. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up .50 at 326.88.
