<FILEID>AP-NR-02-08-89 1124EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Prime     02-08 0259</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Prime,0269</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Continues Order Enjoining Tender Offer For Prime</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has continued an order blocking a
California company's $970 million bid for Prime Computer Inc. shares
until more information about co-bidder Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.'s
role is disclosed, a spokesmen for Prime said.
   Prime, which is based in Natick, said U.S. District Judge A.
David Mazzone on Tuesday continued his order until Drexel Burnham,
an investment banking firm, makes disclosures required of bidders
under federal securities laws.
   Mazzone said in December that the California bidder, MAI Basic
Four Inc., needed to make disclosures about the relationship between
Drexel and New York investor Bennett S. LeBow, who controls MAI
Basic.
   ``Like Judge Mazzone, we find Drexel Burnham Lambert's continuing
omission of the required material information concerning tender
offer bidders `inexcusable and inexplicable,''' Prime said in a
statement.
   Fred Anderson of the Tustin, Calif.-based MAI Basic said the
company has met all of the judge's requirements for lifting his
order ``except for clarification of Drexel Burnham's status as a
co-bidder.''
   ``We're going to wait until we receive the transcript on today's
hearing, and we will evaluate the transcript and then make a
determination of whether we will make the additional disclosures or
consider an appeal,'' Anderson said.
   A decision on MAI Basic's next course of action likely will be
made later this week, he said.
   MAI Basic has said that Drexel has been the primary financier for
LeBow and certain of his companies since 1986 and owns 7 percent of
MAI Basic's common stock.
</TEXT>
