<FILEID>AP-NR-02-08-89 1154EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   02-08 0314</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0326</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wheat Futures Rise On Talk Of Soviet Purchase</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wheat futures prices were slightly higher in early
trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade amid rumors that the
Soviet Union was seeking to buy 600,000 metric tons of U.S. wheat at
subsidized prices.
   Other grain and soybean futures prices were mixed.
   A large wheat purchase by the Soviets would be the first
significant grain export business in more than two weeks.
   But analysts said the futures market had already largely
discounted the potential Soviet purchase, which would be covered by
the long-term grain agreement the Soviet Union signed with the
United States late last year.
   ``The minute they get the credit, it's automatically factored
into the prices, so this is not really a new factor in the market,''
said Cathy Leow, a grain-market analyst with Thomson McKinnon
Securities Inc. in New York.
   In early trading, wheat was unchanged to 2} cents higher with the
contract for delivery in March at $4.30 a bushel; corn was \ cent
