<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Kroger     02-08 0208</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Kroger,0219</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kroger Reports $119 Million Loss for 4th Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kroger Co. reported Wednesday it lost $119
million in the fourth quarter, primarily because of the supermarket
company's massive restructuring.
   Kroger said the loss contrasted to a profit of $47.4 million, or
58 cents per share, reported for the fourth quarter of 1987.
   The company's fourth-quarter sales rose to $4.28 billion from
$4.04 billion a year earlier.
   The grocery store chain undertook a $4.6 billion restructuring
last September to fend off takeover bids by Dart Group Corp. of
Landover, Md., and Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &amp; Co. of New York.
   Under the restructuring, the company agreed to pay shareholders a
special dividend of $40 in cash for each share of common stock plus
$17 per share in securities.
   To finance the restructuring, Kroger sold some of its stores and
other assets. The company also fired about 300 of its 800 employees
at its headquarters here.
   Kroger's full-year earnings fell 81 percent to $34.5 million, or
24 cents a share, from $246.6 million, or $2.99 a share, in 1987.
   The 1987 figure included a $63.3 million one-time gain for an
accounting change.
   For all of 1988, sales totaled $17.46 billion, up from $16.37
billion in 1987.
