<FILEID>AP-NR-02-08-89 1333EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Multinationals     02-08 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Multinationals,0304</SECOND>
<HEAD>California Replaces New York As Home Of Most U.S. Multinationals</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: For release 6:30 p.m. EST.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   California has displaced New York as the state
with the most multinational manufacturing companies, the Conference
Board said in a report released Wednesday.
   California now has 150 publicly owned manufacturing firms with
offices abroad, compared with 130 headquartered in New York state,
according the report by the worldwide organization of corporate
executives.
   The report is based on 1988 corporate data of the foreign
operations of 1,700 publicly held manufacturers. It said there are
990 U.S.-owned manufacturing multinationals with foreign assets of
$126 billion, up from 884 in 1987.
   In 1987, New York was home to 123 foreign-affiliated
manufacturers and California had 108.
   James Greene, an international trade specialist who compiled the
data, said the number of U.S. multinational manufacturers has fallen
from about 2,000 in the late-1970s.
   ``Since then, many have been taken over by foreign firms, others
have been merged into larger multinationals and many have been
privatized through leveraged buyouts,'' he said. ``These trends are
likely to continue through the next few years, concentrating
U.S.-owned foreign assets in fewer and fewer corporate hands.''
   New York still has more multinational firms with annual sales of
$1 billion or more _ 44 compared with California's 24 _ but
California has 66 multinationals with sales of $100 million or less,
compared with 34 in New York.
   The report said California's electronics and computer companies
have led to the increase in manufacturing multinationals, many of
which are establishing offshore production units, especially in the
Far East.
   After California and New York, Illinois had 85 multinational
manufacturers, Ohio 70, Massachusetts 61, Pennsylvania 59, New
Jersey 57, Connecticut 51, Michigan 42 and Texas 38.
</TEXT>
