<FIRST>r f AM-Trump-Rumbolz     02-08 0305</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Trump-Rumbolz,0318</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trump Picks Former Gaming Chief for Nevada Operations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT MACY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Billionaire developer Donald Trump selected
former Gaming Control Board chairman Mike Rumbolz to head his Nevada
operations, a sign Trump is intent on becoming a major player in the
state's gaming industry.
   Rumbolz announced the move Wednesday, saying he will head Trump's
Nevada casino operations.
   The former Control Board chief said he had been negotiating with
Trump since January. Rumbolz did not reapply for his job with the
Control Board when his term expired in December.
   Trump has said for more than a year that he is interested in
becoming involved in Nevada gaming and has disclosed he has a small
stake in Caesars World Inc., a casino operator.
   Rumbolz said he's not certain whether Trump will buy or build in
Nevada.
   ``We're looking at several possible developments as well as some
acquisitions,'' Rumbolz said. ``It's impossible to say how soon we
will make a move. There are so many variables that would impact the
timing.''
   Rumbolz said Trump is looking at possible projects both in Las
Vegas and Laughlin, Nev. Rumbolz said he did not anticipate any
regulatory problems in getting Trump licensed in Nevada.
   In an interview in November, Trump said there was ``tremendous
support'' for his entry into Nevada gaming.
   ``I've been coming here for a long time, and I've always been
very, very well received,'' Trump said. ``This area likes Donald
Trump.''
   Caesars World announced earlier that the real estate magnate had
filed notice with federal agencies to buy more than 15 percent
interest in ther company, and possibly in excess of 50 percent.
   Trump has said he is ``more likely to build'' a new hotel-casino
than buy an existing property.``Then I can do it absolutely first
class,'' he said.
</TEXT>
