<FILEID>AP-NR-02-08-89 1929EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-EEC-US     02-08 0196</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-EEC-US,0206</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Ambassador Leaving European Body</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alfred H. Kingon, the U.S. ambassador to
the European Economic Community, said Wednesday he has resigned to
return to the private sector.
   ``It's time for me to go home,'' said Kingon, who has been the
U.S. envoy to the 12-nation trading bloc for nearly two years.
   He said President Bush has chosen a successor whom he declined to
identify.
   Kingon said he has no firm job plans yet. ``I do want to go home
to New York, where we have family and friends,'' he said.
   He lauded a plan to curtail trade barriers among the group's 12
members by 1992 to create a European-wide market.
   ``I believe in Europe. I believe in 1992,'' he said. ``I believe,
in spite of all the problems that exist, that there's a very
reasonable chance the Europeans will achieve what they want to do.''
   Kingon, 57, became ambassador to the body, also known as the
Common Market, in April 1987.
   He earlier served as an assistant to former President Reagan.
Before entering government, he was an editor of the publications
Financial World, Saturday Review and Money and Credit.
</TEXT>
