<FILEID>AP-NR-02-08-89 1655EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-FirstClass Bjt   02-08 0763</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-First Class, Bjt,0788</SECOND>
<HEAD>Airlines Paying Increased Attention to Service</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY15, LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fancier foods, individual video machines and
money-back guarantees are among the amenities that big airlines are
offering to first-class fliers as competition for travelers
increasingly highlights service instead of price.
   The latest campaign was unveiled Wednesday by British Airways
PLC, which said it is investing $40 million to upgrade its
first-class service on long-haul flights beginning March 1.
   The changes, detailed at a news conference in New York, include
individual passenger video terminals at each seat, redesigned cabin
interiors, a new wine cellar and menus that allow passengers to eat
when they wish.
   ``This investment is a bold and calculated bid for commercial
supremacy in an intensely competitive market,'' said Sir Colin
Marshall, the airline's chief executive.
   The program reflects the increasing importance to many airlines
of their first-class business _ which accounts for nearly $400
million of British Airways' annual revenue _ in the wake of years of
fare wars that have made it tougher to compete for passengers on the
basis of price.
   This is especially true in the United States, where airline
industry deregulation has meant cheaper fares by all carriers,
making it harder to compete by slashing fares.
   First class accounted for 10.3 percent of the revenue generated
by major U.S. airlines in 1988, compared with 9 percent in 1983,
according to the Air Transport Association.
   First class still isn't cheap: British Airways' round-trip,
first-class fare between New York and London is $4,880, compared
with about $900 for an economy-class ticket.
   But even Continental Airlines, which long has had a reputation as
a fare-cutting leader, has re-emphasized service. The carrier last
August tested a novel money-back service guarantee for its
first-class passengers, under which fliers could get a refund of up
to $200 if they were dissatisfied with any aspect of their domestic
flights, from making reservations to claiming their baggage.
   In Western Europe, the gradual liberalization of the industry has
spawned small independent airlines and some cheaper fares. It also
has increased the role of business class, the service that falls
between coach and first class.
   Business class generally offers hurried business travelers
separate check-in facilities, airport lounges with work areas and
wider airplane seats, while stopping short of such first-class
amenities as gourmet food.
   Business class sales have grown so strongly at Scandinavian
Airline System that the company is scrapping its first class service
entirely in favor of business and economy fares.
   Business class doesn't widely exist on domestic U.S. flights. But
fast-growing Piedmont Aviation has introduced a similar service
targeted mainly at business travelers.
   In June 1987 Piedmont introduced first-class service with all the
trimmings at relatively cheaper fares, charging first-class
passengers a premium over the economy fare of up to $60 one way,
depending on distance. That's well below normal first-class fares,
which often run about double domestic economy fares.
   Between Dallas and Miami, for example, Piedmont's competitors
charge $430 to $860 round trip for a regular economy ticket, and
$1,292 for first-class service. Piedmont's economy fares are
similar, but it charges around $300 less for a first-class round
trip ticket.
   USAir Group Inc., which is set to formally acquire Piedmont in
early August, plans to adopt the same service.
   ``There is a certain segment of the market that demands a
first-class product,'' said Mike Clark, a Piedmont spokesman at the
airline's Winston-Salem, N.C., headquarters.
   Another U.S. airline offers nothing but first class. The glitzy
MGM Grand Air, owned by California financier Kirk Kerkorian, only
flies between New York and Los Angeles, for $1,878 round trip.
   What sort of people fly first class?
   According to British Airways, they fall into two categories: the
``Patrician'' and the ``Achiever.'' The Patrician ``has established
wealth, is relaxed but has exacting standards, does not want to be
overly pampered and chooses first class as a matter of course.''
   The Achiever is ``usually a self-made individual who is more
status conscious, is a conspicuous consumer, seeks recognition and
uses first class as a signal of accomplishment.''
   British Airways says its new first-class service is aimed mainly
at business people, predominantly male, usually in their late 40s
and holding to corporate positions such as chairman or chief
executive.
   In the United States, much of the growth in first-class traffic
appears to have come from ``Achiever'' business travelers who don't
have a business class to fly in domestically.
   Furthermore, many first-class passengers are members of
frequent-flier programs who got upgrades to first-class tickets as
awards for accumulating mileage.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
