<FILEID>AP-NR-02-08-89 1740EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     02-08 0337</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Decline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crude futures prices slumped in light trading
Wednesday, influenced partly by higher American Petroleum Institute
statistics.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the March contract for West
Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude oil, fell 21
cents to close the day at $17.49 a barrel. The contract had risen 32
cents in Tuesday's session. Contracts for delivery later in the year
also declined.
   Among refined products traded on the exchange, the March contract
for unleaded gasoline lost 0.32 cent to settle at 48.94 cents, while
domestic heating oil declined 0.80 cent to 49.07 cents a gallon.
Other contract months also fell.
   Observers attributed the slide in prices to a combination of
factors, including a technical correction following several weeks of
rising prices and the weekly API report.
   The API's weekly statistics on domestic energy supplies showed
crude oil stocks rose by 7 million barrels a day, while unleaded
gasoline increased 3.7 million barrels. Heating oil, meanwhile,
declined 3.4 million barrels.
   Traders said some of the rise in crude oil stocks may be the
``lost OPEC oil'' that analysts have been looking for.
   Since the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries' cut
production Jan. 1, market analysts have looked for a weakening in
oil prices as the excess oil produced by the cartel late last year
entered the market.
   Instead, prices have risen steadily, surprising analysts and
leaving many to wonder what happened to the excess oil.
   OPEC was estimated to have produced more than 22 million barrels
per day of oil at the end of 1988. On Jan. 1, it was to lower
production to 18.5 million barrels, although estimates are that it
is producing more than 19 million.
   Nevertheless, analysts have guessed that the excess was either on
tankers en route to market, in on-shore storage tanks in the Middle
East or still in the ground.
   Energy traders said Tuesday's API report suggests that the lost
oil might finally be arriving on the market.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890208-0297 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-08-89 2013EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-CountingSheep     02-08 0235</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Counting Sheep,0244</SECOND>
<HEAD>A Few More U.S. Sheep to Count</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department reported Wednesday
that the nation's flock of sheep and lambs increased slightly in
1988 for the third consecutive year.
   The increase was only a small fraction of 1 percent, however,
boosting the U.S. flock to an estimated 10,802,000 sheep and lambs
on Jan. 1 from 10,784,000 on Jan. 1, 1988.
   Despite the recent gains, the Jan. 1 count was one of the
smallest in U.S. history, according to department records going back
for more than a century.
   In 1970, for example, there were 20.4 million sheep and lambs in
the nation's flocks. And in 1867, when the department began counting
sheep, there were about 46.3 million head. The industry peaked in
1942 at 56.2 million.
   ``Primarily the decline stems from less demand for wool as more
synthetics and cheaper substitute materials were introduced and the
declining demand for lamb in consumer diets,'' the report said.
   Also, it said, there has been ``increased difficulty in obtaining
and keeping reliable herders to manage and care for range flocks,
and increased competing uses for public-owned rangeland.''
   Predators, including coyotes, also are blamed for the decline in
the U.S. sheep industry.
   The value of sheep and lambs as of Jan. 1 was estimated at $890
million, down 8 percent, with the average at $82.40 per head,
compared with $90 a year earlier.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890208-0298 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-08-89 1807EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     02-08 0673</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0697</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cattle Tally Shocks Futures Markets; Sharp Losses Predicted</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   An Agriculture Department report pegging the nation's cattle herd
at 99.5 million head drew expressions of shock and amazement
Wednesday from market experts who had expected a much lower number.
   Analysts predicted cattle futures prices would drop sharply
Thursday in reaction to the cattle inventory report. Cattle futures
settled narrowly mixed Wednesday in cautious pre-report trading.
   On other markets Wednesday, soybean futures were down sharply;
precious metals advanced; and energy futures retreated.
   Livestock-market analysts had projected about a 1.4 percent net
decline in the nation's cattle herd during 1988, to 97.6 million
head, due in part to widespread herd liquidation as a result of the
summer drought.
   But the USDA said the U.S. cattle herd as of Jan. 1 was about the
same size as it was a year earlier.
   ``I was shocked,'' said Charles Levitt, senior livestock market
analyst with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in Chicago.
   Analysts base their projections on previous USDA cattle inventory
reports, which are released semi-annually, and on the daily
slaughter numbers provided by packing houses.
   One explanation for the surprising number could be found in the
USDA's contention that the number of calves born in 1988 was 2
percent higher than the number born in 1987.
   But even with the large calf crop, ``the numbers are larger than
we could possibly have pieced together using any balance sheet
approach,'' Levitt said. ``The only thing I can say at this point is
that it appears we have a phantom herd out there.''
   Thomas Morgan, president of Sterling Research Corp. in Arlington
Heights, Ill., said cattle futures traders had been ``faked out'' by
the two previous cattle inventory reports, which had set a pattern
of declining cattle numbers that many had expected would continue.
   Although futures prices were expected to register an immediate
reaction to the report, Morgan said the impact on beef prices would
not be felt until late 1989 or early 1990, when the the calves born
in the second half of 1988 are ready for slaughter.
   In futures trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, live
cattle settled .30 cent lower to .40 cent higher with the contract
for delivery in February at 75.37 cents a pound; feeder cattle were
.08 cent lower to .25 cent higher with March at 84.42 cents a pound;
live hogs were .25 cent lower to .65 cent higher with February at
42.60 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .65 cent lower to .02
cent higher with February at 38.30 cents a pound.
   Soybean futures prices fell sharply on the Chicago Board of Trade
on rumors the Soviet Union planned to shift some of its purchases of
U.S. soybeans and soybean meal to South American producers.
   Corn futures fell in sympathy with soybeans but wheat futures
advanced slightly on rumors that the Soviets were seeking to
purchase 600,000 metric tons of U.S. wheat at subsidized prices
under the long-term grain agreement signed late last year.
   Wheat settled { cent to 1 cent higher with March at $4.28\ a
bushel; corn was 1\ cents to 3 cents lower with March at $2.64} a
bushel; oats were 3} cents to 5 cents lower with March at $2.09{ a
bushel; soybeans were 9\ cents to 11{ cents lower with March at
$7.46 a bushel.
   Gold and silver futures strengthened on New York's Commodity
Exchange in reaction to the dollar's decline against other major
currencies.
   Gold settled $3.60 to $3.90 higher with April at $399.10 a troy
ounce; silver was 5.5 cents to 5.9 cents higher with March at $5.945
a troy ounce.
   Energy futures prices drifted lower in dull trading on the New
York Mercantile Exchange.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 14 cents to 22 cents
lower with March at $17.49 a barrel; heating oil was .44 cent to .80
cent lower with March at 49.07 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was
.25 cent to .82 cent lower with March at 48.94 cents a gallon.
</TEXT>
