<FILEID>AP-NR-02-08-89 1809EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-ColdCrops Bjt   02-08 0651</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cold Crops, Bjt,0671</SECOND>
<HEAD>Major Damage to California Floral, Citrus Crops Predicted From Cold
Wave</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROB WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRESNO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The arctic cold wave that blew through
California this week sent shivers through the state's
multimillion-dollar floral and citrus industries, ruining part of
the lemon crop and possibly boosting the price of a Valentine
bouquet.
   As the weather moderated in the state's major growing regions
Wednesday, growers assessed the cold-caused damage by slicing open
lemons and eyeing rows of drooping carnations.
   ``There's going to be a shortage right now. They're (carnations)
just not blooming,'' said Mark Yamaguchi, a grower-shipper in
Monterey County.
   Many growers and packers said lemon groves in the San Joaquin
Valley in central Califronia were hit hard by the cold wave, with
some early estimates that 35 percent of the existing crop may have
been damaged.
   California is the nation's top producer of lemons, a crop valued
at $152 million in 1987. It will take about a week to 10 days for an
accurate assessment of the frost's damage, industry experts said.
   But prices already have risen for some crops. The industry's
wholesale price for a 40-pound box of medium sized oranges jumped $1
to $7.50, and a box of larger oranges also jumped $1 to $10.50, said
George Lombardi, marketing director for Sequoia Farms in Exeter.
   Flower growers in San Mateo and Santa Cruz counties already have
seen the effect on their crops.
   ``The damage is done. The freeze has damaged the crops out there
and I don't expect them to recover at all,'' said George Ginilo,
agriculture commissioner of central California's San Mateo County.
The county's 1987 floral crop was valued at $165 million and serves
wholesalers on the West Coast and in New England.
   But while some major suppliers of California flowers predicted a
shortage, it was unclear whether it would affect the market by
Valentine's Day. Yamaguchi said 80 percent of the national carnation
market comes from foreign growers.
   The California Farm Bureau Federation said imports and greenhouse
flowers should provide a ``tight but adequate'' supply of flowers
for Valentine's Day, but said prices may be ``slightly higher in
some cases.''
   Daisies, irises, pom poms, baby's breath and other flowers grown
in open fields may be in short supply even with the imports, said
the federation's floriculture specialist, Maria Sampanis.
   Growers were running greenhouse boilers were run around the clock
for warmth and to encourage roses to bloom on time for Feb. 14. But
Half Moon Bay nursery owner Natalie Pastorino worried the flowers
might bloom late this year.
   ``We're crossing our fingers that the cold weather ends,'' said
Ms. Pastorino. ``If we get the crop after Valentine's (Day), we'll
lose money because the demand is not there.''
   Other crops _ lettuce, carrots, and broccoli _ sustained damage
in Monterrey County, with up to 20 to 25 percent of plantings lost
on some farms, said Richard Nutter, the county agricultural
commissioner.
   Among citrus, the icicles that hung from orange and lemons
earlier this week in the San Joaquin Valley have melted and growers
are waiting for signs of damage to appear.
   Citrus fares poorly when the temperature drops to 26 or lower for
extended periods. In central California's Terra Bella, the prime
region for Tulare County's $357 million citrus crop, temperatures
stayed at 23 degrees or lower for 8{ hours Monday night and Tuesday
morning.
   Growers were more optimistic about the state's $242 million navel
orange crop, which is fairly mature and contains a high sugar
content that helps ward off frost.
   In Southern California, cloud cover and winds prevented a heavy
freeze and spared citrus, flower and avocado crop from serious
damage, officials said. But winds may have scarred or knocked some
fruit from the trees.
   Also, San Bernardino County's $10 million orange crop suffered 25
degree temperatures for 6{ hours, said John Gardner, assistant
agricultural commissioner.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
