<FILEID>AP-NR-02-08-89 1829EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-PanAmShuttle     02-08 0291</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pan Am Shuttle,0299</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pan Am Shuttle Launches New Ad Campaign</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pan Am Corp. announced a new advertising campaign
Wednesday for its Northeast shuttle service.
   Pan Am officials said their service now commands nearly 50
percent of the air shuttle market between New York, Boston and
Washington, shared with the rival hourly shuttle operated by Eastern
Airlines. Pan Am's share of the market is up from around 38 percent
a year ago, company officials said.
   New York developer Donald Trump, having recently cleared a number
of regulatory hurdles, is scheduled to complete his acquisition of
the Eastern shuttle for $365 million in cash within the next month
or so.
   Pan Am officials denied that the new ad blitz, with the theme
``The Pan Am Shuttle: The Corporate Jet,'' was planned in
anticipation of the flamboyant Trump's debut as a competitor.
   The ad campaign ``is related to positioning the Pan Am shuttle as
a leader in the market,'' said Peter McHugh, Pan Am's senior vice
president of marketing. ``The new entrant (Trump) ought to be
thinking about what they're going to do to react to us.''
   McHugh conceded that curiosity about Trump will prompt some
passengers to take his shuttle service on a trial basis, because of
the publicity surrounding the developer. However, he said, Trump
will likely have difficulty meeting the public's expectations for
his shuttle.
   ``He (Trump) may clean it up, but it's still a duck,'' McHugh
said.
   Pan Am plans to spend around $10 million on the new ad campaign,
which will be run by Grey Advertising Inc. Targeted at the shuttle's
predominantly business traveler market, the print and broadcast
campaign will emphasize services such as automatic ticketing at
airport terminals and on-board telephones.
</TEXT>
