<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold 1stLd-Writethru   02-08 0418</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold, 1st Ld-Writethru,0433</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Lower; Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 11th graf to CORRECT that silver rose on the Comex, sted
fell.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar edged narrowly lower against several
major currencies Wednesday as traders appeared reluctant to
speculate on currency shifts in advance of President Bush's budget
address on Thursday.
   A commitment by Bush to take strong action against the budget
deficit could support the dollar, while weak remarks would be likely
to send the dollar lower.
   ``The market took the Bush speech as a signal to just lay low for
the day,'' said Don Quattrucci, a trader at Connecticut National
Bank in Hartford, Conn.
   Gold prices rose in New York after having fallen earlier in the
trading day in Europe. Republic National Bank of New York said gold
bullion was bid at $394.25 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EST, up from
$390.10 late Tuesday.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar closed at 129.50 Japanese yen, unchanged from Tuesday's
close. Later, in London, it edged up to 129.55 yen. In New York, the
dollar fell to 129.38 yen from 129.48.
   In London, the British pound rose to $1.7423 from $1.7377 late
Tuesday. In New York, the pound rose to $1.7440 from $1.7370.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Tuesday's
rates, included: 1.8698 West German marks, down from 1.8716; 1.5895
Swiss francs, up from 1.5893; 1.1844 Canadian dollars, up from
1.1828; 6.3640 French francs, down from 6.3680; and 1,363.6 Italian
lire, down from 1,364.8.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Tuesday,
included: 1.8720 West German marks, unchanged; 1.59165 Swiss francs,
up from 1.5913; 6.3725 French francs, up from 6.3700; 2.1140 Dutch
guilders, unchanged; 1,364.25 Italian lire, down from 1,365.50; and
1.18475 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1813.
   Gold in London was selling at a late bid of $390.25 a troy ounce,
down from $392.55 late Tuesday. In Zurich, the late bid was $390.85,
down from $392 Tuesday.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery rose to $396.20 a troy ounce from $392 on Tuesday.
   Silver bullion fell in London to a bid price of $5.88 a troy
ounce, down from $5.91 bid late Tuesday. On New York's Comex, silver
bullion for current delivery rose to $5.917 an ounce from $5.858.
   Financial markets in Hong Kong were closed for the third day for
the Chinese lunar new year celebrations.
</TEXT>
