<FIRST>u f AM-Earns-Media     02-08 0740</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Media,0773</SECOND>
<HEAD>4th-Qtr Profit Falls at CBS, Washington Post; Up at NY Times, Times-Mirror</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   CBS Inc. said Wednesday its fourth-quarter profit dropped 84
percent from strong results a year ago that included a huge gain on
the sale of its magazine division, and that income from its
broadcasting operations fell 37 percent.
   Two other media concerns posted profit gains for the quarter as
earnings rose 19 percent at the New York Times Co. and 77 percent at
Times-Mirror Co.
   But the Washington Post Co. reported its fourth-quarter profit
dropped 42.7 percent from a year ago.
   CBS said its net income fell to $40.1 million, or $1.56 a share,
in the three months ended Dec. 31 from $251.6 million, or $9.73 a
share, in the same period in 1987.
   Fourth-quarter revenue slipped 1 percent to $772 million from
$773 million.
   The 1987 results included a $179.8 million gain on the sale of
CBS Magazines.
   The company said income from continuing operations rose 78
percent to $40.1 million in the quarter, boosted by higher interest
income and lower corporate expenses.
   But the CBS Broadcast operations' profit fell to $12.4 million
from $19.8 million a year earlier.
   It said the CBS television network results were depressed by the
22-week Writer's Guild strike which delayed the start of the current
television season and led to lower audience ratings and ad revenue.
CBS trails NBC and ABC in prime-time audience ratings.
   CBS said its television stations and radio operations each
reported higher sales and income for the period.
   For the year, CBS said it earned a record $1.15 billion, or
$44.75 a share, compared with $452.5 million, or $17.74 a share, a
year earlier.
   Full-year revenue rose 1 percent to $2.78 billion from $2.76
billion.
   The full-year results reflected a gain of $866 million on the
sale of the CBS Records division in January and interest income on
the investment of money generated by asset sales. The company had
net interest income of $185 million in 1988 compared with a net
interest expense of $6.9 million in 1987.
   New York Times Co. said its net income rose to $50.4 million, or
64 cents a share, in the fourth quarter from $42.5 million, or 52
cents a share, a year earlier.
   Fourth-quarter revenue rose 3 percent to $450 million from from
$435.5 million a year earlier.
   For the year, it said net income rose 5 percent to a record
$167.7 million, or $2.08 a share, from $160.3 million, or $1.96 a
share, a year ago.
   Full-year revenue rose 4 percent to $1.7 billion from $1.6
billion in 1987.
   Arthur Ochs Sulzberger, chairman and chief executive, said ``the
softening in some markets is likely to result in a down first
quarter in 1989.''
   In addition to publishing the New York Times, the company has
interests in regional newspapers, magazines, broadcasting and forest
products.
   Times-Mirror, based in Los Angeles, said it earned $96.8 million,
or 76 cents a share, up from $54.7 million, or 42 cents a share, a
year earlier.
   Fourth-quarter revenue rose 6.9 percent to $925 million from $865
million.
   The 1988 results include a $2 million gain on sale of assets,
while the 1987 results included a pretax loss of $43.7 million on
asset sales.
   For the year, the company said it earned $332 million, or $2.58 a
share, up from $266 million, or $2.06 a share, a year earlier.
   Full-year revenue rose to $3.33 billion from $3.14 billion a year
ago.
   The 1988 results included a $58.9 million gain on the sale of
assets, while the 1987 results reflected a $29.2 million loss on the
sale of assets.
   The company publishes newspapers including the Los Angeles Times,
and has interests in television stations, cable television,
magazines and books.
   Washington Post Co. said it earned $36.9 million, or $2.87 a
share, in the fourth quarter compared to $64.4 million, or $5.01 per
share, a year earlier.
   Fourth-quarter revenue rose 1.6 percent to $370.8 million from
$365 million a year earlier.
   The latest results included a $12.6 million charge related to a
previously-disclosed restructuring at Newsweek while the 1987
earnings included $23.5 million in one-time gains from the sale of
cellular telephone interests.
   For the year, the company earned $269.1 million, or $20.91 a
share, up 44.1 percent from $186.7 million, or $14.52 a share, a
year ago.
   Full-year revenue rose 4 percent to $1.37 billion from $1.32
billion in 1987.

</TEXT>
