<FIRST>u f AM-PanAm-Labor     02-08 0197</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pan Am-Labor,0204</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pan Am Transport Workers Ordered to Make Concessions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal arbitrator has ruled that the largest
union at Pan Am Corp. must give the financially ailing airline wage
and benefit concessions totaling $21 million, Pan Am said Wednesday.
   Pan Am had sought $27 million in concessions from the Transport
Workers Union, which represents about 5,900 mechanics, aircraft
service personnel and flight dispatchers at the nation's
eighth-largest airline.
   Last August, the Transport Workers membership rejected a new
cost-cutting contract that had been agreed to by its leadership and
Pan Am. The airline and the union later accepted federal arbitration
in their contract talks.
   Officials of the union were unavailable for comment late
Wednesday.
   ``We are very pleased that we've been able to achieve substantial
savings without conflict,'' said Pan Am spokesman Jeff Kriendler.
   He said the $21 million in mandated concessions include a wage
freeze and reductions in paid holidays.
   Pan Am has imposed $35 million in cuts on employees represented
by the Teamsters union under federal labor rules. The three unions
representing pilots, flight engineers and flight attendants have
agreed to cuts totaling about $300 million over three years.
</TEXT>
