<FILEID>AP-NR-02-08-89 1913EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Argentina-Economy     02-08 0372</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Argentina-Economy,0385</SECOND>
<HEAD>Austral Continues Slide Against Dollar</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Argentina's national currency fell
another 13 percent against the dollar Wednesday, continuing its
slide in the wake of the government's decision not to stabilize the
austral in foreign exchange.
   At the close of business Wednesday, the dollar fetched 27
australs, compared to 23.50 a day earlier and 17.59 last Friday.
   Some exchange houses were asking 29 to 30 australs to the dollar,
or simply bought and held dollars waiting for the price _ and thus
their profits _ to rise further.
   On Tuesday, when banks and foreign exchange houses opened
following a one-day, government-ordered holiday, the austral's value
slid by 25 percent against the dollar.
   The fluctuations follow the Central Bank's announcement Sunday
evening that it no longer would intervene in foreign exchange to
stabilize the austral, a goal toward which it spent at least $1
billion _ an estimated one-quarter of its liquid reserves _ during
the past several months.
   By making $20 million to $30 million a day available to banks and
foreign exchange houses, and by supporting interest rates on
financial instruments, the government encouraged Argentines to keep
money in australs and in accounts that could be tapped for lending
purposes.
   The goal also was to dampen inflation, which accelerated to 8.9
percent in January and was 387 percent for 1988, by holding down the
cost of imports and Argentine products generally denominated in
dollars, such as apartments, cars and airline tickets.
   The bubble burst last week when Argentines bought $486 million
offered by the Central Bank, even though interest rates on
certificates of deposit and austral-denominated financial
instruments were hiked to near 20 percent a month.
   The Central Bank was criticized by the opposition Peronist Party
as using foreign exchange reserves _ built up partly by not making
payments on Argentina's $58.6 billion foreign debt _ for the
political purpose of creating a favorable perception about the
economy.
   On Wednesday, as Argentines with dollars went shopping in search
of bargains before prices could be raised, Treasury Secretary Mario
Brodersohn denied rumors that Central Bank President Jose Luis
Machinea would resign.
   ``He hasn't resigned and he won't resign,'' Brodersohn said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
