<FILEID>AP-NR-02-08-89 2202EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Earns-Kodak     02-08 0327</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Kodak,0341</SECOND>
<HEAD>Posts 29 Percent Profit Gain for 4th-Qtr</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH PICHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastman Kodak Co. said Wednesday its
profit for the fourth quarter rose 29 percent from a year ago,
capping off a year of record sales and profit for the photographic
giant.
   The news came amid speculation that the company was planning to
announce job reductions. Two newspapers have received internal memos
from Kodak executives that indicate the job reduction plan will be
explained to workers in Thursday's edition of the employee newspaper.
   ``As a matter of policy, we do not comment on rumors. If there is
anything to report we would tell our employees first,'' said Kodak
spokesman Paul Allen.
   Kodak reported a profit of $312 million, or 96 cents a share, in
the fourth quarter, which ended Dec. 25, up from $242 million, or 75
cents a share, a year earlier.
   Fourth-quarter sales rose 29 percent to $4.54 billion from $3.52
billion.
   Kodak's profit for 1988 rose 19 percent to a record $1.4 billion,
or $4.31 a share, from $1.2 billion, or $3.52 a share, in 1987.
   Kodak sales rose 28 percent to a record $17.03 billion for the
year from $13.3 billion in 1987.
   ``It was a good quarter and a good year,'' said Charles Ryan, a
securities analyst with Merrill Lynch &amp; Co. in New York.
   Before the earnings report, Ryan had projected Kodak earnings for
1989 at $4.60 a share. He now expects $4.70 a share.
   The company posted 9 percent growth for the quarter and the year
in domestic sales in its imaging segment which includes photographic
film and paper and copier products. Ryan said that was more than
double recent growth.
   The results were boosted by the contribution of Sterling Drug
Co., which Kodak acquired in February 1988.
   But Allen said even if Sterling Drug's contributions were
excluded, the company would have established new sales and earnings
records for the year.
</TEXT>
