<FILEID>AP-NR-02-08-89 2143EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Pepperell     02-08 0350</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pepperell,0363</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pepperell Sets Deadline For Bids, Delays Shareholders Meeting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West Point-Pepperell Inc., the target of a $1.53
billion takeover bid, Wednesday set a deadline for new bids and
postponed a special shareholders meeting.
   The textile company, which is being sought by Farley Inc. for $52
a share, has announced it will accept bids matching or exceeding its
current stock price, which has risen above $55 per share in the last
week.
   West Point-based Pepperell set a Feb. 15 deadline for competing
offers, the same day Farley's bid is due to expire. Farley last week
raised its $48-per-share made in October.
   The shareholders meeting was postponed to March 2 from Feb. 25,
but the company gave no reason for the delay.
   The meeting was called by Farley and supporters in an attempt to
oust the current board of directors, which has repeatedly rejected
Farley's bid, and replace it with a favorable slate of directors.
   Farley spokesman Jack Albertine said the company agreed to the
delay, but he declined comment on Pepperell's bid deadline.
   Pepperell closed Wednesday at $55.37{, up 25 cents, in New York
Stock Exchange trading.
   ``What I think's going to happen is that there's going to be some
kind of negotiated settlement,'' said Kay Norwood, an analyst with
Johnson Lane Space Smith &amp; Co. Inc. in Charlotte, N.C. ``It looks
like some of the fight's gone out. We don't see any external,
spirited bidding.''
   Farley announced last week that the number of shares it had been
tendered dropped from 15.7 million to about 11 million. Even added
to its 2.9 million currently owned shares, or 9.8 percent, the
company still falls short of half of the outstanding shares.
   Pepperell spokeswoman Toni Cauble declined to say whether the
company has received any other bids.
   Pepperell, the nation's largest publicly traded textile company,
manufactures such brands as Martex towels, Lady Pepperell sheets and
Gold Toe socks. Farley controls Fruit of the Loom Inc., the nation's
largest underwear manufacturer, and Acme Boot Co. Inc., makers of
Acme and Dingo boots.
</TEXT>
