<DOCNO> AP890208-0312 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-08-89 1932EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Audi-Appeal     02-08 0631</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Audi-Appeal,0653</SECOND>
<HEAD>Audi Loses In Car-Owner's Appeal Of Product Liability Case Involving
5000s</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT WADE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state court ruled against Volkswagen of
America Inc. Wednesday in a major liability case, reinstating
damages awarded by a jury that found the company knowingly failed to
correct defects in the Audi 5000.
   The three-judge appeals panel reinstated a $100,000 punitive
award to Germaine Gibbs of Elizabeth, N.J., who was injured along
with her three children when an Audi 5000 smashed through their
apartment in 1983 and sent bricks raining down upon them. The car's
driver, Harold Horowitz of Elizabeth, told police the automobile
lunged forward suddenly.
   Ms. Gibbs' attorney, James Hely, said the ruling demonstrates
Audi's liability in the case, and may affect other cases pending
against the West German automaker and its U.S. subsidiaries.
   ``Because the truth comes out in this opinion about how they
covered up and how they made a correction that was obvious they had
to make, it really reflects terribly on the company and how they
handled this matter,'' Hely said.
   A civil jury last March decided Volkswagen was responsible for a
design problem that placed the accelerator and brake pedal too close
together. In addition to the $100,000 award, the jury awarded Ms.
Gibbs $14,000 in compensatory damages.
   But Superior Court Judge A. Donald McKenzie sided with company
attorneys and set aside the higher award, finding there was no proof
Volkswagen knew the car had problems and failed to correct them.
   The appeals court's 16-page decision reverses McKenzie.
   ``While the evidence to support punitive damages was not
overwhelming, we are satisfied that a jury could reasonably have
concluded that Volkswagen was guilty of deliberate acts of omissions
with knowledge of a high degree of probability of harm or reckless
indifference to the consequences,'' the court said.
   In January, Ms. Gibbs asked the Appellate Division of Superior
Court to reinstate the punitive award, while Volkswagen asked the
appeals court to also set aside a $14,000 award.
   The company said the appeals court opinion is directed only at
the lower court judge's discretionary powers.
   ``The appellate court apparently based its decision on the
feeling that the judge in the lower court had abused his discretion.
We disagree with that,'' said John Bennett, a spokesman for
Volkswagen's U.S. subsidiary in Troy, Mich.
   ``We feel the judge acted within his discretionary rights and we
are looking very carefully to see what additional remedies we might
have,'' he said.
   Volkswagen told the National Highway Traffic and Safety
Administration in 1983 that it would take corrective measures to
``prevent inadvertent activation of brake and gas pedals at the same
time,'' according to court papers Hely filed in arguing the case
last month.
   Internal Volkswagen documents and a government report conclude
the car would lunge when the accelerator and brake pedal were
pressed simultaneously, and the pedals were arranged close enough
that the accelerator often is applied when the driver tries to
brake, Hely said.
   The documents show Volkswagen knew as early as 1979 of the defect.
   Volkswagen declined to comment about the internal documents filed
by Hely, saying they were not properly introduced as evidence.
   Bennett stressed that the case did not involve unintended
acceleration, which involves the car lunging forward uncontrollably
when placed in gear.
   But auto industry analyst David Healy of Drexel Burnham Lambert
Inc. said the newest court ruling only adds to public relations
problems for Audi, which suffered declining sales because of an
unintended acceleration case it eventually won.
   ``The monthly sales numbers for Audis have been dismal since all
of the publicity around the unintended acceleration arose last
year,'' Healy said.
   He said Audi's U.S. sales were 60,000 cars in 1986, 41,000 cars
in 1987 and 23,000 cars in 1988.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890208-0313 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-08-89 1946EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Eastern 1stLd-Writethru   02-08 0560</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern, 1st Ld-Writethru,0577</SECOND>
<HEAD>Management, Workers Huddle</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs with judge issuing injunction; picks up 5th
graf, Matell said.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge on Wednesday rejected a request by
Eastern Airlines management to block members of the machinists union
from walking off the job in a dispute over mandatory overtime work.
   The ruling by U.S. District Judge C. Clyde Atkins followed
short-lived walkouts Tuesday and Wednesday by groups of
International Association of Machinist members. Wednesday's actions
came as management and union officials met to resolve the dispute.
   ``The federal court saw that there were two sides to this and
gave us the opportunity to continue on harmoniously and try to work
things out,'' said Charles Bryan, president of the union's Miami
local.
   Eastern said operations continued normally despite the
controversy, which boiled over Tuesday afternoon in a walkout by up
to 1,000 machinists at Miami International Airport.
   The job action lasted about three hours, and management personnel
replaced baggage handlers and other ground services workers. Two
other small actions occurred Wednesday morning.
   ``I consider it a victory for Eastern Airlines,'' said management
attorney David Ross after Atkins rejected his request for a
temporary injunction. ``The union has admitted in open court that
the work stoppages were illegal, and they have promised the federal
district judge that they will not do it again.''
   Union leaders said they did not call for the walkouts and said
they were spontaneous. Company spokesman Robin Matell blamed it on
``public posturing'' by the machinists, whose 16-month-old contract
dispute with management has a March 3 deadline for settlement.
   Matell said the meeting Wednesday continued discussions from
Tuesday on the suspensions for three days each of eight to 10
Machinists who refused to work overtime required by their contract.
The Machinists said the company failed to show a need for the extra
work.
   ``This is a decision management interprets, when there is a
need,'' Matell said.
   A union member said the strike was a spontaneous action from the
rank and file, crediting ``the pride of our workers'' with sparking
the action.
   ``The company demands from them they stay the overtime and they
refused to do it. They have to prove that they really need the
overtime and they can't do that,'' said Orlando Trujillo.
   ``Nobody has the right to require overtime in certain
conditions,'' said Ronald Orr, district general chairman of
Machinists' union.
   ``We feel that if airplanes are grounded and delayed, people have
to work the overtime. But if it's not grounded and delayed, the
person has the right not to work it,'' Orr said.
   Union sources said baggage handlers started Tuesday's walkout.
They would be particularly hard hit if Eastern imposes its final
contract offer, calling for $150 million in cuts, after the
federally imposed 30-day cooling-off period ends March 3.
   No other airports were affected by the action and no flights were
cancelled.
   Machinists locals around the country are voting this week on
whether to authorize a strike if the March 3 deadline passes. Union
officials expect overwhelming support for strike authorization.
   The Miami local's 4,000 members will vote Thursday. Mechanics
make up about half of the 8,500-member union, which includes more
than a quarter of all Eastern employees. The other members are
baggage handlers, ramp agents and other ground services workers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890208-0314 </DOCNO>
