<FILEID>AP-NR-02-08-89 2236EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Rockwell     02-08 0329</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rockwell,0344</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rockwell Rules Out Purchase Of Electronics Firm</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rockwell International Corp., maker
of the B-1B bomber, has decided against resuming negotiations to buy
AIL Systems Inc., maker of the bomber's electronic defense gear, the
company's top executive said Wednesday.
   However, Rockwell may consider acquisitions to expand its current
lines of aerospace, electronics, automotive and industrial products,
Donald Beall, chairman and chief executive officer, said at the
annual shareholders meeting.
   In January, Rockwell ended negotiations with Cleveland-based
Eaton Corp. to buy AIL, a Deer Park, N.Y., company that makes the
electronic countermeasures equipment for the supersonic Air Force
bomber.
   At the time, the companies said the decision was made because
Eaton hadn't concluded a definitive contract with the Air Force for
follow-up work on the system, called the ALQ-161.
   The system is intended to counteract enemy radar and other
electronic gear. The Air Force says the bomber is fully operational,
but congressional critics maintain the ALQ-161 isn't performing up
to expectations.
   Beall told reporters that Rockwell wouldn't resume negotiations
to buy AIL, but would continue to work with the smaller company on
the electronic countermeasures system.
   Beall didn't say if the Pittsburgh-based company had specific
acquisition targets.
   ``We would expect any acquisitions to be smaller businesses that
offer product line and or geographic expansion potential,'' he said.
   Beall said he expects the company's 1989 profit to exceed that in
1988, when Rockwell earned $811.9 million on sales of $11.9 billion.
   One reason, he said, is diversification into private-sector
businesses. Government contracts, including NASA business, declined
to 47 percent of Rockwell's business in 1988, from 58 percent in
1987 and 64 percent in 1983.
   The last of 100 B-1B bombers was delivered to the Air Force in
April 1988, and all that remains of the program is production of
spare parts.
   Rockwell also is the prime contractor on the Space Shuttle and
works on the Strategic Defense Initiative, or ``Star Wars,'' among
other programs.
</TEXT>
