<FILEID>AP-NR-02-08-89 2308EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Hasbro     02-08 0182</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Hasbro,0189</SECOND>
<HEAD>Toymaker's Earnings Jump More Than 50 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PAWTUCKET, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hasbro Inc.'s 1988 profit jumped more than
50 percent over the previous year, thanks to an increase in revenues
and declines in several expense categories, the toymaker said
Wednesday.
   For the three months ended Dec. 25, the Pawtucket-based company
earned $21.1 million, or 36 cents a share, on revenues of $394.9
million, compared with profit of $6.7 million, or 11 cents a share,
on revenues of $378.4 million for the same period a year earlier.
   Hasbro's total 1988 earnings were $72.4 million, or $1.24 per
share, on revenues of $1.36 billion, compared with a profit of $48.2
million, or 82 cents a share, on revenues of $1.35 billion in 1987.
   The improved earnings came despite a $16.4 million pre-tax loss
from the company's aborted attempt to develop a video game system,
Chairman Stephen Hassenfeld said in a statement.
   ``Our results for both the year and the quarter were consistent
with previous estimates,'' Hassenfeld said. ``The earnings growth
came from both the international and domestic segments of our
business.''
</TEXT>
